<FIRST>r p PM-ELN--TV     11-07 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ELN--TV,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Reports on Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two television networks are planning brief
special reports tonight on today's state and local elections while
a third says it will cover the results in its regular news programs.
   ABC plans to interrupt its programming with a brief special
report when results on major races become available, then give more
coverage in its half-hour ``Nightline'' show at 11:30 p.m. EST,
according to spokeswoman Elise Adde.
   NBC will have a 15-minute special report, ``Decision '89,'' at
11:30 p.m. EST, said spokeswoman Katherine McQuay.
   CBS plans to report on the elections in its regular news
broadcasts, including up to an hour of coverage on ``Nightwatch,''
airing at 1:35 a.m. EST Wednesday in some areas, 2 a.m. in others.
   On cable television, Cable News Network will have election
reports throughout the night, said spokesman Steve Haworth.
   Major contests include races for governor in Virginia and New
Jersey and for mayor in New York City.
</TEXT>
