<FIRST>r a AM-General-Bribery     11-07 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-General-Bribery,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dominican Republic General Arrested in Bribery Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general from the Dominican Republic was jailed
Monday for allegedly accepting bribes to release a drug plane
impounded in his homeland.
   Gen. Joaquin Pou, 54, who U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said had
identified himself at different times as either an active or
retired general, was ordered held without bond during an appearance
Monday before a U.S. magistrate.
   He was taken into custody when he arrived at a Miami airport,
said Lehtinen.
   ``All I can tell you he was arrested Sunday,'' Lehtinen said.
``He came to Miami in furtherance of the conspiracy.''
   Pou, who had close contacts with other Dominican generals and
aviation officials, allegedly received about $20,000 to release a
confiscated plane, according to federal authorities.
   Also arrested for violating the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act
was Jose F. Guasch, 43, a Miami-based aide to the general, who was
granted a $250,000 bond Monday. A third defendant, pilot Robert
Neil Gurin, was expected to turn himself in Tuesday, the U.S.
attorney's office said.
   Lehtinen, saying the investigation was continuing, refused to
reveal many details of the case, but authorities released an
affidavit by U.S. Customs Agent Gary Lang.
   Lang said in the affidavit that in February Customs and the FBI
began investigating ``allegations of the bribery of high-ranking
military officials of the Dominican Republic by Robert Gurin ... to
assure the release of aircraft seized by the Dominican Republic for
narcotics smuggling.''
   Gurin was also involved with officials in Jamaica, Haiti, and
the Bahamas, the affidavit said.
   Informants told Lang that Gurin, who owns AEA Aircraft Recovery,
was aided by Thomas Martin, manager of the international field
office of the Federal Aviation Administration in Miami, the
affidavit said.
   At one point, Martin was taped by agents as saying ``my darkest
dream is being picked up and put in a ... jail right here in
Miami.''
   Martin was not indicted, and FAA spokesman Roger Myers said the
agency had only just learned of the case. Lehtinen would say only
that the investigation was continuing.
   Through informants and taped phone calls, Customs learned that
Gurin was trying to recover a Rockwell Aerocommander 690 B seized
in the Dominican Republic.
   Gurin at one point said he paid $50,000 to get another plane
released in that country.
   On the tapes, Gurin also said a Miami attorney, Alfredo Duran,
was channeling the money to generals in the Dominican military
through an escrow account. Duran has not been charged in the case,
and Lehtinen refused to discuss him further.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
