<FIRST>r a PM-Names     11-07 0910</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0954</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Anthony Quinn withdrew from a
production of ``A Walk in the Woods'' after experiencing chest
pains, organizers said.
   ``It became clear he could not handle the show,'' said
co-producer Barry Weisler. ``He ... won't be permitted to travel
until he is out of pain and the doctor gives his approval.''
   Quinn's withdrawal Saturday forced cancellation of previews
scheduled for Sunday, today and Wednesday at Syracuse Stage.
   Stage officials said Monday the 74-year-old actor was under the
care of his personal physician in New York City. They said there
was no diagnosis.
   Director Arthur Storch said Quinn was in pain early last week.
   ``We were rehearsing the scene in which the Soviet diplomat has
an angina attack and Tony said, `I know what that is. I have it.'
And we talked about it,'' Storch said.
   Quinn was to portray the diplomat in the play, which is about
the friendship struck between Soviet and U.S. arms negotiators.
   Opening night is still set for Friday, but Quinn has been
replaced by Ben Hammer. The show also stars Nicholas Hormann.
   A planned tour may be scuttled, Storch said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Duchess of York ended a five-day visit to
Texas with a visit to an inner-city school, where she took part in
a day filled with anti-drug messages.
   The 30-year-old former Sarah Ferguson also was serenaded by more
than 600 pupils at Blackshear Elementary School.
   The duchess, who is married to Britain's Prince Andrew, came to
Houston on Thursday at the invitation of the Houston Grand Opera,
which is saluting 300 years of British opera.
   At the school, she participated in an anti-drug play and handed
over autographed copies of her two children books about a
helicopter named ``Budgie.'' The students gave her a book they had
written and made her feel like royalty with a playground
performance.
   ``Your Royal Highness, the Duchess of York, from the boys and
girls of Blackshear School, may I present to you these flowers and
ask for your permission to sing?'' shouted 8-year-old Jermaine
Thibodeaux, who gave the duchess a bouquet of yellow roses.
   The duchess gave her the go-ahead, and the students sang ``Deep
in the Heart of Texas,'' ``Yankee Doodle Dandy,'' ``We are the
World,'' and an anti-drug song.
   Later Monday, she left on a flight to New York, where she was to
meet with her publisher, Simon &amp; Schuster.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Alaska Southeast has set
its sights high for a speaker at next spring's commencement: Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   ``My feeling is there can be no way to find out unless you do
ask,'' said Professor Wallace Olson, who suggested the invitation.
   Chancellor Marshall Lind said Monday he discussed the invitation
with Yuri Dubinin, the Soviet ambassador to the United States,
during Dubinin's recent Juneau visit.
   Lind said he was told the invitation is being considered in
Moscow.
   A response is not expected until December. The commencement is
scheduled May 4 in Juneau.
   ``We feel that he would be a very appropriate speaker for us in
view of all the things that are taking place between Alaska and the
Soviet Union,'' Lind said.
   Olson said his idea was inspired by Gorbachev's role in
permitting visa-free travel between the Soviet Union and Alaska for
the region's natives.
   If Gorbachev is unable to speak in person, the university is
hoping for the next best thing _ a speech broadcast by satellite or
videotape.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engelbert Humperdinck will appeal a judge's
dismissal of his $50 million lawsuit against The National Enquirer
for its report that the mother of the singer's daughter fears he
had the AIDS virus.
   Robert Rotstein, an attorney for the singer, said Monday the
U.S. District Court lawsuit was dismissed last week but Humperdinck
would appeal.
   Humperdinck has tested negative for the virus, Rotstein said.
   The Enquirer stood behind the article, which it said was based
on a court filing and was thereby not libelous.
   ``We feel vindicated by the judge's verdict,'' said Mike Walker,
an editor with the Florida-based tabloid.
   Kathy Jetter filed papers in New York City's Family Court
demanding that Humperdinck, 53, provide for the financial future of
her 12-year-old daughter, ruled by a court to be his daughter.
   Humperdinck's lawsuit said the woman's claims about the
entertainer were false and have been dismissed by the New York
court. Rotstein said the Los Angeles court's decision was based on
an overly broad reading of libel law.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jaclyn Smith, one of the original
``Charlie's Angels'' TV sleuths who moved on to serious roles in
such dramas as ``Windmills of the Gods,'' now has a star on the
Hollywood Walk of Fame.
   More than 200 fans and friends, including actors Mel Ferrer and
Ralph Bellamy, cheered during Monday's unveiling of the sidewalk
star, the 1,903rd dedicated along Hollywood Boulevard and Vine
Street.
   Universal Studios sponsored the star and paid the $3,500 cost.
   In 1976, she starred with Farrah Fawcett and Kate Jackson in
``Charlie's Angels.'' Four years later, she played the title role
in ABC's ``Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy.'' In recent years, she has
appeared in ``Rage of Angels,'' ``Florence Nightingale,''
``Sentimental Journey,'' ``The Bourne Identity'' and ``Settle the
Score.''
   Miss Smith returns to series television this fall in the new
two-hour ABC-TV series ``Christine Cromwell,'' part of ``The ABC
Saturday Mystery'' lineup.
</TEXT>
