<FIRST>r a PM-USATodayTV     11-07 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USA Today TV,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Producer Settles Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Bellows, the former managing editor of
``USA Today on TV,'' has settled his $1.8 million lawsuit against
the company that makes the syndicated series. He called the
agreement ``an amicable settlement.''
   Bellows' attorney, Michael Zweig, and M.S. ``Bud'' Rukeyser, a
spokesman for the producers GTG East, said terms of the settlement
could not be revealed. The company is the New York branch of GTG
Entertainment, which is based in Culver City, Calif., and is a
co-venture of former NBC chairman Grant Tinker and the Gannett Co.
   Bellows filed his lawsuit in U.S. District Court here on Oct. 2.
He was the second of four senior executives that have run GTG's
show since it premiered in September 1988 as ``USA Today: The
Television Show.''
   Bellows was hired under a two-year contract paying him $275,000
a year. He took over the series in October 1988 and left in March
to help develop a new program for GTG. His lawsuit alleged he was
fired without cause or warning.
   Bellows, 66, is a former newspaperman who also has worked at ABC
News and has been executive producer of the syndicated
``Entertainment Tonight'' series. He said in an interview he hasn't
decided what he'll do next.
   However, he said Monday, he plans to move back to Los Angeles
next summer. He has lived in New York since 1983.
</TEXT>
