<HEAD>Three Dead, Two Wounded in Ga. Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 to ADD locator, CORRECT spelling of Frederick's
wife's name to Gwendolyn, sted Gwyn. SUBS last 4 grafs, `Police tried ...,'
with 5 grafs to UPDATE with niece's name, quote from sheriff, CORRECT that
children were two daughters, sted daughter and son. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDERSONVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man shot his mother and wife to
death Monday, wounded his sister and a niece, then killed himself,
a state police spokesman said.
   The rampage occurred at the home of Polly Mae Frederick, mother
of Tony Frederick, in the southwest Georgia city, said Georgia
Bureau of Investigation spokesman John Bankhead.
   Frederick, 28, of Sumter County and his 20-year-old wife,
Gwendolyn, had gone to the house to do laundry Monday afternoon,
Bankhead said.
   An argument occurred around 1:30 p.m., and Frederick shot the
two women in the head, killing both, the spokesman said.
   Frederick's 33-year-old sister, Jackie, ran outside to lead
their brother, LeRoy, who is blind, to safety. But Frederick
followed them outside and shot his sister in the head.
   LeRoy Frederick ran to Georgia 271, and got the attention of a
truck driver, who called police. Sumter County sheriff's deputies,
the GBI and state police rushed to the scene.
   Police tried to talk Frederick out, but eventually fired a
tear-gas canister into the house. Officers found him dead and a
niece, Tammy Watts, hiding under a bed with a gunshot wound in her
side, Bankhead said.
   Officers found Ms. Watts' two daughters, aged 4 and 2, locked
inside a car parked near the house, where they apparently fled when
the shooting began, the spokesman said.
   Jackie Frederick underwent surgery at Columbus Medical Center,
and was in critical condition Monday night.
   Ms. Watts was in stable condition at Sumter Regional Hospital in
Americus.
   ``I was shocked,'' said Sumter County Sheriff Randy Howard. ``He
wiped his family out. I just don't understand. We may never know
why it happened.''
</TEXT>
