<FIRST>r a AM-DriftNets 1stLd-Writethru a0591 11-07 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drift Nets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0591,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Urge Reduction of Drift Net Fishing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs to ADD U.N. action. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Western states and the province of British
Columbia on Monday issued a proclamation urging their federal
governments to take action to reduce drift net fishing in the North
Pacific.
   The proclamation was announced at a news conference preceding
the International North Pacific Fisheries Commission meeting this
week in Seattle.
   The proclamation seeks reductions in Japanese high-seas salmon
fisheries to reduce the impact of squid fleets on salmon, albacore
tuna, seabirds and marine mammals.
   The proclamation also wants Canada, the United States, the
Soviet Union and Japan to establish a new convention in the ocean
region aimed at protecting salmon in international waters.
   It would also form a research organization among the nations.
   The states are Alaska, Washington, Oregon, Idaho, California and
Hawaii.
   Drift nets are small, monofilament nets that are draggd through
the water and catch everything they come in contact with. About 800
fishing vessels from Japan, Korea and Taiwan use the nets in the
Pacific Ocean. On any given day, the drift net fleet can cover
30,000 miles of ocean.
   The Alaska Department of Fisheries estimates that the annual
damage to fisheries on the high seas by drift net boats at about
$100 million _ including the effects on salmon, albacore tuna and
other Pacific fisheries.
   Also Monday, the United States joined South Pacific nations at
the United Nations in denouncing driftnet fishing as ``potentially
devastating technology'' that massacres marine mammals, sea birds
and unwanted fish.
   A U.S. delegate, Ambassador Jonathan Moore, told the General
Assembly's Second Committee, which deals with the environment and
other social affairs, that the United States is joining the Pacific
and other nations in a resolution banning the huge drift nets.
   Under the General Assembly resolution, drift-net fishing would
be abolished immediately in the South Pacific, and phased out
worldwide by June 30, 1992.
   Moore said the United States had no objection to developing
nations using small drift nets that allow fish multiply and renew
the stocks, but was opposed to the vast ``pelagic'' driftnets.
   The resolution is cosponsored by New Zealand, Australia, Canada,
Fiji, Mauritania, Papua New Guinea, the Solomon Islands, Vanuatu,
Zaire, Colombia and Sweden.
   It does not single out any nation for criticism, but expresses
concern of the indiscriminate nature of driftnet fishing and sets
out proposals for international management and the eventual ban of
driftnet use.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
