<FIRST>r a AM-SacramentoUnion 1stLd-Writethru a0420 11-07 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sacramento Union, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0420,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules for Guild on Workers, Pay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The newspaper ...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
comment by one of four fired employees; picks up 5th graf, ```We believe
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has upheld
government rulings that the Sacramento Union acted improperly in
cutting salaries by 15 percent in 1986 and firing four employees
who criticized the newspaper in a letter to advertisers.
   The two 3-0 rulings by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
which were made public Monday, were victories for The Newspaper
Guild in disputes stemming from negotiations with the newspaper in
1986.
   An agreement was recently announced to sell the newspaper to a
group headed by Sacramento developers Daniel Benvenuti and David
Kassis.
   Bob Saucerman, one of the four employees fired over the letter,
said he expected the decisions and felt vindicated.
   ``I'm very pleased. I hope the employer would now swiftly
implement the court's order and give everybody their 15 percent,''
said Saucerman, who was a retail advertising salesman.
   But Sacramento Union President Jack Bates said the newspaper
will appeal both rulings to the U.S. Supreme Court. Bates said 170
to 180 employees were affected.
   ``We believe very strongly that we were at impasse'' in contract
negotiations and had the right to implement the pay cut, Bates
said. ``We also believe very strongly that we had the right to fire
those (four) people on the basis of their actions.''
   The Guild, representing editorial, circulation, business,
advertising and maintenance employees, negotiated with the
newspaper in 1986 on a contract to replace the one that was to
expire that May.
   The talks continued beyond May, but in early August 1986 the
newspaper declared an impasse and put its last offer into effect,
including an across-the-board 15 percent pay cut and elimination of
a longstanding provision requiring all employees to join the Guild.
   The union denied that negotiations were at an impasse, as
required for an employer to implement its final contract offer. A
hearing officer ruled in the newspaper's favor but was overruled by
the National Labor Relations Board, whose decision was upheld by
the appeals court.
   The court said there was evidence to support the NLRB's
conclusion that no real bargaining had taken place on the key issue
of union security when the talks were suspended.
   When the security issue was raised, ``the company put the matter
off to a later time and then declared an impasse before any real
discussion took place,'' the court said. It rejected the
newspaper's argument that the Guild had refused to discuss the
issue.
   The court upheld the NLRB's order requiring the newspaper to
reinstate the former contract, which included the higher pay level
and the union membership requirement.
   The unsigned ruling was issued by Judges Otto Skopil, Betty
Fletcher and Ferdinand Fernandez.
   The other ruling involved a letter written by four members of
the Guild's negotiating committee to 50 of the newspaper's
advertisers in October 1987.
   The letter described the employees' efforts to get a contract,
mentioned the pay cut, and declared that the paper was ``speeding
downhill,'' with circulation plummeting and good staffers leaving.
The advertisers were urged to contact executives of the newspaper.
   The court said the four employees _ Bob Saucerman, Ana Sandoval,
Georgia Canfield and Sue Harper _ were fired two weeks later. Bates
accused them of disloyalty and said the letter contained falsehoods
that disrupted the newspaper's relationship with advertisers, the
court said.
   In an opinion by Fletcher, the court upheld the NLRB's decision
that the letter was within the employees' rights of collective
bargaining and was not an improper act of disloyalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
