<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     11-07 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Ross and Evelyn Skinner are proving that
love and marriage really do go together like a horse and carriage.
   Ross, 58, who runs a horse-drawn carriage business in the
Waikiki tourist area, knew Ms. Skinner was the woman for him the
moment the 60-year-old Tennessee woman got into his carriage while
vacationing with her father and stepmother recently.
   ``The first thing the driver said to me was, `Would you like to
go for a cruise, go out to dinner or get married?''' Ms. Skinner
recalled. ``Well, it was just foolishness so I said, `I'd rather
get married.'''
   ``The moment I spotted her beautiful brown eyes, I knew that
this is it,'' Ross said. ``I've waited 18 years for a woman like
her. I've prayed to the Lord for it and he finally sent me an
angel.''
   It was a whirlwind romance after that first carriage ride. After
a breakfast date the next day, Ross asked Ms. Skinner's father for
her hand.
   ``My father said: `Well, she's 60 years old, she ought to be
able to make up her own mind,''' said Ms. Skinner, a registered
nurse.
   The date hasn't been set, but the wedding, the second for each,
will be as soon as possible.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Good drivers are getting tickets these days _
to the movies.
   Officers on the city's west side are handing out movie passes to
courteous and careful drivers.
   ``There's so many citations given out to violators who abuse the
law, the LAPD thought it would be nice to reward the good drivers
in our city for a change,'' said Officer Chuck Lovold of the Los
Angeles Police Department's West Traffic Division.
   The program will last through the end of the year, courtesy of a
movie studio and theater chain that donated the passes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tired of scrounging under the car
seat for change to drop in the parking meter? This city is
considering introducing the latest in convenience for the motorist
on the go: the personal parking meter.
   If the City Commission goes along with the proposal today,
drivers would be offered pocket computer-sized devices that
automatically keep track of parking time in metered zones. The
``Parkulators'' would sell for $50, and be dumped in the trash when
$50 worth of curb time is used up.
   ``It's your own personal parking meter,'' said Tom McCormick,
city parking manager. ``We get complaints constantly: `If I only
had enough change on me or had some way to prepay the meter, I
wouldn't have gotten this ticket.' Now they won't have that
excuse.''
   Motorists would be responsible for turning the units on and
punching in the maximum time allowed at whatever meter they've
pulled up to. If they don't, or if they fail to come back and punch
in another deposit when the time's up, McCormick said, they'll get
tickets just like an old-fashioned meter scofflaw.
</TEXT>
