<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     11-07 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Committee Chairman Urge Defeat of Cason</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairmen of two Senate committees that
oversee natural resources issues are urging their colleagues to
reject James Cason as assistant secretary of agriculture.
   Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., who is chairman of the Senate
Energy and Natural Resources Committee, and Sen. Patrick Leahy,
D-Vt., chairman of the Agriculture Committee, are sending a letter
to all senators, saying Cason ``is neither qualified nor suitable''
for the job.
   Cason, 35, has been nominated to head the Agriculture
Department's forest and conservation programs.
   He has drawn fire for his record as a high-ranking official
during the Reagan administration at the Interior Department, where
critics contend he put private development interests ahead of
environmental concerns.
   ``A review of Mr. Cason's education and employment history
indicates that he came to the Department of the Interior with
little, if any, by the way of background or qualifications for the
job,'' said the letter, dated Nov. 3.
   ``Moreover, Mr. Cason's record indicates a reluctance to rely on
the professional expertise available to him at the Department of
the Interior,'' it says.
   Leahy opposed Cason during committee hearings, saying he
repeatedly shrugged aside public interests in decisions on how to
use public lands.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, who is widely admired on
Capitol Hill, has sought to assure senators that he sets
environmental policy at the department and Cason would be taking
orders from him.
   But Johnston and Leahy cited testimony critical of Cason from
Max Peterson, who retired recently as chief of the forest service
after 38 years with the agency and currently holds the title chief
emeritus.
   ``In my judgment, he (Cason) clearly is not qualified,'' the
senators quote Peterson as saying.
   ``The opposition to Mr. Cason's nomination is broad and deep,
and ranges across political and ideological viewpoints,'' said
Leahy and Johnston. ``It is opposition based on the recognition
that we need appointees who are dedicated to protecting the public
trust, whatever their party.''
   The nomination was approved by the Agriculture Committee on a
12-7 vote, but full Senate action was been put on hold because of
opposition to the appointment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal subsidies would be available to cities
that start tree-planting programs if a bill passed by the House
becomes law.
   The legislation, known as the urban and community forestry act,
was approved on voice vote Monday and now goes to the Senate.
   It directs the Agriculture Department to start a matching grants
program that would provide cash, services or in-kind contributions
for up to 50 percent of the cost of any tree-planting program.
   The legislation addresses ``an important concern in our country
about what can be done to reforest our nation's cities, to cool
down and green up our urban areas,'' said Rep. Jim Jontz, D-Ind.,
who authored the bill.
   Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash., said that for every tree being
planted in cities, four are being lost. He advocated passage of the
bill, saying it would help clean the air and battle against global
warming.
   The measure also:
   _Directs the Agriculture Department to start an educational and
technical assistance program in cooperation with state foresters
and state extension agents.
   _Establishes a 15-member National Urban and Community Forestry
Advisory Council to help develop criteria for the cost share
program and develop a national urban and community forestry plan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee this week will begin a
series of four hearings on controversies surrounding the use of
national forests.
   Rep. Harold Volkmer, D-Mo., is planning to take testimony
Thursday from administration officials on the status of forest land
and resource management plans.
   ``Our National forests supply a vast array of products and
opportunities, from timber and minerals to recreation for millions
of Americans,'' said Volkmer, chairman of the House Agriculture
subcommittee on forests, family farms and energy.
   ``Conflicts over the use of resources in the national forests
are increasing in frequency and severity, and we need to explore
alternatives for addressing some of these tough issues,'' he said.
   A hearing is scheduled for Nov. 15 on timber harvesting systems;
Nov. 21 on timber sale economics and the timber sale information
reporting system; and Nov. 29 on issues associated with timber
supply and sustained yield.
</TEXT>
