<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MapFlap     11-07 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Map Flap,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man's Persistence Changes Boundaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took Martin Miller seven years, but he's
finally convinced the CIA and the State Department to change their
maps of Israel and Jordan to reflect historical fact and U.S.
policy.
   It's a story about a persistent advocate, a cumbersome
bureaucracy and the intractable Israeli-Arab conflict.
   Miller, a retired Treasury Department official, began his
crusade in 1981 when he noticed that a government-published map
book showed the West Bank of the Jordan River as part of Jordan.
   This was despite the fact that the United States and most of the
rest of the world have never recognized Jordan's 1950 annexation of
the 2,200-square-mile territory.
   On the official U.S. maps published by the Central Intelligence
Agency, the Israeli-Jordanian border was drawn along the 1949
armistice line, which defined Israel's physical borders until the
1967 war. The maps did not reflect Israel's capture of the West
Bank in that war and the new cease-fire lines created as a result.
   ``It wasn't right. It just didn't reflect reality,'' said Miller.
   He undertook his campaign in a methodical way, buying a computer
and poring over history books and archive documents, far from the
controversy generated by every wrinkle of the Arab-Israeli dispute.
   The first step was a letter to then-Secretary of State Alexander
Haig. The retired general referred Miller's letter to a
little-known State Department entity called the Office of the
Geographer.
   The office maps official U.S. policy on sovereignty issues for
internal State Department publications, and acts as an advisory and
arbitration board for other government agencies that issue maps.
   Miller began corresponding with the geographer, who issued a
directive in 1982 ordering cartographers to stop showing the West
Bank as anyone's territory.
   But still, the public maps were not changed.
   Miller also enlisted his congressman's help, wrote opinion
pieces and editorial letters, but the maps were still wrong.
   Finally, Miller asked to see Haig's successor at the State
Department, George Shultz, whom he had known when Shultz was
Treasury secretary. ``That was very exciting,'' Miller said. He
left Shultz with 92 documents buttressing his argument.
   More conversations with administration officials and letters
followed.
   In 1984, Miller read an opinion piece in The Washington Post by
former deputy CIA chief Robert Gates, who said the agency was
emphasizing accuracy and objectivity in its assessments.
   Miller decided to call Gates, talking his way past skeptical
aides and secretaries until he got through.
   ``I told him his people were not adhering to his standards,''
Miller said. Two days later, on Jan. 2, 1985, he was summoned to a
meeting with two CIA officials.
   They promised the maps would be changed, but a year later
nothing had been done, Miller said.
   Miller called again _ and this time a promise was fulfilled. The
map of Jordan was changed in 1986. It took until January 1989 to
change the Israel map.
   The new maps show the 1967 cease-fire line between Israel and
Jordan, with the West Bank designated as two cultural regions _
Judea and Samaria. The two biblical names are also used by Israeli
nationalists to describe the region.
   Miller's efforts also bore fruit outside government circles when
the Encyclopedia Britannica changed its maps, he said.
   The State Department is reluctant to give all the credit to
Miller for the changes, but concedes his campaign influenced the
decision. ``He was very, very active, and believed in his cause,''
said one official familiar with the case.
   Perhaps the best tribute to Miller's determination was contained
in a letter from Shultz earlier this year, soon after the Israel
maps were changed.
   ``Dear Marty,'' wrote the man who labored in vain for six years
to bring about Israeli-Arab peace talks. ``I'm glad you kept at it
and accomplished something that is of genuine and lasting
significance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-07 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall, Dollar Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mimicking an overnight decline in New York, share
prices fell on a broad front today on the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
while the dollar firmed against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the stock market's key
indicator, fell 163.54 points, or 0.46 percent, to close at
35,470.26. It lost 60.86 points Monday.
   The overnight decline in New York, where the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 major issues posted its third-largest
single-day decline this year of 47.34 points, sparked a broad round
of selling, driving the Nikkei down 301.22 points in the first 15
minutes of trading.
   Dealers said investors in both markets were reacting with
disappointment over fading prospects for an interest-rate cut
following Friday's release of U.S. jobless figures, which showed
the U.S. unemployment rate unchanged from a month earlier at 5.3
percent.
   A quarterly auction of U.S. Treasury securities to begin today
in the United States also kept some participants on the sidelines,
they said.
   The Nikkei recovered some of its early losses later in the day
as investors bought popular issues such as petroleum and mining
shares as well as some incentive-backed issues, dealers said.
   A estimated 750 million shares changed hands in moderately
active trading, up from 611 million shares Monday.
   In currency trading, the dollar closed at 143.63 yen, up 0.18
yen from Monday's close of 143.45 yen. It opened at 143.85 yen and
ranged between 143.53-144.04. The dollar closed at 143.88 yen in
New York overnight.
   The dollar surged against the yen in early trading following an
upswing in New York overnight, said a trader with the Bank of
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Many investors bought the dollar in early trading,'' he said,
``but their buying incentive was not strong enough to keep pushing
the dollar beyond the 144-yen line.''
   Demand for the dollar due to today's Treasury auction bolstered
the dollar later in the day as it came under selling pressure from
security houses and life insurance companies, said Kaneo Ogino, a
trader at Goldman Sachs in Tokyo.
   ``Rumors of an imminent rate hike by the Bank of Japan are
putting downward pressure on the dollar,'' Ogino said.
   Traders said the dollar-yen rate is unlikely to move much ahead
of the release of the U.S. wholesale price index for October on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
