<FIRST>r a PM-PakistaniPlot     11-07 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistani Plot,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Suspect Testifies He Plotted to Kill Pakistan's Zia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man prosecutors say is a major
heroin trafficker testified he paid another accused drug dealer in
a plot to assassinate Pakistan's former leader, who died in a
mysterious plane crash.
   Federal prosecutors allege that Mushtaq Malik, a 41-year-old
Pakistani on trial on charges of conspiracy and importation of
heroin, arranged for Samir N. Houchaimi of Amman, Jordan, to bring
$10 million in heroin to the United States for resale.
   Houchaimi was arrested in Springfield with heroin nearly two
years ago, authorities said.
   Prosecutors say Malik is known as ``The Black Prince,'' and they
allege he is one of the world's biggest heroin traffickers.
   Malik testified Monday in U.S. District Court that he had hired
Houchaimi to kill Pakistani President Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
Malik did not make clear whether the assassination plot he said he
was involved in had anything to do with the crash.
   Malik, a self-described Pakistani prince, said Houchaimi was a
former colonel in the Jordanian army.
   ``I don't know anything about money for heroin in America,''
Malik said.
   Malik was summoned to testify by his attorney Stephen Ferrarone.
   He was scheduled for cross-examination today by Assistant U.S.
Attorney Kevin O'Regan.
   Malik testified he advanced Houchaimi $1 million on behalf of
superiors in the left-leaning Pakistan People's Party _ whose
current leader is Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto _ to secure
personnel and equipment for the assasination.
   The 51-year-old Houchaimi testified last week that he had been
given 2 kilograms of heroin in Nicosia, Cyprus, to sell in the
United States for Malik. Houchaimi was arrested with a nylon
handbag filled with the heroin on Feb. 6, 1988, near a downtown bus
terminal, authorities said.
   Six months later, on Aug. 17, 1988, Zia died in a plane crash
that also killed 29 other people, including U.S. Ambassador Arnold
Raphel.
   After Houchaimi was arrested, he arranged a meeting in Rio de
Janiero, Brazil, between Malik and a ``Mr. Costa,'' the alias for
undercover U.S. drug agent William J. Powers, according to the
Springfield Union-News.
   Malik and the agent met in March 1988, supposedly to fly to
Costa Rica together, but Malik was arrested and returned to the
United States where he has been held in custody, the newspaper
reported.
   Malik said he had lost face among his compatriots because he
recommended a man who failed to carry out his task in the plot.
   ``I don't know anything about money for heroin in America,''
Malik testified. ``I wanted to have that money back for my people
and save my face.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Traficant-Flight103     11-07 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Traficant-Flight 103,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Provides Part of Promised Report on Flight 103 Insurance
Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. James Traficant says part of an insurance
investigator's report on ill-fated Pan Am Flight 103 shows the
United States was warned an hour before takeoff about a possible
bomb.
   The plane blew up last December over Lockerbie, Scotland,
killing 259 people on the jumbo jet and 11 on the ground. The
airline has been sued for more than $300 million.
   Traficant, D-Ohio, said he has a report indicating the CIA got a
warning from West German intelligence about a suspicious suitcase
on the plane.
   The CIA termed the report ``nonsense,'' and administration
officials said the United States was not warned about a Flight 103
bomb by any foreign intelligence agency.
   On Monday, Traficant passed out five pages from what he said was
a 27-page report prepared for Pan Am's insurance company.
   The document says a West German agent watching baggage handlers
singled out one suspicious suitcase and reported ``something was
very wrong.''
   West German intelligence passed on the concern to a CIA unit in
Frankfurt, which relayed it to an unidentified ``control,'' says
the excerpt.
   ``Control replied: `Don't worry about it, don't stop it, let it
go,''' the excerpt says.
   A former CIA employee, Victor Marchetti, joined Traficant at the
Capitol Hill news conference to identify himself as the person who
gave the congressman the document. Marchetti said he was not
involved in writing the report but believes ``it is essentially
accurate.''
   ``I know the intelligence officers who prepared this report,''
said Marchetti, who retired from the agency in 1969 and wrote a
book critical of the CIA.
   CIA spokesman Mark Mansfield, who last week called the report
``nonsense,'' said Monday, ``It's still nonsense.''
   ``My gut instinct is, the CIA is very defensive and that they
know a hell of a lot more than they're telling us,'' said
Traficant. ``I think that there are questions that now have to be
answered.''
   Traficant said the full report shows connections between the
bombing, drug-running and hostage rescue efforts.
   Pan Am already has subpoenaed documents relating to one of the
people mentioned prominently in the report: Monzer Al-Kassar, who
is characterized as having connections with both the terrorist
bombers and the CIA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
