<FIRST>r w PM-Manley     11-07 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manley,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamaican Leader Renews Campaign for Anti-Drug Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jamaican Prime Minister Michael Manley admits
his dream of a United Nations strike force to combat drug cartel
terrorism lacks necessary political support, but he says he will
keep up his crusade for the idea.
   Manley told the Senate Judiciary Committee on Monday that a
Western hemisphere training center for agents and intelligence
could serve as an alternative _ but only an international strike
force would really do the job.
   ``It isn't a regional problem, it's an international problem,''
Manley said in pitching for an eight-point program aimed at
fighting the narcotics scourge.
   He said the Organization of American States or some other
international group might be interested in sponsoring such a
project.
   Manley was preaching his gospel to a friendly audience.
Committee Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., is a leading
congressional supporter of the concept of a multinational force to
combat the drug cartels.
   ``The strike force plan could turn the rhetoric about
apprehending drug kingpins into a reality _ and yet to my amazement
we have not had a firm recommendation by the administration on this
plan,'' Biden said.
   Manley said quite a few governments have been skeptical about
the idea of allowing foreign troops on their soil, even if by
invitation and under U.N. auspices as called for under his plan.
   After the hearing he met for 20 minutes with Vice President Dan
Quayle to discuss the drug problem. Before leaving for that session
he told reporters it would be ``too ambitious'' to expect Bush
administration support for the idea of a multinational force.
   Manley likened the strike force to paramilitary forces
established a decade ago to fight aircraft hijackers and urban
guerrillas in West Germany and Italy. The unit, Manley said, would
be used where drug lords ``create a terror in society and (try to)
break its will to fight them.''
   He said it might be possible to get action soon on the seven
other points in his anti-drug program.
   The package includes a central intelligence-gathering system, a
school for narcotics agents and an international reserve pool of
narcotics agents and intelligence operatives.
   Manley said the seven other pieces of the package were actually
more important if taken in total than the proposed paramilitary
force, although the idea of such an elite unit has drawn most of
the spotlight.
</TEXT>
