<HEAD>Nixon Urges Restoration of Relations With China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Nixon is urging the United
States to restore its relations with China, despite Beijing's
military crackdown on pro-democracy forces, but the White House
says it isn't ready to make dramatic changes.
   ``The issue that would change our position are changes and
actions in China,'' White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater
said Monday after announcing that President Bush had met with Nixon
for two hours Sunday. Nixon recently returned from China.
   The administration's approach to China includes suspension of
all high-level official contacts.
   Asked if Bush and Nixon disagreed over strategy toward China,
Fitzwater said, ``I wouldn't want to suggest agreement or
disagreement or suggest anything of the kind. Simply, we just
aren't willing to describe the former president's remarks.''
   Fitzwater also revealed that Bush had summoned officials from
the CIA, State Department and National Security Council to CaMP
David on Saturday for the first in a series of meetings for his
summit in December with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Fraud Reports Prompt Cut-Off of Route Used By Thousands of Soviet
Jews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department, citing reports of
fraudulent Soviet exit permits, has restricted access to a European
route used by tens of thousands of Soviet Jews to come to the
United States.
   A pattern of fraud emerged last month, apparently involving some
individuals in the Soviet agency that issues the permits, officials
said Monday.
   Permits had to be dated before Oct. 1 for Soviet Jews to obtain
U.S. visas in Rome or Vienna, and the applicants had to also have
Israeli visas. Otherwise, prospective emigrants are processed
through the U.S. Embassy in Moscow.
   The new restriction required emigrants to obtain their Israeli
visas by Monday. As a result, Soviet Jews may remain at home rather
than waiting in Rome or Vienna until their entry to the United
States is approved.
   Jews who leave the Soviet Union after Monday on Israeli visas
will be presumed to have chosen to emigrate to Israel, U.S.
officials said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Congress Urged to Repeal Part of Immigration Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is being urged to repeal part of the
1986 Immigration Reform and Control Act that a report says causes
widespread discrimination against Hispanics.
   A report issued Monday, the third anniversary of the law, said
the section of the law providing for fines against employers causes
discrimination.
   The law granted legal immigration to workers who had been in the
United States since 1982. It also set out guidelines for hiring and
provided sanctions for employers who failed to verify that all
newly employed workers had proper documentation.
   The report was issued by the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Education Fund and the American Civil Liberties Union.
   The report said 16 percent of the 3.3 million American employers
aware of the law increased or began discriminatory policies by
asking only ``foreign-looking'' or ``foreign-sounding'' job
applicants to present work authorization documents.
</TEXT>
