<SECOND>PM-China-Arrests,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Arrests 10 Accused Of Counterrevolutionary Activity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 10 people in the southern
province of Guizhou and accused them of trying to overthrow the
Communist Party, an official newspaper said today.
   The Legal Daily said the 10 were members of ``an organized,
planned and programmed counterrevolutionary group'' called ``The
China Three People's Principles Liberation Party.
   The three principles of nationalism, democracy and the people's
livelihood were put forward by Sun Yatsen, who is viewed as the
father of modern China. They are still espoused by the rival
Nationalist government on Taiwan.
   The short report did not provide details of how the group
allegedly planned to overthrow the party or when the arrests were
made.
   It also did not say if the arrests had any connection with the
pro-democracy demonstrations of last spring, which the government
has branded as a counterrevolutionary rebellion.
   It said the leader of the 10, Li Xingfu, was an ex-criminal but
gave no details.
   Last week, the semi-official China News Service reported that
police in the Sichuan city of Chongqing broke up a
``counterrevolutionary clique'' called the ``Chongqing Patriotic
and Democratic Alliance'' and arrested four members.
   That report said the Chongqing group participated in the spring
demonstrations. It said that after the June 4 military crackdown in
Beijing, the group held secret meetings, planned the organization
of underground armed forces, and tried to steal guns.
</TEXT>
