<FIRST>r p PM-ELN--Dukakis-Elections     11-07 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ELN--Dukakis-Elections,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says Nation's Democrats Learned From His Defeat: Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-ELN--Elections Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after his failed presidential bid, Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis said the legacy of his campaign may have been to
teach a potent lesson to fellow Democrats: attack.
   ``You had better be ready to attack,'' Dukakis said. ``You may
not like it, and the public may not like it, but the alternative is
to watch yourself be trashed and be defeated.''
   Where Democrats face tough election battles, particularly in
today's New Jersey and Virginia gubernatorial and New York City's
mayoral contests, the governor said those candidates have been
aware of the danger in ignoring attacks.
   ``If there's one contribution I've made to the three races, it's
at least to give the three Democrats a sense of what not to do,
what the danger is,'' Dukakis said Monday. ``And I think the three
of them were very much aware of that from the beginning, having
been forewarned by what happened in the presidential race.''
   Rep. James J. Florio, a Democrat, is running against Republican
Rep. Jim Courter in New Jersey, and Democratic Lt. Gov. L. Douglas
Wilder opposes Marshall Coleman, a Republican, in Virginia. In New
York, David N. Dinkins, a Democrat, is running against Rudolph W.
Guiliani. Polls show all three Democrats lead their opponents.
   Dukakis said he could redo his presidential campaign, he would
have struck hard at George Bush.
   But, Dukakis said, he held back because he had won the
Democratic nomination without resorting to such tactics.
   ``I felt, however mistakenly, that that was really something the
people wanted, that they had had enough negativism for eight years,
enough polarization,'' he said.
</TEXT>
