<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--NeedleExchange     11-07 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Needle Exchange,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portland Needle Exchange Program Finally Under Way</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A needle exchange program intended to
protect drug addicts from AIDS _ once planned as the first in the
nation _ has begun after nearly 1{ years of delays caused by
problems getting insurance.
   Outside-In, a nonprofit agency, started giving addicts clean
hypodermic needles in exchange for their dirty ones Nov. 1, said
Kathy Oliver, the agency's administrator.
   The 400 addicts expected to use the service also will be offered
bleach to sterilize their own needles, drug-purifying cookers and
condoms to prevent the spread of AIDS, Ms. Oliver said. The virus
is transmitted through blood and semen.
   The program was to begin in June 1988 but was delayed until the
agency found liability insurance it could afford, Ms. Oliver said.
Since then, other cities have started needle exchanges.
   The agency delayed announcement of the program's start to shield
addicts from the news media, she said.
</TEXT>
