<FIRST>r a PM-VreelandMemorial     11-07 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vreeland Memorial,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribute Paid to Late Diana Vreeland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and family of the late Diana Vreeland,
Vogue editor and curator of the Costume Institute of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, shared memories of her wit and
originality.
   Photographers' strobes illuminated former first lady Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis, actress Lauren Bacall, and fashion designers Mary
McFadden, Issey Miyake and Diane von Furstenberg, among others, on
their way in to Monday's memorial service at the museum.
   Photographer Richard Avedon said he remembered how at age 22 he
was intimidated by Vreeland, who for 25 years was fashion editor of
Harper's Bazaar before becoming editor in chief of Vogue.
   She ``accidentally'' stuck a model with a pin, and called Avedon
``Aberdeen,'' the photographer said. When the photo session was
done, Avedon said ```I can't work with that woman.'
   ``But we worked together for another 40 years,'' he said.
   Another eulogist, George Plimpton, who helped Vreeland write her
memoirs, ``D.V.,'' said, ``She liked that title. That's how the
popes sign their papal bulls: deus vobiscum.''
   Vreeland herself once said, ``I know what they'll be wearing
before they wear it. I know what they'll be eating before they eat
it. And I know where they're going before it's there.''
   Predictably, prominent colors on the backs of the fashionable
attenders at the service were the always-correct black and
Vreeland's favorite, red.
   Vreeland died in August in her late 80s.
</TEXT>
