<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     11-07 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0259</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 supporters of Ferdinand
Marcos spit on an American flag today and burned it in front of the
U.S. Embassy to demand that their late leader's body be returned
from Hawaii.
   Marcos backers also held Roman Catholic Masses marking the 40th
day since the former president died. Filipino Catholics
traditionally hold memorial services 40 days after someone's death.
   Marcos died Sept. 28 at age 27 in Hawaii, where he lived in
exile since he was ousted in a popular uprising three years ago.
   His successor, Corazon Aquino, refused to allow his body to be
buried in the Philippines, saying its return could lead to violence.
   During today's noisy demonstration, protesters carried placards
claiming the Americans ``kidnapped'' Marcos in 1986 and demanding
that his body be returned ``or else all Filipinos will curse the
Americans forever.''
   Other banners denounced Mrs. Aquino as a ``puppet of U.S.
imperialists.''
   Protesters then stomped and spit on a U.S. flag, burned it with
cigarette butts and set it afire while chanting ``Marcos once
more!''
   Several police officers stood by but did not interfere.
   On Friday, about 25,000 Marcos loyalists marched in Manila to
demand that Mrs. Aquino lift the ban on returning the former
president's body and to denounce her government.
   Police later used water cannons and clubs to disperse a few
thousand of the Marcos loyalists after an all-night vigil in front
of the headquarters of the Philippine Constabulary.
</TEXT>
