<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia     11-07 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Retires Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 15-member Politburo retired
Prime Minister Fikre Selassie Wogderess today, saying he was ill
and no longer could carry out his responsibilities, state radio
reported.
   Fikre Selassie, about 48, was the second ranking Politburo
member and the second most powerful person in the Marxist
government of President Mengistu Haile Mariam's Marxist government.
   The broadcast said Fikre Selassie, a former air force officer,
had been undergoing medical treatment for some time for an
undisclosed illness and was retired after no improvement in his
condition was noted.
   State radio did not name Fikre Selassie's successor, but
informed sources said Hailu Yimenu, a Politburo member and a deputy
prime minister, had been appointed acting prime minister.
   The prime minister's office oversees the nation's administrative
machinery.
   Fikre Selassi was one of a clique of officers who staged the
1974 coup that overthrew Emperor Haile Selassie and led to
Mengistu's assumption of power.
   He had served as prime minister since the formation of
Ethiopia's Parliament, the Shengo, in 1987, and before that was one
of three senior ministers in Mengistu's government.
   Observers said he and Mengistu differed over economic policy
with Fikre Selassie reportedly supporting greater liberalization of
the private sector.
   Hailu, his possible successor, is about 50 years old and has
served as a deputy prime minister since 1987. He also has run
several ministries including industry and mines and energy.
</TEXT>
