<FIRST>r a PM-ShipAground     11-07 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship Aground,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses: Confusion over Navigation, Lights Led to Grounding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confusion over navigation equipment and warning
lights led to the grounding of a Yugoslavian freighter on a fragile
coral reef, witnesses told a Coast Guard inquiry.
   Also Monday, the federal government filed a civil lawsuit
seeking $9 million in damages for destruction of the 500-foot swath
of reef in the Dry Tortugas, about 65 miles west of Key West.
   The suit blames the grounding on the ship's ``unseaworthiness
and the negligence of those in charge.'' The damage amount
represents the value of the seized ship and cargo, as well as the
reef damage, the U.S. attorney's office said.
   The ship's captain testified at the opening of the hearing
Monday that his second officer, who was in charge at the time of
the grounding Oct. 30, became confused while making a minor course
change.
   The move sent the phosphate hauler west into a charted shoal
instead of east into Rebecca Channel between the Dry Tortugas and
Key West, ship's captain Zdravko Beran testified. A depth finder on
board was turned off at the time.
   ``I think that he was confused. I think that he must go port,
and he went starboard,'' the captain, a merchant seaman for 30
years, said in broken English. ``He told me that he did wrong _ big
error.''
   The freighter, carrying 14,300 tons of phosphate and 143,000
gallons of fuel, was refloated without damage Thursday and
impounded by the government.
   Marine Patrol officer Gorden Sharp testified that Second Officer
Zvonko Baric told him he had mistaken a warning light for a channel
light and had hit the reef at 12 knots without slowing down.
   Beran also said he was using one large chart covering an area
from the Mississippi River to the Florida Keys because a strike had
held up delivery of more detailed charts.
</TEXT>
