<FIRST>r a PM-Cocaine-Abuse     11-07 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine-Abuse,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abuse Charges Dropped Against Mother of Cocaine-Addicted Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Child-abuse charges against the
mother of a baby born addicted to cocaine have been dismissed by a
judge who ruled the fetus is not a child.
   The judge threw out the charges Monday against 23-year-old
Cassandra Gethers, who was arrested in February after she and her
daughter were found to be addicted.
   She had given birth to a cocaine-addicted son a year before her
daughter was born and received counseling at the time on the
dangers of using the drug while pregnant.
   In dismissing the charges, Circuit Judge Robert B. Carney cited
an appeals court ruling in the case of a man who was charged with
battery against an infant after he shot a woman in the abdomen and
she gave birth to a wounded baby.
   The court ruled the fetus was not a person.
   ``That issue has been decided,'' Carney said.
   Dennis Bailey, an assistant state attorney, said he will appeal.
   Ms. Gethers remains in jail, serving an 18-month sentence for
violating probation on a conviction for possession of cocaine.
   Carney's ruling means the state cannot ``legislate morality
prior to birth,'' said Ms. Gethers' attorney, Russell Adler.
</TEXT>
