<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-US     11-07 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Approaches Needed to Calm Fears Over Japanese Investment, Expert
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors should adopt new, cooperative
alliances with U.S. firms to ease fears they are ``buying up
America'' and help revitalize the U.S. manufacturing sector, a U.S.
businessman said today.
   Peter G. Peterson, former U.S. secretary of commerce and the
chairman of The Blackstone Group of New York, called on Japanese
investors to participate in a ``global, private-sector Marshall
Plan'' to help the U.S. manufacturing sector.
   The Marshall Plan was the financial aid program drafted in 1947
by U.S. Secretary of State George Marshall to help rebuild
war-ravaged Western Europe.
   ``The United States desperately needs investment and Japan has
immense capital. The question is, how can it be done so that it's
both economically and politically productive?'' Peterson told
reporters at the Foreign Correspondents Club of Japan.
   He defended Japanese direct investments in the United States,
such as Mitsubishi Estate's recent purchase of a stake in
Rockefeller Center and Sony Corp.'s $3.4 billion buyout of Columbia
Pictures, which The Blackstone Group helped put together.
   Given huge U.S. trade and federal deficits and the need to
service the almost $1 trillion U.S. foreign debt, ``we need a
voracious amount of foreign financing,'' Peterson said, arguing
against curbs on further investments.
   Peterson said Japan should do more to ease American fears about
the so-called ``buying up of America'' by going all out to open its
own markets to foreign investment and trade and by avoiding
excessive concentration of acquisitions in such areas as Hawaii.
   ``The fears of Americans are real,'' he said.
   ``In every Japanese acquisition of a New York skyscraper or a
Waikiki hotel, some see an inevitable pattern of Japanese
ascendancy and American decline,'' he said.
   Japanese and U.S. firms should form joint ventures and minority
investment arrangements that enable both sides to exchange
technology, market access and distribution facilities, while
avoiding the political problems and managerial pitfalls of
speculative acquisitions, he said.
   Japanese companies and the government could do more to help ease
trade frictions, he said.
   ``If the Japanese companies are not more creative and flexible
in permitting foreign companies to participate directly in this
market, ... I think it will have a serious backlash effect,''
Peterson said.
</TEXT>
