<SECOND>PM-Barry-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Drug Dealer Says He Gave DC Mayor Crack Cocaine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 11th graf, Lewis' statement, to CORRECT charges to two
counts of conspiracy, rather than two counts of possession and distribution.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted drug dealer's sworn testimony that
he gave crack cocaine to Mayor Marion Barry several times is
reviving questions about whether the mayor uses drugs.
   Charles Lewis, 49, testified under oath in U.S. District Court
on Monday that he gave Barry cocaine at least three times while
Barry visited Lewis' room at a downtown Washington hotel late last
year.
   Despite many press accounts of investigations against the mayor,
Lewis' statement was the first on-the-record, under-oath accusation
that Barry, the city's mayor since 1979, had been given drugs.
   ``I'm not worried at all about this,'' Barry, who has repeatedly
denied ever using drugs, told reporters Monday. He described Lewis
as a ``convicted felon'' and added, ``He'll say anything in court
... trying to save his own hide.''
   The federal investigation began in December when city police
called off an attempt to make an undercover drug buy from Lewis on
discovering that the mayor was in Lewis' hotel room.
   Barry, who has described Lewis as an old friend, acknowledged
making at least six visits to Lewis' hotel during that period. But
the mayor has steadfastly denied using, seeing or purchasing drugs
during those trips.
   The mayor's attorney, Kenneth Mundy, scoffed at the defendant's
comments.
   ``We question the credibility of the source,'' Mundy said.
``Charles Lewis is a besieged and beleaguered man who knows that
his only salvation comes by not giving truthful statements about
the mayor.''
   Rumors about Barry's alleged use of drugs have persisted for
years. In 1984, Karen Johnson, a convicted drug dealer, went to
prison on contempt of court charges after refusing to tell federal
prosecutors whether she used cocaine with Barry or sold drugs to
him and other top city officials.
   Barry, who is married, admitted to having had an unspecified
``personal relationship'' with Johnson, but denied ever using drugs
with her.
   Lewis' statement came as Judge Stanley Sporkin was reviewing a
plea bargain calling for Lewis to plead guilty to two counts of
conspiracy to possess and distribute cocaine.
   The second count centered on Lewis' activities at the hotel last
December, and made reference to Lewis distributing cocaine to one
individual on at least three separate occasions.
   ``Because I don't want to look like a fool, was one of the
individuals you gave cocaine to the mayor of this city?'' Sporkin
asked Lewis.
   As the defendant was preparing to answer, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Judith Retchin asked to discuss the matter privately with
the judge.
   During the bench conference, Sporkin was overheard to say, ``I
don't think it fair that we read all this in the newspaper,''
apparently in reference to press leaks about the case. ``He's under
oath and should answer.''
   Sporkin then overruled the prosecutor's objections to the
question and ordered Lewis to answer.
   After hearing the query repeated by the court stenographer,
Lewis replied, ``Yes, your honor, crack cocaine.''
   When Sporkin reminded Lewis that he was under oath and asked him
whether he was telling the truth, Lewis replied, ``No question
about it, sir.''
   Sporkin then accepted the plea agreement and the two guilty
pleas under it. Sentencing was set for Jan. 8.
   Lewis faces a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and a $1
million fine for each count. Lewis had originally faced a 14-count
indictment that included perjury charges and additional counts of
cocaine distribution and possession, but prosecutors dropped 12 of
those counts.
   Lewis was convicted on cocaine distribution charges in the
Virgin Islands earlier this year. His sentencing in that case was
postponed indefinitely Monday as part of the plea bargain.
   After the court proceeding, Lewis' attorney Alan B. Soschin
predicted that Lewis will serve between 10 and 12 months in jail,
the minimum called for under the rules governing the plea bargain.
   As part of the agreement, Lewis is bound to cooperate with
prosecutors in the District of Columbia drug investigation.
   U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens refused to comment on the case, or
whether Barry is now a target of the investigation. Barry has
testified twice before the grand jury hearing evidence on the Lewis
case.
   Lewis, a former District of Columbia government official, had
been a consultant to the Virgin Islands government. He said he was
staying in the Washington hotel while looking for work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
