<FIRST>r a PM-FamilyFeud     11-07 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Feud,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Died Without Knowing of Brothers' Dispute Over Her Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maude Plymale Barber went to her grave
not knowing that one son was dead and the other in jail, charged
with killing his brother in a fight over how the cancer-stricken
woman should spend her final days.
   ``I don't know of anyone being cruel enough to tell her,'' her
brother, J. Fred Plymale, said after Monday's funeral.
   Mrs. Barber was buried Monday, the day her son Larry appeared at
a bail hearing in the Oct. 25 shotgun slaying. Charles Barber, 51,
was slain in an argument with his brother in the laundry room over
the care of their 86-year-old mother, who died Friday and had
lapsed in and out of consciousness for days, police said.
   Larry Barber, 53, did not attend the funeral but was allowed a
few moments alone with her body before he was taken in shackles to
a courtroom, where he told Judge Alfred Ferguson he helped make his
mother's last days comfortable.
   ``Mother paid all the bills and I took care of the house,'' he
said.
   Plymale told a reporter that Larry Barber, who lived with his
mother, was insensitive to her and the family.
   ``He was a liar ... and a smoker and a drunkard,'' Plymale said.
``He used to brag that he'd sit on the back porch and shoot
squirrels and eat them.''
   Charles Barber was shot as he prepared to pack his bags to
return home to Las Vegas. He had come to Huntington in early
October to help his mother but decided to leave after two weeks of
arguing with his brother, authorities said.
   Ferguson said he will decide by Wednesday whether to allow bail
for Larry Barber, who told the judge he had a drinking problem he
tried to control but often ``sat and nipped'' in front of the
television.
   Larry Barber also said he had been arrested several times for
public intoxication and once spent a night in jail for hitting a
police officer.
   ``And of course my ex-wife was always sending me to jail,'' he
told the judge.
</TEXT>
