<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     11-07 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Bombs Policeman's Home; Family Escapes Unharmed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Norther Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb planted by the Irish
Republican Army exploded today outside the home of a senior police
official, but the man and his family narrowly escaped injury.
   David Mellor, assistant chief of the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
had returned from his mother's funeral in England hours before the
bomb blew up below the living room window of his home in Drumbo,
outside Belfast, officials said.
   Mellor had just left the living room when the blast ripped
through the bulletproof window behind an armchair where he had been
reading. His wife was in another room.
   Mellor's 7-month-old daughter Rebecca was asleep in a cot in the
living room and was showered with debris, a police spokesman said.
His 18-month-old daughter Rachel was asleep in an adjoining bedroom.
   ``Both infants were only six to eight feet from the bomb when it
went off,'' the spokesman said, speaking anonymously in keeping
with British custom. ``They had a miraculous escape.''
   He said the bomb caused extensive damage.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility and, in a
statement to Belfast news media, said it had been watching Mellor's
movements for some time.
   The IRA said the bomb contained three pounds of explosives.
   ``We deliberately placed a small charge only, because we were
aware of the young children in the house,'' it said. ``Otherwise we
could undoubtedly have guaranteed Mellor's death with a larger
charge.''
   The English-born Mellor, 49, is in charge of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary's complaints and discipline branch. He is scheduled to
take over as deputy chief constable of South Wales later this month.
   Eight Royal Ulster Constabulary officers, including one chief
superintendent and two superintendents, have been murdered by the
IRA this year.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule of Northern Ireland and
unite the predominantly Protestant province with the Roman Catholic
Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
