<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     11-07 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Supporters Attack Opponents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian teen-agers today beat up
vendors who ignored a strike that was called to show solidarity
with the army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun, in his opposition to the
new president, witnesses said.
   Rene Mouawad, who was elected president Sunday, consulted with
politicians in Syrian-controlled north Lebanon in an effort to form
a government.
   Aoun, who headed a Christian Cabinet for 14 months prior to
Mouawad's election, remained in the shell-ravaged presidential
palace in suburban Baabda, refusing to relinquish it to Mouawad.
   He termed the presidential election ``unconstitutional.''
   About 500 youths chanting ``Aoun is the legitimate leader!''
gathered outside the French Embassy in Hazmieh, just south of
Baabda. They waved portraits of Aoun, Lebanese flags and slogans
calling on French President Francois Mitterrand to ``protect
Lebanon.''
   France has been the Christians' main protector here. It ruled
Lebanon until independence in 1943.
   About 40 of the demonstrators began a sit-in outside the
compound. They raised a banner that said: ``Mitterand has
disappointed us.''
   Paris, Washington and other major Arab and international
governments have backed Mouawad, a Maronite Catholic and a 32-year
veteran of Lebanese politics.
   He was voted into office by Lebanese legislators who also
approved a peace accord giving the Moslem majority more power in
decision making. Aoun opposed the accord because it did not set a
deadline for withdrawal of Syrian troops from Lebanon.
   His main problem with Mouawad is the president's close links
with Syria. Syria has 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab
League peacekeeping mandate. Aoun wants them out because they are
the Moslems' main supporters.
   A committee of Christian youths who support Aoun called a
general strike for a fourth day in east Beirut and the Christian
heartland to the north, which is controlled by Aoun's 20,000 troops.
   Only bakeries were allowed to open, and thousands of people
lined up outside.
   Some vendors in the east Beirut neighborhood of Ashrafiyeh
defied the strike call and opened their stands. Young demonstrators
attacked them with sticks, witnesses reported.
   ``We want peace. We want to work to make money. We live
hand-to-mouth,'' a vendor shouted as teen-agers beat him up, one
witness reported.
   He said some demonstrators were ``kids around the age of 12.''
The others were slightly older.
   ``The vegetable vendors and the kids fought with fists and
sticks. Policemen at a nearby police station did not interfere. In
fact, they didn't dare interfere because they know the
demonstrators are backed by the army,'' another witness said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said hundreds of demonstrators drove by in cars decorated
with Aoun's pictures and Lebanese flags ``shouting orders to abide
by the strike.''
   A car mechanic said: ``We want an end to war. We've had enough.
   ``What more does the general want? does he want to get the
Maronites (Catholics) slaughtered?'' he said. He identified himself
only as Fares, and added: ``You publish my name and the general's
intelligence men will pick me up in 10 minutes.''
   ``They didn't spare the patriarch,'' he said, referring to the
attack early Monday on Maronite Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir, the
highest Christian religious authority in Lebanon.
   Pro-Aoun demonstrators ransacked his compound in Bkirki, north
of Beirut, shouted insults at the patriarch and forced him to kneel
on the floor and kiss a poster of Aoun.
   Sfeir supported Mouawad.
   Mouawad has been at his home in the mountain resort of Zghorta,
in north Lebanon, where dozens of parliamentrians, former prime
ministers and senior politicians visited him for consultations.
   In west Beirut, an old stone villa was being prepared for
Mouawad.
   The Baabda palace is a wreck. It was destroyed in six months of
ferocious fighting between Aoun and Syrian troops. The fighting was
halted by a cesae-fire in September.
</TEXT>
