<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Kissinger     11-07 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kissinger,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Arrives in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger
arrived in Beijing today for a private visit expected to include
meetings with China's top leaders.
   Kissinger, making what is believed to be his 15th visit since
his historic secret trip of 1971, arrived by private plane from
Hong Kong and was whisked to the secluded Diaoyutai State
Guesthouse in western Beijing.
   The Foreign Ministry, his host, has told the foreign press it
will have no access to Kissinger and has refused to divulge his
schedule. Kissinger aides also refused to discuss the visit.
   Foreign sources said he is expected to meet top officials,
including senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   Kissinger is the third prominent American to visit China in a
private capacity since Washington suspended high-level official
contacts with China. That was in response to the June military
crackdown on the pro-democracy movement.
   Alexander Haig, an aide during Richard Nixon's administration
and secretary of state under Ronald Reagan, attended a business
symposium at the beginning of October. Nixon was in Beijing last
week for extensive talks with Chinese leaders.
   Like Haig and Nixon, Kissinger is expected to stress that China
and the United States should strive to overcome their current
differences in the interest of restoring normal relations.
   Kissinger, in a speech in Hong Kong on Monday, urged the United
States not to cut itself off from China, despite its condemnation
of the military crackdown in June that left hundreds of people dead.
   ``It is not in the interest of China to isolate itself, and it
is not the interest of outside countries to isolate China,'' he
said. ``We have to deal with the future, and the future requires a
resumption of dialogue based on mutual respect.''
   During Nixon's visit, the two sides agreed on the importance of
improving relations, although the Chinese repeated their claims
that the United States was interfering in its internal affairs.
   Nixon briefed President Bush on his visit at a White House
dinner on Sunday. After the dinner, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said Bush found the former president's views
``interesting and productive, but our general policy has not
changed.''
   Kissinger's secret visit to Beijing in 1971 for talks with the
late Premier Chou En-lai set the stage for Nixon's February 1972
trip, which reopened relations between the United States and
Communist China after 23 years of animosity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
