<FIRST>r a PM-GhettoHospital-Army     11-07 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ghetto Hospital-Army,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Surgeons Training at Ghetto Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army is training young surgeons to handle
war carnage by sending them to the emergency room at a ghetto
hospital inundated with victims of gang violence.
   Two Army residents recently completed two months' training at
Martin Luther King Jr.-Drew Medical Center in the city's Watts
section. County supervisors were to vote today on allowing four
more surgeons to train there next year.
   ``At King, we see the kind of penetrating trauma that we just
don't see at other hospitals,'' said Dr. John McPhail, chief of
surgery at William Beaumont Army Medical Center in El Paso, Texas.
``It's a place where the residents will have to treat a large
volume of high-velocity wounds, the kind we would see in war.''
   Army doctors used to receive their trauma surgery training at
public hospitals near their home bases. But the young surgeons
rarely see the kinds of gaping, multiple wounds caused by automatic
and semiautomatic gunfire common to gang violence here, where more
than 353 gang-related slayings were reported last year.
   Dr. John Holcomb, a fourth-year resident at the Army hospital in
El Paso, completed his two-month stint in trauma surgery at
King-Drew last week. The hospital is at the Army's Fort Bliss.
   ``It makes sense that since we're military surgeons, we'll treat
the kinds of wounds that we would see in combat,'' he said. ``And
that's definitely what I saw there.''
   The 430-bed, county-run teaching hospital treated almost 3,500
trauma victims in 1988, or nearly 40 percent of the county's trauma
patients. Health officials estimate that doctors there treat more
than 100 gunshot cases and dozens of stabbings each month.
   Dr. Arthur Fleming, chief of trauma and surgery at King-Drew,
proposed the facility as an Army training site to boost manpower at
the overburdened trauma unit.
   Army officials said they hope to make it a permanent part of
their surgical training.
</TEXT>
