<FIRST>r a PM-PrisonSuit     11-07 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Suit,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU Asks Federal Judge to Unshackle Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union has
gone to court to get Camp Hill prison officials to remove the
shackles and handcuffs used to bind some 1,000 inmates in pairs
since a riot last month.
   U.S. District Judge Sylvia Rambo set a hearing for today in a
suit filed by the Pennsylvania branch of the ACLU on behalf of four
inmates.
   The suit also claims inmates have not had adequate clothing,
heat, plumbing, food or medical treatment since the uprising was
put down Oct. 27. The rioting left 123 people injured and half the
prison in flames.
   The continued restraint of the inmates is ``designed solely to
inflict cruel and unusual punishment,'' said the suit, filed Monday.
   ``I think it's torture. We do not treat animals this way,'' said
ACLU legal director Stefan Presser.
   A Corrections Department spokeswoman said about 1,200 inmates
remain restrained and in locked cells.
   Another spokesman, Kenneth Robinson, said the staff is trying to
identify inmates who were not directly involved in the rioting.
Those inmates will be moved to other blocks where prisoners are not
shackled, he said.
   ``The purpose of the handcuffs is for security,'' he said. ``We
are concerned about the safety of both staff and inmates.''
   Robinson would not comment on the specifics of the ACLU suit.
   Four guards and two inmates hurt in the rioting remain
hospitalized.
</TEXT>
