<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-FirstYear     11-07 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-First Year,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Marks First Anniversary of Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush offered his thanks today, on
the first anniversary of his election, to the American people for
choosing him and said he would move to ``shed light in the dark
corners of American life.''
   The president called an Election day news conference to mark the
occasion.
   ``I'm very pleased that our administration has come together
rapidly with good people and with good ideas and a quiet sense of
purpose,'' he said in an opening statement.
   Bush expressed satisfaction with his record in international and
national affairs, saying he had seen the greatest surge toward
democracy around the world in at least 40 years.
   And, he said, he had responded to those challenges. Critics have
called him overly cautious in reacting to changes sweeping the
Soviet Union, Poland, East Germany and elsewhere in Eastern Europe.
   He cited his forthcoming meeting with Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev; plans for a formal summit after that; his proposal
for aid to Poland and his support for international efforts to
bolster the movement throughout Eastern Europe toward free market
economies and democratic forms of government.
   Throughout that area, Bush said, ``important decisions have been
made for freedom and we've supported those movements.''
   At home, the president said, he is ``more convinced today than
ever that we can shed light in the dark corners of America'' and
offer hope to the needy.
   He promised to continue a bipartisan approach toward Congress,
said more had to be done to combat the federal deficit, repeated
his pledge to oppose any new federal taxes and basked in ``the
underlying strength of the American economy.''
   Bush cited ``the longest expansion in history,'' and low rates
of unemployment and inflation.
   ``I want to thank the American people on this Election Day for
giving me this opportunity to serve,'' he said. ``I enjoy it.''
