<FIRST>u i PM-Namibia 2ndLd-Writethru a0538 11-07 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0538,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pre-Independence Vote Launched In Longtime South African Territory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to ADD quote from government spokesman on
voting conduct. ADDS estimated population of Namibia. Pickup 7th pvs, ``Today
we...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters stood in lines more than a mile
long today as balloting began in an election that is to lead to
independence for Africa's last colony.
   Authorities reported violations of election rules and at least
one attempt to distribute bogus pamphlets but said there had been
no major disturbances.
   ``The behavior of the voting public has been an example to the
rest of the world,'' said Gerhard Roux, spokesman for the South
African-installed territorial government.
   The U.N.-monitored elections are for a 72-member assembly that
is to write a constitution. Namibia, ruled by South Africa for 74
years, is expected to become independent early next year.
   ``After all the years of waiting, the people of Namibia
themselves, and no one else, will have their say in free and fair
elections,'' the U.N. special representative, Martti Ahtisaari,
said in a radio broadcast as five days of voting began in the
southern African territory.
   There are 701,488 registered voters in Namibia, about 60 percent
of them illiterate. The population was 1.3 million in 1981, when
the last census was taken, but is believed to be far higher now.
   The key issue in the elections was whether the South-West Africa
People's Organization (SWAPO), favored to win the most votes, would
capture the two-thirds majority needed to write a constitution
without consulting any of the other nine parties.
   ``Today we are finally burying apartheid colonialism,'' SWAPO
leader Sam Nujoma told reporters at a polling station in Katutura,
the main black neighborhood on the edge of Windhoek.
   ``There is a beautiful lady expecting a baby,'' Nujoma told a
cheering, singing crowd at a rally Monday night. ``That lady is
mother Namibia, and that baby is the freedom and independence of
this land.''
   The queue of voters stretched for about 1.2 miles when the polls
opened in Katutura. Long lines also were reported elsewhere.
   Namibians may vote daily through Saturday and Chief Electoral
Officer Abraham Visser said he was confident results would be
available Nov. 15.
   More than 7,000 U.N. military and civilian representatives _ one
for every 1,000 voters _ are in predominantly black Namibia and
have supervised a massive campaign to promote voting and prevent
fraud.
   Posters and television advertisements financed by U.N. and
territorial officials have stressed that ballots will be secret and
urged voters to ``vote without fear.''
   All voters are required to dip their fingers in invisible ink
after they cast their ballot. The ink is indelible for five days.
When voters enter the booths at the polling stations they must put
their fingers under an ultra-violet light, which will reveal the
ink if they already have voted.
   Officials said most of this sparsely populated desert territory
now is tranquil. But the four-month election campaign was marked by
sporadic violence and intimidation, including the Sept. 12
assassination of the only ranking white in SWAPO, Anton Lubowski.
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard cautioned that ``the peace is a very
fragile peace.''
   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
noted Monday in a final pre-election report that almost one in 10
Namibians had a gun permit and an unknown number were armed
illegally.
   ``While at this time there have been marked improvements in the
security situation on the eve of the election, I remain vigilant to
the possibility of a deterioration in the field of law and order,''
Perez de Cuellar said.
   In neighboring South Africa, President F.W. de Klerk urged
Namibians to ``cast your vote in the interest of peace and
prosperity.''
   ``The strife and bitterness, the mistrust and misunderstandings
of the past must be put behind us,'' he said.
   South Africa seized mineral-rich Namibia from its German
colonizers in 1915. The League of Nations, forerunner of the United
Nations, provided South Africa with a mandate to administer the
territory.
   The U.N. revoked the mandate in 1966 and SWAPO launched a
guerrilla war later that year after South Africa refused to grant
independence.
   More than 20,000 people, mostly SWAPO guerrillas, died in the
bush war that finally ended in April.
   Nujoma said his left-leaning organization would accept any
election result certified by the United Nations.
   The organization once espoused a Marxist-Leninist one-party
state, but Nujoma last month promised that SWAPO ``has no intention
of imposing a one-party political system on the Namibian people
against their will.''
   Its chief rival is the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, a
moderate, multiracial coalition that favors a capitalist economy
and was part of a South African-installed transitional government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
