<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Verri     11-07 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Verri,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Chairman Killed In Car Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Italian state-owned airline was
killed when his car collided with a city bus, authorities said.
   The accident happened Monday night while Alitalia Chairman Carlo
Verri was telephoning his wife while sitting in the back seat of
the car, the Italian news agency ANSA reported.
   Verri's car ran a red light at high speed, crashed into an
oncoming bus and was thrown against a soft drink stand on the
corner of the intersection, according to initial police reports.
   Verri's driver, Enrico Grappelli, 25, also was killed. No one on
the bus was hurt.
   Verri, 50, was appointed chairman of Alitalia in 1988.
Previously, he had served as director-general of the Swedish
company Riv-Skf, director of Italian Zanussi Elettrodomestici and
director and member of the executive committee of the Swedish
Electrolux Component Group.
   He is survived by his wife and two children.
