<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-07 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0533,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Captures Ring Believed to Have Slain Two Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to update with Palestinian killed. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army has captured a ring of Moslem
fundamentalists in the occupied Gaza Strip who are believed to have
kidnapped and killed two Israeli soldiers, the military announced
today.
   The body of one victim was never found, but an army statement
said interrogation of the suspects yielded the first concrete
evidence that the soldier, reported missing in May, was slain after
being abducted.
   The trooper, 18-year-old Ilan Saadon, of the Mediterranean
coastal town of Ashkelon, would be the 41st Israeli slain in the
Palestinian uprising against Israeli occupation of the Gaza Strip
and West Bank. At least 612 Arabs have been killed by Israelis
during the 22-month revolt.
   The latest death occurred today, when riot police shot and
killed a Palestinian teen-ager in the West Bank town of Qalqilya.
The army said he was killed during a clash with stone-throwers.
   Arab reports said at least three other teen-agers were wounded
in the same protest.
   Also today, the body of a 28-year-old Palestinian was found in
the West Bank town of Nablus with multiple stab wounds. Arab
reports said he was suspected of collaborating with Israeli
authorities.
   The victim, Nabil Samhan, was the 142nd Palestinian killed by
fellow Arabs during the uprising.
   The army did not give the number of suspects arrested in the
soldiers' deaths. It said the ring's leader was among those
detained. It added that the three prime suspects have fled the
country.
   The statement said evidence gathered in the case ``has
strengthened the belief that the soldier Ilan Saadon was kidnapped
and killed as well, similarly to Avi Sassportas, and was buried
somewhere in Israeli territory.''
   Saadon was last seen by a fellow soldier entering a white sedan
in southern Israel on May 3.
   The suspects are also believed involved in the Feb. 16
kidnapping and slaying of 21-year-old soldier Avi Sassportas, who
disappeared while hitchhiking home. His body was found May 7 in a
grove near the Gaza Strip.
   A police inquiry published today recommended that six policemen
be fired and put under criminal investigation for the fatal
shooting of an 18-year-old Palestinian in the West Bank town of
Bethlehem on Oct. 26.
   Police spokesman Uzi Sandori said the recommendations for firing
and investigating the six officers were given to National Police
Commissioner David Kraus, who was reviewing them.
   Israel radio quoted the findings as saying the policemen are
suspected of causing death, fabricating evidence and giving false
testimony.
   The inquiry was launched after Israeli newspapers quoted Arab
witnesses as saying the 18-year-old Palestinian was shot at
point-blank range, not during a car chase as police reported.
</TEXT>
