<DOCNO> AP891107-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Greece     11-07 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Leader Receives Mandate To Try To Form Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative leader Constantine Mitsotakis
received a mandate today to try to form a new government. Party
officials said he faces a difficult time.
   Mitsotakis, whose New Democracy party won the most parliamentary
seats in Sunday's elections but just missed a majority, got the
exploratory mandate from President Christos Sartzetakis.
   Mitsotakis has until Friday to drum up enough support to
persuade the president to let him go before Parliament with the
proposed government for a vote of confidence.
   ``In three days I will return to the president and inform him of
the results of my efforts,'' Mitsotakis told a news conference.
   New Democracy defeated Andreas Papandreou's Panhellenic
Socialist Movement, PASOK, in national elections for the second
time in five months. However, it failed to win the 151 seats
necessary for a parliamentary majority.
   Papandreou, who governed Greece from 1981 to the June elections,
will be given a chance to form a government if Mitsotakis fails.
The former premier has 128 seats in the 300-seat Parliament,
compared to New Democracy's 148.
   The third-largest party, the Communist-led Coalition of the Left
and Progress, has said it will not give the conservatives or the
socialists its 21 seats.
   Three independents were also elected.
   New Democracy officials said they expected Mitsotakis to have a
tough time gathering enough support for a government, especially
since one of the independents was allied with the leftist parties.
   Mitsotakis said he will not enter any alliance that will force
his party to water down its program to revive the economy and seek
closer U.S. ties.
   A continued deadlock among the parties could lead to a third set
of elections this year. The conservatives were not enthusiastic
about the possibility.
   ``I don't see new elections right now, for the simple reason
that no one (of the parties) wants them, nor do the Greek people.
Only in the event of a total deadlock will we go to elections,''
said Ioannis Palaiokrassas, a senior New Democracy member.
   If all three main parties fail to form a government the
president will invite them to put together a joint administration.
The leftist Coalition supports a government of all three parties.
   New Democracy and the Coalition formed an alliance after the
inconclusive June poll. That alliance was dedicated solely to
investigating Papandreou and former ministers in his
administration. It resigned in October shortly after the former
premier and five of his ministers were indicted by Parliament.
   Another set of elections would not necessarily produce a strong
government. The proportional electoral system introduced by PASOK
before the June elections makes it very difficult for any party to
win a parliamentary majority.
</TEXT>
