<FIRST>r p PM-ELN--NYCMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0486 11-07 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ELN--NYC Mayoral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dinkins Holds Big Lead in Poll on Eve of New York Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Dinkins, Giuliani, Koch casting
their ballots. PICK UP 3rd graf, `Should Giuliani ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-ELN--Election Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat David Dinkins entered the voting booth
today with a big lead in opinion polls but with mayoral rival
Rudolph Giuliani snapping at his heels with allegations of
financial irregularities.
   ``I hope we prevail, of course,'' said Dinkins, who has accused
the Republican of running a negative campaign.
   Giuliani emerged with confidence after casting his ballot.
   Today's election will decide the successor to Democrat Ed Koch,
the outspoken symbol of the city for 12 years. Koch stopped off at
a police precinct before voting to ``say goodbye to the cops.''
   Should Giuliani, the former federal prosecutor, pull off an
upset, he would become the city's first GOP mayor elected since
John Lindsay in 1965. Dinkins, the Manhattan borough president,
would be the city's first black mayor.
   A weekend poll of 3,010 likely voters by WNYW-TV and the Gallup
Organization showed Dinkins leading 56 percent to 42 percent.
   Dinkins' backers planned a massive get-out-the-vote effort,
using 12,000 volunteers. Workers staffing a 600-line phone bank
were encouraging 300,000 supporters to vote and more than 100 sound
trucks were being deployed.
   More than 60 percent of the city's nearly 3.2 million voters
were expected to turn out. Democrats outnumber Republicans by 5-1.
   The candidates spent Monday in familiar poses: Dinkins
surrounded by prominent Democrats like Koch, whom he defeated in
September's primary; Gov. Mario Cuomo and Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, speaking of ``unity and tolerance.''
   Giuliani, surrounded by supportive police officers, sharply
questioned Dinkins' financial dealings.
   ``So many serious questions have been raised about my opponent
that this election has become a referendum on integrity,'' Giuliani
said in a speech downtown.
   Giuliani was referring to alleged financial transgressions,
including Dinkins' admitted failure to pay taxes 20 years ago and
the payment of $9,500 to an ex-convict to get out the vote in the
primary. He sold cable-television stock he once valued at $1
million to his son for $58,000.
   ``David Dinkins has a history of getting away with things that
others don't get away with,'' Giuliani said.
   The latest allegation was that Dinkins failed to list on
financial disclosure or tax forms that a friend paid in part for a
trip to France last year.
   Dinkins said it is unclear whether such a gift must be listed on
financial disclosure forms, but added he would amend his statement
anyway ``in order to provide the fullest possible disclosure.''
   He dismissed the accusation as ``desperate'' and called on
supporters to reject ``the scurrilous politics of divide and
conquer.''
   ``We've rejected the negative politics of slam and slander _ and
stayed on the high ground of substantive dialogue and moral
leadership,'' Dinkins told cheering supporters at a rally.
   Giuliani, who has never held elective office, projected himself
as an outsider who can clean up a scandal-scarred municipal
government and portrayed Dinkins as a product of Democratic
``clubhouse politics.''
   ``I enter City Hall with no strings, no deals, no ethical or
legal problems that will envelop my administration,'' Giuliani said.
</TEXT>
