<FIRST>u w PM-Carter-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0468 11-07 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carter-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter Says Bush Too Cautious To Eastern Europe Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 2nd graf with Bush reax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter says President Bush is
``delaying too long'' in responding to the initiatives of Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the rebirth of democracy in
Eastern Europe.
   ``We have got to get our act together,'' Carter said on Monday
in the strongest criticism he has offered to date on Bush's
performance in office.
   Bush today dismissed such criticism, although he made no direct
reference to Carter.
   At a White House news conference, the president challenged
critics to come up with specific ideas ``other than triple the
spending'' on aid to Poland and Hungary.
   Bush said, contrary to the basis of one question, that leaders
in Western Europe ``don't seem to agree'' with some of the poltical
criticism he gets in connection with his dealings with nations that
have been in the Soviet sphere since World War II.
   Carter, in Washington for a reunion with the people who staffed
his campaigns and administration, told an audience there is
``substantial proof'' that at least in some areas Gorbachev is
producing irreversible change in the Soviet Union and Eastern
Europe.
   The response of the Bush administration ``doesn't match what
Gorbachev is doing,'' Carter said.
   ``I think we are delaying too long in responding effectively to
this change that is occurring,'' Carter said during a seminar
sponsored by the Center for National Policy on the subject of
``waging peace.''
   In the absence of U.S. leadership in Eastern Europe, a policy
vacuum occurs that cannot be filled by the leaders of Britain,
France, West Germany or any other nation, Carter said.
   ``The spokesman for the Western world has got to be the
president of the United States,'' Carter said. ``I think we need to
be able to respond to Gorbachev because he is winning a tremendous
propaganda victory in all of the many countries I have visited.''
   Walter F. Mondale, who served as Carter's vice president and who
himself sought the presidency, echoed Carter's complaints.
   ``I think now is the time to strike,'' Mondale said. ``I think
the circumstances are such that we need a much more rapid U.S.
policy response.''
   ``They speak to us in Eastern Europe of the joy of democracy and
freedom,'' Mondale said. ``We sort of come back in the language of
bookkeepers and bureaucrats.''
   Robert M. Kimmitt, undersecretary of state for political
affairs, another participant in the seminar, said the United States
``does have to encourage and respond vigorously'' to rapidly
evolving events in Eastern Europe, but the administration is
looking for ``elements of irreversibility'' in Gorbachev's policies.
   Carter called Gorbachev's rise to power ``one of the
transforming political developments of our lifetime,'' citing the
Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, Soviet encouragement of the
Vietnamese withdrawal from Cambodia, Gorbachev's arms control
initiatives and willingness to permit independent policies in
Warsaw Pact nations.
   ``It's hard to find fault with what he says,'' Carter said of
Gorbachev. ``In some cases there is substantial proof he means what
he says.''
   The former president also challenged Bush to more closely engage
the United States in pursuing peace in the Middle East.
   He said Bush must make it clear he intends to vigorously pursue
a peace agreement with all the means at his disposal and will not
withdraw until it is achieved.
   Using the resources of the Carter Presidential Center in
Atlanta, Carter has monitored the electoral process in Nicaragua.
   He said he wants ``to make it extremely difficult _ impossible _
for either party to withdraw from the election when one side or the
other discovers it is likely to lose.''
   ``Once they get involved in a highly publicized peace effort,
its difficult for them to withdraw,'' Carter said. ``It would be
devastating for them in terms of their public relations.''
   Carter said he believes Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega
``made a tragic and deplorable mistake'' last week when he
announced cancellation of a cease-fire with the rebels.
   But he said he does not believe Ortega's action ``is going to
interfere with the holding of an election.''
   And Carter said he believes recent attacks by Contra rebels
across the Honduran border into Nicaragua have been aimed at
disrupting the process of registering voters.
   Carter, who was hailed by participants in the reunion for his
accomplishments as a former president in the fields of health,
education, housing, and conflict resolution, used the occasion to
appeal for funds to raise a $50 million endowment to perpetuate the
work of the Carter center.
</TEXT>
