<FIRST>r p PM-ELN--PropositionsRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0422 11-07 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ELN--Propositions Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0422,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ballot Issues Include Baseball, Taxes, Cruise Missile, AIDS Discrimination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, `In St. ...' to fix `subside' to `subsidize.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay rights, a proposed smoking ordinance in the heart of
tobacco-land, and the fate of a championship baseball club are
among key ballot issues voters were deciding today.
   In all, residents of 10 states will consider 56 statewide
issues, 21 in Texas alone. Scores of citywide issues also are being
contested in this off-year election. As has often been the case,
many of the most controversial local contests are in California.
   San Francisco Bay area residents, fresh from a major earthquake,
weighed a proposal to raise more than $100 million for a new
stadium to keep the National League champion San Francisco Giants
from fleeing.
   San Franciscans also were considering a ``domestic partners''
measure entitling unmarried couples employed by that city to the
same funeral and sick-leave benefits as married couples.
   The issue of discrimination against AIDS victims got its
first-ever ballot test in nearby Concord, where voters were
deciding whether to repeal a recent ordinance protecting the rights
of those victims.
   In affluent Irvine, voters were considering deleting a section
of the Los Angeles suburb's human rights ordinance that outlaws
discrimination against homosexuals. Backers of the proposal say the
measure could promote immorality. Opponents including Mayor Larry
Agran called the repeal effort homophobic.
   Los Angeles, Washington, New York and Laguna Beach, Calif., are
among cities with gay rights provisions.
   In Greensboro, N.C., where the tobacco giant Lorillard Inc.
employs 2,000 workers and more than half the city's registered
voters smoke, voters decided whether to ban smoking in elevators
and in certain stores, and require restaurants seating more than 50
people to set aside a quarter of their seats for non-smokers.
   Kansas City, Mo.-area voters weighed a sales-tax increase to
raise $14 million to wage a war on rising drug abuse.
   Voters in New York City considered a sweeping charter revision
to bring it into compliance with a U.S. Supreme Court order to make
its legislature more representative.
   In St. Louis, voters considered a 4-cent property tax hike to
subsidize the St. Louis Symphony. Orchestra officials say they
can't raise any more money from the wealthy or ticket buyers.
Critics in the Missouri legislature have called the symphony
elitist.
   Seattle residents considered a measure ending forced school
busing and promoting educational choice.
   Among statewide issues:
   _ Michigan and Washington residents considered hefty sales-tax
increases aimed at raising hundreds of millions of dollars for
education.
   Washington's ``Children's Initiative'' would hike the sales tax
by nearly a penny per dollar to help raise at least $360 million a
year for smaller school classes, early childhood education,
child-abuse and drug education.
   _ Utah residents decideed whether the state should spend $56
million for ski jumps and ice rinks that could bring that state the
1998 Olympic Winter Games.
   _ In Maine, a non-binding referendum asks whether voters want
the Navy to stop testing Tomahawk cruise missiles over their state.
The Navy began testing the missiles over Maine last winter. Voters
decided whether to approve an agreement to dispose of nuclear waste
from Maine at a facility in Beatty, Nev.
   _ In Texas, where the ballot is laden with 21 propositions,
questions include whether to triple the current $7,200 salaries of
state legislatures, whether to authorize a $500 million bond issue
aimed at bringing running water and sewers to disease-ridden border
towns, whether to enshrine a ``victim's bill of rights'' in the
state constitution, and whether to finance a record $400 million
build-up of the state's prison system.
   Texans will decided whether to drop a 113-year-old provision
requiring state office-holders to publicly affirm that they didn't
bribe their way into their positions. Some consider the oath
demeaning, but at least one official who recently took it said he
didn't mind.
   ``I kind of like it,'' said Secretary of State George Bayoud.
``During my swearing in, there were people from around the state
here and they said they liked it.''
</TEXT>
