<FIRST>u w PM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru a0457 11-07 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Opens Debate On Minimum Wage Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>EDs: Top 8 grafs new with Dole and Mitchell complaining about stall
tactics, Bush comment on domestic agenda. Editing throughout. ^By JOHN
KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders today urged colleagues to stop
using delaying tactics preventing final passage of a compromise
plan to raise the hourly minimum wage to $4.25.
   Both Majority Leader George Mitchell and Republican leader Bob
Dole called on any senators who plan to offer amendments to the
proposal to come forward. A few senators have indicated they might
propose amendments, and debate has been all but stopped because
none has actually done so.
   Dole and Mitchell said they hoped a final vote on the minimum
wage could come today so the Senate could concentrate on
negotiations to raise the government's debt ceiling.
   The possible amendments range from an attempt to revive
President Bush's call for a capital gains tax cut to technical
changes in the minimum-wage bill. Most are considered little more
than attempts to delay final passage of the measure because of
partisan disputes, particularly those over capital gains and
efforts to raise the government's debt limit.
   ``This is, of course, a situation with which we in the Senate
have become all too familiar,'' Mitchell, D-Maine, said of the
delay.
   ``It is important we finish minimum wage, get some agreement to
vote,'' said Dole, R-Kan.
   The minimum-wage bill was among several President Bush mentioned
at a morning news conference at which he said Congress was moving
too slowly on his domestic agenda. ``I urge the Congress to move
quickly on these proposals,'' Bush said.
   Senate debate began Monday and only two senators spoke despite
Mitchell's urging that any senators with amendments step forward.
   During that debate, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., praised
Bush for compromising with Congress on the minimum wage. Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, predicted easy passage of the measure but said it
would hurt the economy.
   ``The nine-year stalemate over the minimum wage is finally
broken,'' said Kennedy. ``We certainly welcome that change of
attitude between the Reagan administration and the Bush
administration.''
   The increase would be the first since the federal wage floor hit
$3.35 in 1981.
   Hatch said the increase would not help many working poor but
would cause wage and price inflation.
   ``Every good and material that is sold in America is going to go
up in cost,'' Hatch said. ``I think that means we're going to have
some very difficult economic times in the future. I hope I'm
wrong.''
   Kennedy countered by calling the planned increase ``a very small
adjustment'' that still would leave minimum-wage earners well
behind price inflation since the last increase in 1981.
   ``May we do everything in our power to make sure that the
working poor never have to wait that long again,'' Kennedy said.
   The proposal, which also would create a subminimum for
teen-agers, is the product of a deal struck a week ago between Bush
and congressional Democrats.
   The measure provides two 45-cent increases, one next April 1 and
the other a year later.
   It also allows employers to pay a lower wage to workers age 16
to 19 with less than three months total job experience. The
subminimum could be paid for three additional months if the workers
were in certified training programs. The subminimum would be $3.35
beginning next April 1 and rise to $3.61 on April 1, 1991. The
provision allowing the lower wage expires in 1993.
</TEXT>
