<FIRST>r a PM-ElephantFetus     11-07 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elephant Fetus,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Asian Elephant Sets Pregnancy Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fetus carried by an Asian elephant for a
record two years is probably dead, say veterinarians at the San
Diego Wild Animal Park.
   ``The chances are essentially nil that she is carrying a live
fetus, but there's still an outside chance because she is
healthy,'' James Oosterhuis, park director of veterinary services,
said Monday.
   The average gestation period for Asian elephants is 618 to 648
days.
   The pregnancy of 19-year-old Jean reached 725 days Monday,
surpassing that of an Asian elephant that went 720 days before
giving birth at a German zoo.
   Veterinarians attempted an endoscopy on the pachyderm last week,
but the 5-foot instrument for getting a glimpse of the fetus wasn't
long enough. Park staffers located two longer instruments after
more than a dozen phone calls, but the endoscopy isn't needed
immediately because Jean appears healthy.
   Veterinarians had not decided whether to induce labor or allow
nature to take its course. They are concerned the fetus, which
weighs 185 to 200 pounds, could pass an infection to its 2{-ton
mother, Oosterhuis said.
   ``If she were sick and the going got tough, then we would have
to deal with it immediately,'' Oosterhuis said.
</TEXT>
