<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Abortion     11-07 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Abortion,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Abortion Not Most Important Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that he doesn't
believe voters cast their ballots on the single issue of abortion,
nor is it the most important issue on his agenda.
   ``I think our party is broad enough to contain differing views
on this and I think the Democratic Party is,'' Bush told a White
House news conference.
   ``I don't believe most voters are single issue voters. There is
no evidence to support that, none at all,'' he said, citing data by
his campaign pollster, Robert Teeter, showing the issue of abortion
ranked between ninth and 14th on the list of what voters consider
most important.
   Bush said he had ``no intention of changing my position'' on
abortion.
   The president opposes abortion except in cases of rape, incest
or endangerment to the mother's life. He opposes federal money to
fund abortions for poor women.
   ``Abortion divides,'' said Bush, acknowledging the volatile
atmosphere on abortion since the Supreme Court gave states
increased power to restrict it this year.
   ``Is it the most important issue for me? Absolutely not,'' he
said
   Bush recently vetoed a $157.6 billion funding package for the
departments of Education, Labor and Health and Human Services
because of abortion-funding provisions.
   ``It's just so personal,'' he said. ``I just come down more on
the side of life. ... I don't fault people who view this
differently. There's plenty of room for difference.''
</TEXT>
