<SECOND>AM-BRF--Uganda-Journalist,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugandan Journalist Detained Over Article</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have detained the editor of
Uganda's only independent English-language daily newspaper because
of an article that calls President Yoweri Museveni a liar, a
journalists' group said Tuesday.
   Samuel Katwere, editor of The Star, has been held without charge
since his arrest Monday, said James Namakajjo, president of the
Uganda Journalists Association.
   Namakajjo said Katwere, who became editor of The Star in
October, was being held because of a Sept. 22 article titled
``Telling Lies.''
   It said the managing director of the government-owned commercial
bank is paid hundreds of thousands of dollars annually as
compensation for his two children killed during Museveni's
five-year bush war that brought him to power, ``while masses who
lost more go without even the basic needs.''
   It also called the president a liar for defending the banker
against allegations he was being paid more than he is worth.
   Allegations were raised in Parliament in September that the
banker earned $331,663 in salary and other, unspecified
renumerations between March 1988 and June 1989.
</TEXT>
