<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--France-Satellite     11-07 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--France-Satellite,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Satellite Begins Charting Stars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A European satellite launched Aug. 8 has recovered
from an early failure of its booster and has been reprogrammed to
provide accurate measurements of 100,000 stars, the European Space
Agency said Tuesday.
   Named Hipparcos after an ancient Greek astronomer, the satellite
failed to reach its planned geostationary orbit and has had to
undergo a complex revision of its mission involving ground stations
in French Guyana, West Germany and Australia.
   The further use of a U.S. ground station is being contemplated,
bringing the satellite's coverage to about 93 percent of the area
originally planned.
   The life of the satellite in its revised orbit is likely to be
limited by the reduction of electricity generated by its solar
cells, the agency said.
   The agency said it would give an evaluation of Hipparcos'
performance next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
