<DOCNO> AP891107-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-ELN--ElectionsRdp Bjt   11-07 1069</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Elections Rdp, Bjt,1100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Democrats Seek Historic Victories in Virginia, New York City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls Close At 7 p.m. EST in Virginia, 8 in New Jersey, 9 in
New York; Material below the dash will stand.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing, LaserGraphic Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   L. Douglas Wilder of Virginia, the grandson of slaves, bid to
become the nation's first elected black governor Tuesday, and
fellow Democrat David Dinkins sought triumph as New York City's
first black mayor in off-year elections enlivened by the
combustible mix of race and abortion.
   Rep. James Florio was the heavy favorite to defeat Rep. James
Courter in the New Jersey governor's race and reclaim the office
for the Democrats after eight years of Republican control.
   In the sole congressional seat on the ballot, 11 candidates vied
to fill out the term of the late Rep. Mickey Leland of Texas,
killed in a plane crash last summer in Ethiopia.
   Wilder, his state's lieutenant governor, battled former attorney
general J. Marshall Coleman in a contest in the old capital of the
Confederacy that focused more on abortion than race.
   Dinkins, the 62-year-old Manhattan borough president, ran as the
man who could bring racial harmony to the Big Apple. Rudolph
Giuliani, 45 and a former U.S. Attorney making his first try for
elective office, hammered away at his rival's transfer of stock to
a son and his failure to file income-tax returns for four years two
decades ago.
   Big-city mayors on the ballot included Coleman Young in Detroit
and Kathy Whitmire in Houston, each seeking their fifth term; Don
Fraser in Minneapolis seeking his fourth and Xavier Suarez in
Miami, going after his third.
   Cleveland picked a new black mayor, choosing between City
Council President George Forbes and state Sen. Michael R. White in
a particularly bitter race. Forbes called his rival a ``slumlord.''
White said his opponent was a ``master of sleaze.''
   Democrat John Daniels was heavily favored to become the first
black mayor in majority-white New Haven, Conn.
   In Seattle, city councilman Norm Rice battled opponent Doug
Jewett in his drive for a similar distinction.
   Ben Nichols, a socialist, was favored to win election as mayor
of Ithaca, N.Y.
   Michigan decided the fate of two competing plans to raise the
state sales tax for education, one calling for a half-penny
increase and the other a two-cent rise.
   The Maine ballot included an advisory measure to ban cruise
missile testing in the state, while San Francisco, in danger of
losing its Giants baseball franchise, decided whether to build a
new $115 million stadium to replace Candlestick Park.
   President Bush campaigned for GOP candidates in Virginia, New
Jersey and New York in an election season that served as prelude to
1990, when 34 Senate seats, 36 governorships and all 435 House
seats will be on the ballot.
   But just as Republicans and Democrats watched the returns for
signs of partisan success, so, too, was the year marked by interest
in abortion and race _ with a heavy dose of negative campaign
commercials thrown in.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The elections were closely watched for clues to shifting voter
sentiment on abortion in the wake of the Supreme Court's ruling
last summer that permits states to restrict the rights of women
seeking to end their pregnancies.
   Bush, in a news conference marking the first anniversary of his
own election, minimized the importance of abortion in this year's
campaign and said people ``are not for the most part single-issue
voters. They care about war and peace, they care about the
environment.''
   Even so, the issue played a role in New Jersey and New York, and
particularly in Virginia, where pro-choice and pro-life groups
bought television commercials to boost Wilder and Coleman,
respectively.
   In all three races, Republican candidates were thrown on the
defensive by their pro-choice opponents.
   Wilder made the issue the cornerstone of his candidacy, running
television commercials in October that accused Coleman of wanting
to ``take away your right to choose and give it to the
politicians,'' even on abortions in cases of incest and rape.
   His campaign challenged a decade of conventional political
wisdom which held that abortion was an issue best ignored by a
pro-choice candidate and best exploited by one with right-to-life
views.
   Courter and Giuliani both softened their original pro-life
positions as the campaigns wore on.
   The issue of race was largely silent in Virginia until the final
days, when Coleman suggested his rival had been the beneficiary of
a ``double standard'' in press coverage. Wilder's rebuttal:
campaigning on Saturday with a woman who said she was originally a
Coleman supporter, but changed her mind after his comments.
   The current governor, Democrat Gerald L. Baliles, is barred by
state law from seeking a second consecutive term.
   The New York race was to succeed three-term Mayor Ed Koch.
Dinkins defeated the outgoing mayor in a primary in which he
depicted himself as the man capable of calming the racial
antagonism that often flares in the city.
   Giuliani, who established a natiional reputation as a prosecutor
of white-collar criminals, said Dinkins needed to be investigated
for his failure to pay income taxes and for allegedly covering up
the details of a stock tranfer to his son.
   ``I don't want someone voting for me because I am white,'' he
said. I don't think that's right. And I think the same thing is
true of my opponent. No one should vote for him because he's
black.''
   Dinkins replied, ``I ask that nobody vote for me because I an
African-American, but I ask as well that nobody vote against me
because I am an African-American.''
   The New Jersey race was between two men who couldn't have been
less alike.
   Florio, the liberal Democrat, lost a gubernatorial primary in
1977 and came within 1,700 votes of winning the governor's job in
1981. The man who beat him, Thomas Kean, is stepping down after two
terms as required by the state Constitution.
   Courter, a conservative Republican was making his first try for
statewide office.
   Their race was nasty for weeks.
   Florio struck with campaign commercials in October that showed
Courter's nose growing longer and longer as a narrator ticked off a
series of alleged lies and misleading statements.
   Courter lashed back with a variation on the same theme: the
faces of the two men side by side, Florio's nose growing longer and
longer and his own shorter and shorter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-Bush-Text 3rdAdd   11-07 0956</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush-Text, 3rd Add,940</SECOND>
<TEXT>
   WASHN: to accept.
   Q: May I follow up on the abortion. ...
   A: How many follow-ups do you get? (Laughter.)
   Q: This is my follow-up. In the China family planning program,
the American money would not have anything to do with abortion, and
also in the D.C. bill that you vetoed, the federal money would not
go to abortion. You seem to be saying you want to affect the policy
beyond the federal role.
   A:Well, look, there are many issues, and abortion divides. We
have room in our party for people that feel one way, pro-life or
pro-choice. The Democratic Party is the same way. I think everyone
knows that this is an issue that divides. But you say, is it the
most important issue for me? Absolutely not.
   Yes?
   Q: You're probably ready for this one, but you campaigned as an
environmentalist and said you were a strong environmentalist. Yet
on the issue of global warming, it seems that the U.S. is being
dragged kicking and screaming into trying to address this problem.
How do you respond to that?
   A: I respond to it by saying it's not true.
   Q: Why are you resisting the moves in this international
conference now?
   A: We're just standing off against extremes. We have a unanimous
communique out of that global conference. We have an outstanding
environmentalist in Bill Reilly. We have an outstanding scientist
in Dr. Bromley. They agree that our approach to all of this is
right. And I think we cannot be _ this policy of the environment
cannot be driven by the extremes. But I would like to take your
question to challenge the United States Congress to go forward on
the revisions to the Clean Air Act, on other initiatives that we
have supported, instead of sitting back there and carping about it.
And if they don't like our way, go ahead and try it and then add to
it in later years. But they sit there and argue back and forth with
each other, and nothing happens.
   In this global conference, I can tell you United States' science
is the best in terms of global warming. And we will be in the lead
as we are now with our science on global warming. But you can't
take a policy and drive it to the extreme and say to every country
around the world, ``You aren't going to grow at all.'' We've got to
use our science to help solve this problem.
   Yes, back there _ these two in the middle.
   Q: Mr. President, the gubernatorial campaigns, as you know, in
New Jersey and Virginia were dominated by the abortion issue. Some
pro-choice Republicans are disturbed with your current position.
What advice are you going to give Republicans legislators and
congressional candidates next year when the Democrats start
pounding on them on this issue?
   A: Well, they've already started. Those who favor _ favor the
pro-choice have already started pounding on them, and started
certainly pounding on me. But you see, one, I think our party is
broad enough to contain differing views on this. Secondly _ and I
think the Democratic Party is. You see that. You see that out there
in practice.
   Secondly, I don't believe that most voters are single issue
voters. There is no evidence to support that. None at all. Indeed _
I hate to talk about polls, because I don't believe them when I see
ugly things _ but I can tell you that that issue ranks about 9th to
14th, if you talk to a pollster like Bob Teeter. I can't remember
whether it was 14th or 9th, so I'm giving you a range there. But
people are not, for the most part, single issue voters. They care
about war and peace. They care about the environment. They care
about education. They care about anti-narcotics. They care about
crime in their neighborhoods. So when you see all this attention to
this question, I happen to think it's those that are
editorializing, the columnists, or some in the political arena that
think the voter is a one-issue voter. I don't agree with that, and
I've seen no evidence.
   Q: But if Republicans cling to the hope that you might change
your position, are they wrong that you're going to. ...
   A: I have no intention of changing my position. It's _ it's so
personal. It's so _ um _ I just come down more on the side of life.
I mentioned in my speech last year at the _ a year-plus ago _ of
adoption and what it's meant. And _ but I _ look, I don't fault
people that view this differently. As I say, there's a _ plenty of
room for difference. But it's not one, John, where people are as
single-issue, as you would _ as some would like to believe.
   Yes, Ellen?
   Q: Mr. President, your predecessor, Ronald Reagan, just came
back from a trip to Japan, where he collected $2 million for his
speaking engagements. Eventually, you're going to be an
ex-president. Is that the kind of behavior that you anticipate
yourself endorsing _ (laughter) _ accepting that kind of money?
   A: I will not have anything negative to say about President
Reagan _ if that's an invitation for this _ because I prefer to
emphasize the positive _ positive parts of that trip, talking
openly about the need for freer trade, the affection shown to him
by the Japanese people. It's important symbolism when it comes to
the _ when it comes to this relationship that sometimes has strain.
And what happens in the future? I don't know.
   Yes?
   Q: Excuse me, a follow up, sir?
   MORE
