<HEAD>Bush Says He Is Willing to Meet with Shamir</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Bush comments, picks up 6th graf pvs, There
is. Trims last 2 grafs as redundant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he is willing to
meet with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir so long as the two
sides have ``something positive to talk about'' on the U.S. pln for
Mideast talks.
   Bush said he didn't know if or when Shamir intends to visit
Washington, but he is ``certainly willing to consider'' a meeting.
   Israel has given its qualified acceptance of the proposal by
Secretary of State James A. Baker III for talks between Israelis
and Palestinians.
   Israel is asking for a half-dozen assurances, including a U.S.
promise to quit the talks if Israel walks out. Bush officials are
now looking for word from Egypt and the Palestine Liberation
Organization on their stands.
   Bush said Shamir is making a ``real effort'' to support the
Baker plan. As for a meeting, he said, ``I'd like to feel that ...
it would be constructive, that we'd have something positive to talk
about.''
   Under the Baker plan, talks between the Israelis and the
Palestinians are supposed to set the stage for an election on the
West Bank and in Gaza. The Palestinians elected in the territories
would negotiate five years of limited self-rule with the Israeli
government.
   ``There is still much to do and many details to be worked out
before it would be possible to put together a pre-election
dialogue,'' State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said. ``For
now, we look forward to receiving an Egyptian response.''
   Egypt's role is to convey the position of the Palestine
Liberation Organization. Without PLO acquiescence, Palestinians on
the West Bank and in Gaza are unlikely to participate in Shamir's
election plan.
   Boucher said Israel's acceptance of the U.S. plan was ``a very
positive step ... a clear step forward.''
   But Yossi Ahimeir, a spokesman for Shamir, said after the
Cabinet action that without the assurances ``we will not enter into
these talks.''
   The Israeli demands include exclusion of the PLO and all of its
members from the deliberations.
   Boucher and other U.S. officials did not close the door on the
Israeli demands. Referring to them as ``assumptions,'' he said:
   ``We know that both Israel and Egypt are likely to request
certain clarifications or understandings about the process. We have
made clear to both sides that we're prepared to discuss these
issues.''
