<FIRST>r p AM-ELN--BuffaloMayoral     11-07 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Buffalo Mayoral,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Four Parties Behind Him, Mayor Awaits Victory Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 9 p.m. EST; material below dash should stand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor James D. Griffin, running with the
endorsements of four parties, was a virtual shoo-in for re-election
Tuesday to his fourth, four-year term _ an unprecedented
achievement in New York's second-largest city.
   The only opposition faced by Griffin came from Liberal Party
candidate William Hoyt, a state assmemblyman who remained on the
ballot despite dropping out of the race after losing the Demoractic
nomination, and Wilbur Trammell, a former city court judge on whose
behalf a write-in campaign is being mounted.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Griffin, 60, had the Democratic, Republican, Conservative and
Right-to-Life nominations. Trammelll and Hoyt finished behind
Griffin in September's Democratic Party primary.
   In his campaign, Griffin emphasized major downtown redevelopment
_ including several new office buildings and hotels, waterfront
condominiums and Pilot Field, the city's highly-praised baseball
stadium.
   A former worker in the city's grain elevators, Griffin lost his
first election for city councilman in 1959, but was subsequently
elected to the state Senate.
   An enrolled Democrat, Griffin nonetheless has never been a
favorite of the Erie County Democratic Party. In becoming mayor in
1977, he beat out the party's challenger, Assemblyman Arthur O.
Eve, by running with the Conservative Party endorsement.
   In his last election in 1985, Griffin again beat out the
Democratic Party's challenger, city councilman George Arthur. This
time, he ran with the Republican Party endorsement.
</TEXT>
