<FIRST>r p AM-ELN--CharlotteMayor     11-07 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Charlotte Mayor,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charlotte's First Woman Mayor Tries for Second Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 7:30 p.m. EST; material below the dash should
stand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sue Myrick, the first woman
mayor of North Carolina's largest city, tried to retain her seat
Tuesday against one Democrat who has never held political office
and another who became the focus of a write-in campaign.
   Craig Madans, 37, became the Democratic nominee last month when
city councilman Al Rousso, the only other candidate, dropped out of
the race. But Rousso resurfaced as a write-in candidate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In 1987, Myrick unseated two-term incumbent Harvey Gantt by a
995-vote margin on a campaign pledge to improve Charlotte's clogged
road system. Last year, she successfully led a campaign for a $100
million highway bond issue.
   Deeply religious, Myrick, 48, has said she makes political
decisions by listening to ``the will of God first, the will of the
people second.''
   Madans, a textile executive who has never held political office,
criticized Myrick's handling of the Hurricane Hugo cleanup and her
``lone wolf'' style on some issues.
   Myrick criticized Madans' admitted use of marijuana and cocaine
during his college days in a campaign that became increasingly
bitter. In the final days of the campaign, she refused to talk to
reporters.
</TEXT>
