<FIRST>r p AM-ELN--ClevelandMayor     11-07 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Cleveland Mayor,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Blacks Competing in Tuesday's Cleveland Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 7:30 p.m. EST; material below dash should stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters were given an unprecedented choice
between two black candidates Tuesday in an election to pick a
successor to popular Mayor George Voinovich.
   The two hopefuls, City Council President George Forbes and his
youthful former aide, state Sen. Michael White, fought a bruising
campaign that was notable as much for its nastiness as its
historical significance.
   Forbes accused White of being a slumlord and of beating two
former wives, while White denounced Forbes as a ``master of
sleaze.''
   The non-partisan race between the two Democrats was made
possible when Voinovich decided to step aside to seek the 1990
Republican nomination for governor.
   Dayton, Toledo and Youngstown were among the other Ohio cities
choosing mayors Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Cleveland's first black mayor was Carl Stokes, who won office in
1967. Stokes, who served one term and subsequently became a
municipal judge, briefly considered running for mayor this year.
   He didn't, and Forbes and White finished first and second in an
Oct. 3 primary that included three white candidates. In a city
nearly evenly split between whites and blacks, the two focused much
of their campaigning on the city's predominantly white west side.
   The five-week campaign epitomized Cleveland's bare-knuckle style
of politics. White, 38, who has been married three times, defended
himself against allegations by his first two wives that he beat
them. He also was put on the defensive when 200 city code
violations were found in seven houses he owned.
   Forbes, 59, defended himself against charges of ethical
conflicts involving his City Hall duties and his private law
practice, and brushed aside allegations that police and other city
workers were defying the city charter by becoming personally
involved in the campaign on his behalf.
</TEXT>
