<DOCNO> AP891107-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-Bush-Glance     11-07 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush-Glance,590</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights from
President Bush's news conference Tuesday.
   
   YEAR IN REVIEW
   
   On the eve of the first anniversary of his election, Bush said
he was ``pleased that our administration has come together rapidly
with good people and with good ideas and a quiet sense of purpose.''
   Internationally, he said that ``important decisions have been
made for freedom and we've supported those movements.''
   Domestically, Bush said he was more convinced than ever ``that
we can ... give hope to the homeless and help to the needy,
inspiration to millions of Americans who want to reach out and help
their neighbors.''
   ``I enjoy it,'' he said of being president.
   
   HOSTAGES
   
   Bush said he hoped the decision to return $567 million in frozen
Iranian assets will get the ``underbrush cleaned out'' and lead
eventually to freedom for Americans held hostage by Iranian-backed
forces in Lebanon.
   He said he hoped Iranian officials ``will do what they can'' to
influence the hostage-holders and said the United States was
``continuing behind the scenes to follow rabbit trails'' in hopes
of winning freedom for the hostages.
   
   ABORTION
   
   Asked about his vetoes of legislation expanding the conditions
under which Medicaid funds can finance abortions, he said, ``I have
no intention of changing my position. It's so personal. I just come
down on the side of life.''
   Asked about the emergence of abortion as a major issue in
Tuesday's gubernatorial elections in Virginia and New Jersey, Bush
said, ``People are not for the most part single-issue voters.''
   
   NEGATIVE CAMPAIGNING
   
   Asked about the role of negative campaign commercials in
Tuesday's elections, Bush said he believes ``the American people
have a way of sorting out what's fair and what's not fair, what's
ugly and what's not ugly.''
   He said he hoped future elections would be ``a little more
positive.''
   
   RELATIONS WITH CONGRESS
   
   Bush said he would ``veto and exhort'' Congress until he gets
action on his legislative programs and, asking, ``What else can I
do?'' blamed Democrat majorities in the House and the Senate for an
impasse on reducing the federal deficit.
   Bush conceded Democrats ``have the votes'' to have forced him to
pull back his plan to reduce capital-gains taxes but pledged,
``I'll be ready come the fall of 1990.''
   
   EASTERN EUROPE
   
   Reacted to a comment Monday from ex-President Carter that he was
slow in his response to Eastern European pro-democracy movements by
challenging critics to produce specific proposals ``other than
triple the spending'' to aid those movements.
   He said he felt that his cautious approach had the support of
allied leaders in Western Europe and that ``I don't think you can
contain now the people's aspirations for freedom by going back to
totalitarianism.''
   
   RELATIONS WITH MOSCOW
   
   Bush said he could not say ``everything is hunky dory'' until he
is convinced the Soviet government has reined in its defense budget
and expansionist desires. Bush said he would raise those issues
when he meets with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev next month.
   
   GLOBAL WARMING
   
   The president said the United States was not joining a call by
more than 60 nations for capping carbon monoxide emisisons by the
year 2000 because ``this policy of the environment cannot be driven
by extremes.'' He called on Congress to expedite action on his
proposed rewriting of the Clean Air Act.
   
   LEBANON
   
   Bush said that followers of Lebanese strongman Michel Aoun were
``totally out of order'' in forcing the country's Maronite Catholic
patriarch, Bishop Nasrallah butros Sfeir, to kiss a picture of Aoun
a day after the patriarch endorsed a Moslem-Christian accord
opposed by Aoun.
   
   QUAYLE
   
   Said he would not say if he would seek re-election in 1992 but,
if he does, Quayle was ``my choice'' as his running mate.
</TEXT>
