<HEAD>New Haven Expected To Elect First Black Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 8 p.m. EST; material below dash should stand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat John Daniels, a five-term state
senator, was heavily favored Tuesday to defeat Republican
Alderwoman Robie Pooley and become the first black mayor of this
overwhelmingly Democratic city.
   Also in the race for mayor was a Green Party candidate, Matthew
Borentein.
   In Hartford, Mayor Carrie Saxon Perry, also a Democrat, was
expected to easily win re-election to her second term. Her
Republican opponent was Rosemary Z. Cardwell.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Daniels, 53, entered the race for mayor a month before the
incumbent, five-term Mayor Biagio DiLieto, announced he would not
seek a sixth term.
   In the primary, he faced a former top city administrator, John
DeStefano, who managed to narrowly win his party's endorsement
despite a lack of political experience.
   A majority owner of a plumbing business and a college football
referee, Daniels ran a campaign of what he called inclusion,
describing himself as the candidate who could best bring the city's
diverse neighborhoods together.
   He raised about $400,000 in contributions, a record for a
mayoral race, loaning his campaign $88,000 of his own money.
   Democrats outnumber Republicans by nearly 10-to-1 in this city
of 127,000, where blacks make up about 35 percent and Hispanics
about 12 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
