<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Films     11-07 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Films,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banned Films From 1960s to be Shown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All films made in the 1960s and
banned after Soviet tanks crushed the ``Prague Spring'' reforms in
1968 will be shown in Czechoslovakia, the Communist Party newspaper
said Tuesday.
   Government cultural officials were quick to add, however, that
the decision was not meant to rehabilitate the liberalization
period.
   The decision to ban the films ``was motivated especially by the
needs of (political) consolidation after the years of crisis in
1968-69,'' the party daily Rude Pravo said.
   ``This decision, however, does not mean any kind of reversal in
our distribution policy, reappraisal of historical events or the
films themselves,'' Rude Pravo said.
   During the 196Os, ``the Czech wave'' of young filmmakers
represented by Milos Forman and Jiri Menzel swept Europe, winning
two Oscars for ``Closely Observed Trains'' and ``Shop On Main
Street.''
   After the Soviet-led invasion in August 1968, Forman decided to
live in the United States, where he scored successes with ``One
Flew Over The Cuckoo's Nest'' and ``Amadeus.'' Menzel fought a long
battle with authorities at home.
   ``This move is certainly a positive one, albeit a little bit
belated,'' said Jan Foll, a film historian and member of a
commission which managed to lift the ban this summer.
   ``This ... leaves the drawers clean, there are no films banned
anymore,'' said Alois Humplik of the Czechoslovak Film Distributing
Agency.
   To many moviegoers in Czechoslovakia, the 1960s still represent
``the golden era'' of arts and culture. Film production has been
received with much less enthusiasm in the last 20 years.
   Eleven of the old films will be shown in general distribution,
while 13 others will be shown in film clubs throughout the country,
the daily said.
   Among them will be ``The Party And The Guests'' directed by Jan
Nemec and featuring Zdena Salivarova and writer Josef Skvorecky.
   The decision ``will make it possible for a better and more
objective determining of values inside and outside the times, will
strip them of the smell of cheap sensation and myth, while
contributing to an objective view on the rich and complex period of
the sixties in our film,'' said Hviezdoslav Stefan, director of the
Czechoslovak Film Institute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-ELN--SeattleMayor     11-07 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Seattle Mayor,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slight Edge to Black Candidate in Seattle Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 11 p.m. EST; material below dash will stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Councilman Norm Rice, seeking to become
Seattle's first black mayor, faced City Attorney Doug Jewett on
Tuesday in an election dominated by an anti-busing school
initiative.
   Jewett helped draft Initiative 34, dubbed ``Save Our Schools''
by supporters, and made it the prime vehicle of his campaign to
become Seattle's first Republican elected mayor in 24 years.
   Also on the ballot in municipal elections around Washington
state were races between Tim Strege and Karen Vialle for mayor of
Tacoma and Sheri Bernard and Rob Higgins for Spokane mayor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Seattle's anti-busing measure went from a commanding lead in
early polls to a 50-50 proposition a week before the election under
a fierce attack from city, state and school officials in this city
of 500,000.
   The initiative asked but did not require the independently
elected and self-budgeting city School Board to halt mandatory
busing of students for racial balance. In exchange, about $4.3
million to $4.5 million in city tax revenue would be earmarked for
``magnet'' programs to attract a racial balance in school
enrollment.
   In the officially nonpartisan contest to succeed Mayor Charles
Royer in Seattle, Rice trumpeted his Democratic party credentials,
including endorsements from Royer, Gov. Booth Gardner, the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, U.S. Rep. Jim McDermott and virtually all of the
city's state legislators.
   Jewett, a maverick moderate who briefly supported former Rep.
John Anderson for president in 1980 and once tried to form a third
political party, downplayed his GOP affiliation.
   The two were allies in their first political forays, with Rice
supporting Jewett for election as the city's chief legal officer in
1977 and Jewett supporting Rice for one of the nine City Council
seats the next year.
   Royer, who did not seek re-election to a fourth term, has
accepted a job as director of the Institute of Politics at the John
F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
