<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TeacherTraining     11-07 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Training,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Integrated Curriculum Could Recruit More Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Association of American Colleges said
Tuesday that institutions of higher education can help alleviate a
shortage of qualified teachers by more aggressively attracting
undergraduates to the profession.
   ``Few institutions are trying seriously to recruit large numbers
of more able students into teaching or provide them with more
challenging and substantive programs,'' said Joseph Johnston,
association vice president for programs.
   More liberal arts majors could be recruited if colleges and
universities combined undergraduate arts and science programs with
education courses, the association said.
   Education courses also should be added to the general-education
curriculum, which is usually taken in the first two years of
college before the student declares a major, the group said.
   By adding an education course, colleges and universities might
recruit students who have not seriously considered teaching, or who
even have ``some aversion'' to it.
   Integrating non-education courses with education training will
produce ``bright, broadly educated'' graduates with ``command both
of the subjects to be taught and of the ways in which they can be
taught effectively,'' said Johnston.
   The suggestions in the association study, ``Those Who Can:
Undergraduate Programs to Prepare Arts and Sciences Majors for
Teaching,'' differ from two influential 1986 studies by the
Carnegie Corp. of New York's Task Force on Teaching as a Profession
and by the Holmes Group.
   The earlier studies recommended prospective teachers be required
to earn an undergraduate degree in an academic discipline before
undertaking professional training at the graduate level.
   The Department of Education predicts the demand for new public
school teachers will rise from 128,000 in 1988 to 174,000 in 1995.
Only 8.8 percent of the 1988 first-year students plan to pursue
careers in elementary or secondary schools.
   As recently as 1980, 34 percent of new college graduates who
were certified to teach had completed baccalaureate degrees in the
arts and sciences. By 1984, that number had fallen to 19 percent,
the report said.
   Johnston said the association's report, supported by the
Rockefeller Foundation, is the result of a three-year study that
included a national survey of four-year institutions with
teacher-certification programs for arts and sciences majors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
