considered negative. I don't have to stand here and defend the
campaign of 1988. I'd be perfectly prepared to do it, but I was
elected. I put confidence in the American people, their ability to
sort through what is fair and what is unfair, what is ugly and what
is unugly. And be as positive as possible, but while people were
running around, you know, in campaigns talking about _ talking
about ads this year _ the candidates have been out there taking
their case on various _ various issues out there. So, I _ I think
we're _ I think there's a little bit of a Beltway syndrome here in
terms of this intense focus on negativism. And, yet, if their trend
is that way, maybe I can have a role in seeing that it gets a
little more positive.
   Q: How would you do that?
   A: Well, say I think it ought to be a little more positive.
(Laughter). I mean, what else can you do? I'm certainly not going
to legislate it, and certainly not going to try to dictate to a
candidate how he or she, you know, reacts in a certain situation.
