<HEAD>Eds: Deletes extraneous word `would' in 6th graf, The president</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in an election-anniversary
news conference, claimed a successful start for his presidency on
Tuesday and voiced hope that the return of $567 million in frozen
assets to Iran will eventually help lead to freedom for American
hostages in Lebanon.
   The president said he would ``veto and exhort'' Congress until
he gets action on his legislative programs, exclaiming, ``What else
can I do?'' as he blamed Democrat majorities in both House and
Senate for an impasse on reduing the federal deficit.
   Much of the session revolved around complicated foreign policy
matters as Bush dismissed criticism _ most recently from former
President Carter _ of his policies toward eastern Europe. He said
the administration is dealing properly with the tumultuous changes
there, and that his opponents just want to spend more money on aid.
   Bush returned to the podium after ending the televised news
conference to rebuke militant Christians in Lebanon for grabbing a
Catholic patriarch at his home and manhandling him for endorsing a
compromise political accord.
   He said that behavior was ``totally out of order'' and urged
that all foreign forces be withdrawn from Lebanon and warring
factors be reconciled.
   The president said the release of Iranian funds might get
``underbrush cleaned out.''
   ``I carry the fate of the hostages with me every single day,''
Bush told reporters. He said he knew of no reason to be encouraged
at this time, however, on an issue that has bedeviled his
predecessors and complicated the first 10 months of his term.
   Bush arrived with a statement marking Wednesday's anniversary of
his election and saying ``we've had so far a successful first year
in office.''
   ``I enjoy it; I like the challenge,'' he said of his 10 months
in office.
   Later, in response to a question about today's off-year
elections, Bush said he hoped future campaigns would be ``a little
more postive.''
   Asked about the emergence of abortion as a critical issue in
gubernatorial elections being held in Virginia and New Jersey, Bush
asserted ``that issue ranks about 9th to 14th.''
   ``People are not for the most part single-issue voters,'' Bush
said of an issue that often seemed to cut against Republicans
during the campaign period. He added, ``I have no intention of
changing my position. It's so personal. I just come down on the
side of life.''
   Bush recently vetoed two spending bills over a provision
expanding the use of federal Medicaid funds to pay for abortions
for poor women in cases of rape or incest. ``It supports compulsory
abortion,'' he said. ``I am not going to do that.''
   Currently, such funds can be used only if the mother's life is
in danger.
   Bush rejected criticism that he has failed to exert leadership
in wordwide efforts to combat global warming. He said he was not
prepared to join some 60 nations meeting in The Netherlands on a
resolution to cap carbon dioxide emissions by the year 2000 saying
such a move is too early and too extreme.
</TEXT>
