<HEAD>Florio Enters New Jersey Election With Big Lead in Polls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 8 p.m. EST; material below dash will stand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Rep. James Florio, who lost the
closest governor's race in New Jersey history eight years ago,
entered Tuesday's election confident he would reverse his fortunes
and beat Republican Rep. James Courter in an unusually nasty
contest.
   Election officials said voter turnout around the state ranged
from moderate to heavy, and was especially strong in Florio's home
district of Camden.
   The race to succeed Republican Gov. Thomas H. Kean was Courter's
first and Florio's third. In the final weekend, Florio, an
eight-term congressman, held a 24-point lead in an independent poll
that gave him a better than 2-to-1 advantage among independent
voters.
   As he grew increasingly confident of his lead, Florio devoted
most of his campaign stops to key Assembly districts where close
battles were waged for control of the Legislature's 80-member lower
house, where the Republicans held a 41-39 margin.
   At stake was control of the Legislature which will control
redrawing congressional districts after the 1990 census.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Florio, 52, ran fourth in the 1977 Democratic primary, and lost
the 1981 general election to Kean by 1,797 votes out of nearly 2.3
million cast, a margin of less than one-twelfth of 1 percent. Kean
is barred by state law from seeking a third consecutive term.
   Political observers said Florio softened a brusque and aloof
personality that hurt him in 1981, and ran a nearly flawless
campaign that kept Courter on the defensive. Courter, 48, appeared
troubled by internal disarray and stumbled on delicate issues, such
as abortion and homosexual rights.
   Abortion entered the campaign after the U.S. Supreme Court
ruling in July gave states more power to restrict abortions.
   Florio, who once opposed abortion, immediately condemned the
erosion of abortion rights. It took Courter weeks to remold his
long-held anti-abortion stand and assure New Jersey's largely
pro-choice electorate that he would not impose his personal views
on voters.
   Each gubernatorial candidate spent $5 million, the maximum
permitted under the state's public financing law. Most was spent on
television commercials in the costly New York and Philadelphia
markets as the candidates exchanged charges over the environment,
corruption and taxes.
   Florio, and then Courter, accused each other of repeatedly lying
on the campaign trail. Both ran commercials showing their
opponent's nose growing like that of Pinocchio.
   Florio, who wrote the federal Superfund cleanup law, repeatedly
attacked Courter's environmental record in Congress and the
Republican's plan to cut premiums by deregulating the insurance
industry to increase competition.
   Courter called for changes in New Jersey's death penalty law and
promised to fight for tough laws to combat illegal drugs. Florio
said the current capital punishment law was adequate.
</TEXT>
