<FIRST>r a AM-FalwellMagazine     11-07 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Falwell Magazine,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Falwell to Stop Publication of Monthly Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNCHBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell has decided to stop
publication of his monthly Fundamentalist Journal with the December
issue, a spokesman says.
   The magazine, started by Falwell in 1982, ``did not make money
and it's not something that Rev. Falwell was willing to personally
put in the time and energy to make the magazine stand on its own,''
the spokesman, Mark DeMoss, said.
   Circulation, paid and unpaid, was about 70,000, he said. He was
unable to give a percentage of paid subscribers. A year's
subscription, 11 issues, cost $14.95.
   DeMoss said it cost about $750,000 a year to publish the
magazine.
   The magazine staff was told of the decision Monday, DeMoss said.
The five people involved with the magazine probably will be laid
off, he said.
   The Moral Majority, which Falwell founded, stopped publishing
its monthly newsletter when it was disbanded earlier this year.
   Falwell is meeting with other officials this month to discuss
the future direction of the ministry, which has been making
financial cuts this year, despite what officials say are record
revenues approaching $135 million.
   More than 500 jobs have been terminated since January.
   ``He's asked that his staff evaluate everything we're doing to
determine how strategically each operation relates to one of three
areas _ Thomas Road Baptist Church, Old Time Gospel Hour and
Liberty University _ and furthermore, our goal is that everything
we do in these three areas have some impact on world
evangelization,'' DeMoss said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
