<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1342EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-CouncilConviction     11-07 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Council Conviction,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acting City Council President Convicted of Extortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council's acting president, once
considered a top mayoral prospect, has been convicted of accepting
nearly $48,000 in kickbacks from two businessmen for help in
getting city contracts.
   Ben Woods, 47, resigned from the council hours before a federal
jury convicted him Monday on 17 of 22 counts, including extortion,
racketeering, conspiracy and tax evasion.
   U.S. District Judge Alan N. Bloch ordered Woods to forfeit
$47,727 _ the amount in kickbacks he was convicted of receiving _
under the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations
Act.
   Woods' co-defendant, businessman Michael Hartman, 38, was
convicted of conspiracy, racketeering and filing false corporate
tax returns. Hartman's firm, Ablebuilt Construction Co., was
convicted of racketeering.
   The racketeering and extortion counts alone carry 20 years in
prison each. Woods' sentencing was set for Jan. 17.
   Woods was accused of taking $19,600 from Hartman to help the
contractor get city housing contracts and expedite payments on a
project. Prosecutors also alleged Woods accepted $36,727 from
Joseph Wozniak, a businessman who testified for the government, to
help Wozniak sell concrete sealants to city agencies.
   Woods was elected acting council president in May 1988 when
Sophie Masloff left the post to become mayor upon the death of
Richard Caliguiri.
   In resigning, Woods said the time had come to turn the council
over to ``others whose personal matters do not detract from the
critical issues facing the people of Pittsburgh.''
</TEXT>
