<DOCNO> AP891107-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-JamesReston Bjt   11-07 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-James Reston, Bjt,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>After 34 Years of Columns, Some Lingering Thoughts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Timesman James Reston, sage of
American journalism, says he doesn't join those who wring their
hands and ask where the giants of yesterday are. He was around, he
says, when the giants were Hitler and Stalin. He's had enough of
giants.
   Reston does wonder, as he retires, what happened to the idea
that people in government were supposed to set the standards, not
just shrug off their misdeeds with an ``everbody-does-it.''
   He's not surprised that George Bush is turning out to be a
cautious president.
   ``You get from George about what you see,'' he says. ``I know
that family. I lived up the street from his mother and father for
10 years. George is not the kind of guy to run a revolution, but he
won't do anything stupid.''
   Reston does raise an eyebrow over the president's weekend
declaration that he would run again with Dan Quayle if he decides
himself to seek re-election.
   ``If presidents go on choosing people like Dan Quayle and
telling us they're the best available, you're bound to have
problems,'' Reston says.
   After all, he points out, a country of two or three million
``produced Mr. Jefferson and Mr. Washington and Ben Franklin. I
can't believe we're getting anything like the best people in
government today.''
   Reston retired Friday, on his 80th birthday, half a century
after he joined the Times. He is writing a book of memoirs.
   He's an old sportswriter, and fond of saying so. He started for
the Springfield Daily News, in Ohio, in 1932, for $10 a week and
was a publicity man for Ohio State University in 1933, a traveling
secretary for the Cincinnati Reds in 1934 and an Associated Press
man in, he recalls, a rathole of a bureau in London from 1937 to
1939, when the war was fomenting and the Times hired him away.
   He spent most of the rest of his life observing Washington. For
34 years, what Reston's column said was important to Washington. He
did his own thinking, took the long view, was generally optimistic.
He retired without fanfare, but shared some parting ideas in a
telephone interview.
   He doesn't think America suffers from a shortage of great men.
Rather than a giant, he likes people like Harry Truman: ``They knew
what they didn't know.''
   The presidents ``who have gotten in the most trouble in the last
40 or 50 years are those who thought they could do everything on
their own and thought they didn't need a State Department and could
run it out of the White House,'' Reston says.
   ``Look where the giants got us in the world, Stalin and Hitler.
I think we can do without giants. If we just get a lot of pretty
smart guys around and argue it out we've got a better chance of
coming out all right.''
   He would like to see a return to ``the idea that people in
government are supposed to be the models who set the standards for
personal conduct. That idea has kind of gone by the boards for some
reason or other.'' Now, ``they say, `Well, Everybody does it.'''
   Reston doesn't join Ronald Reagan in wishing the 22nd Amendment
could be erased from the Constitution. In his last year in office,
Reagan often said he thought it was a mistake to limit presidents
to two terms.
   ``I don't like the idea of people being in power too long,''
Reston says. ``They tend to get corrupted or lazy.
   ``Reagan ran downhill at the end of his second term. Even Ike
did.'' And in England, Prime Minster Margaret Thatcher, after 10
years in office, ``is beginning to get a little schoolmistressish.''
   Reston says newspapers are better than ever. Competition from
broadcasting has forced them to do what they should _ ``report the
causes and consequences of things, not just the event itself.''
   He says it is healthy when people don't like newspapers.
   ``We're not cheerleaders,'' he says. ``It's our business to
carry the news, the way the mailman carries the mail.''
   But he salutes the power of television to wring changes.
Newspapers wrote about injustice to the blacks for years, but the
pictures of police turning their dogs on demonstrators made the
difference.
   ``If you had TV coverage, the first and second world wars would
have ended sooner,'' he says.
   Television is what's forcing change in Eastern Europe and the
Soviet Union. People there see the rest of the world and begin to
think it's crazy that they ``have to line up for 10 hours to get a
turnip.''
   But the revolution is just beginning, he says. It took a century
and a civil war for America to accommodate to its states' rights
problems.
   ``The Soviet Union is now running into states' rights problems.
It's going to take a long to resolve and, if the Russians can do it
without a civil war, they'll be very lucky.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
