<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Protest     11-07 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Protest,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion-Rights Protesters Disrupt Supreme Court Proceedings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men and two women briefly disrupted
Supreme Court proceedings Tuesday, as they stood up to denounce a
recent high court ruling limiting abortion rights.
   ``The Supreme Court has declared war on women and I'm here to
declare war on the Supreme Court,'' said one of the woman,
according to spectators in the courtroom.
   ``I had an abortion 20 years ago. ...'' said the other woman
before she was led from the courtroom by court police.
   All four were arrested and charged with disrupting the high
court, an offense that carries a 30-day jail sentence and a $100
fine upon conviction, said court spokeswoman Toni House.
   Arrested were Michael Madewell, 27, of Athens, Ga.; Benjamin
Fraser Troxell, 26, of Cleveland Heights, Ohio; Sandra Lines, 41,
of Jersey City, N.J., and Michelle Pahl, 27, of New York City.
   A group called Refuse &amp; Resist distributed a statement that said
the protest was intended to focus attention on the court as ``an
oppressor of women.''
   ``The oppressors of women will know no peace until the dogs are
called off from attacking women's (abortion) clinics,'' the
statement said.
   The court last July 3 gave states new power to limit abortions,
but stopped short of overturning its 1973 ruling that said women
have a constitutional right to abortion.
   Such protests are highly unusual during the normally sedate
court proceedings.
</TEXT>
