<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Chess     11-07 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Chess,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Applies to Rejoin International Chess Federation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCERNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has applied to rejoin the
International Chess Federation after an absence of eight years, a
senior chess official said Tuesday.
   ``It's a return to the fold,'' said the federation's president,
Florencio Campomanes of the Philippines.
   He said Iran would be considered a provisional member of the
124-member federation as soon as it pays its back dues.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomenei, the late Iranian leader, banned
chess following the 1979 revolution. Last fall, however, he said
the game was acceptable so long as it did not involve gambling.
   The general secretary of the Iranian Chess Federation, Khosra
Hirandi, told chess officials that women and men would not be
allowed to play one another, according to Boris Kutin of
Yugoslavia, a member of the international federation's 14-man
executive council.
   Campomanes said Iran would compete with the other countries of
the Middle East.
   ``There was a question of whether it was compatible for Iran to
be in that zone, when Iraq was in the same zone, and Mr. Harandi
said there was no problem from that direction,'' he said.
   Campomanes said the last Iranian to compete in a federation
competition was in 1979, although it continued to pay membership
dues until 1982.
   Casto Abundo of the Philippines, the federation's general
secretary, said he did not know how much the Iranian Chess
Federation owed in unpaid dues.
</TEXT>
