<SECOND>PM-ELN--NJ Governor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0512,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>N.J. Gubernatorial Hopefuls End Campaign with Frantic Dash for Votes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with turnout; PICKS UP 2nd graf
pvs, ``I'm very ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-ELN--Election Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey voters chose between
Democrat James Florio and Republican James Courter for governor
today, with Florio heavily favored for the office he nearly won
eight years ago.
   Turnout was reported moderate in some places to heavy in others,
including Florio's district in southern New Jersey.
   ``It's Jim Florio driving it,'' said Pat Marshall, the
Democratic administrator with the Camden County Board of Elections.
``Let's be honest here _ that's the only issue in Camden County.''
   The two candidates ended their campaigns with vote-seeking
dashes despite Florio's wide lead in the polls.
   ``I'm very comfortable that we've been able to get our message
out, and now of course the goal is to get people out to vote,''
Florio said at an election eve rally Monday at a racetrack in
Cherry Hill.
   The rally, which featured fireworks and a 10-piece rock-jazz
band entertaining 4,000 supporters, brought a raucous end to
Florio's bid to win the job he lost narrowly to Gov. Thomas H. Kean
in 1981.
   Courter continued to dismiss the polls that show him trailing by
24 points.
   ``We have a great state and it's important for all of us to go
to the polls on Tuesday,'' Courter told supporters in Lyndhurst.
``Ignore what some of the pundits are saying, ignore what some of
the pollsters are saying, because people are the ones who vote, not
polls.''
   Florio, who has held a consistent lead in the polls, has widened
the gap to 24 points over Courter, according to a poll released
Sunday by Rutgers University's Eagleton Institute of Politics and
The Star-Ledger of Newark.
   Florio lost to Kean in 1981 by 1,797 votes out of nearly 2.4
million cast, or one-twelfth of 1 percent, the closest margin in
state history.
   Courter's campaign has been mired in internal problems and the
candidate has stumbled on some delicate issues such as abortion and
homosexual rights.
   By contrast, Florio has largely avoided pitfalls and put Courter
on the defensive. A series of nasty television commercials have
marked both campaigns.
   Each candidate ran a commercial in which his opponent's nose
grew a la Pinocchio with every alleged lie or misleading statement
cited in the spot.
   In addition to today's gubernatorial election, also at stake is
the battle for control of the Assembly. Republicans hold a 41-39
edge, and there are hotly contested races in 10 districts.
   The party that wins control of the Legislature also will control
the redrawing of congressional districts after the 1990 census. The
Democrats control the Senate, which does not face election this
year.
</TEXT>
