<FIRST>r w AM-US-Panama 310   11-07 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama, 310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Reports Panama Shooting Incidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Marines and Army soldiers guarding a
military site at Galeta Island near the Panama Canal exchanged
gunfire twice Friday with a small group of unidentified intruders,
the Pentagon reported Tuesday.
   ``There were no known casualties and sweeps conducted in the
area at daybreak revealed no evidence of intruders or hostile
fire,'' Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman told reporters.
   However, one Army MP was taken to the U.S. Army hospital with
arm, leg and head injuries sustained in a fall into barbed wire.
   The Marines first noticed ``unidentified intruders outside the
gate'' Friday evening at the Galeta site, located at the northern
end of the Panama Canal area and connected to the mainland by a
road, Hoffman said.
   About an hour later, he said, ``a group of Marine Guards and
Army MPs (military police) were fired on by a small group of
intruders. The U.S. Marines and soldiers returned the fire.''
   There was a second exchange somewhat later, Hoffman said.
   Pentagon spokeswoman Maj. Kathy Wood said the exchange of
gunfire was the first in months.
   After the failed coup attempt against Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega last month, the top U.S. military commander in the region _
Gen. Maxwell Thurman _ recommended that the rotations of military
personnel be speeded up so that U.S. dependents could be removed
from the area more speedily.
   Hoffman said that no decision had been made on that
recommendation.
   There are about 10,000 U.S. military permanently assigned to
Panama, with slightly more than 2,000 on temporary duty. There also
are about 2,700 U.S. civilian Department of Defense employees, as
well as about 7,700 military dependents and 3,300 civilian DOD
dependents, the Pentagon has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
