<FIRST>r a PM-MasonCanceled 1stLd-Writethru a0610 11-07 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mason Canceled, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0610,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Cancels Jackie Mason's Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comment from ABC executive, ADDS other
shows canceled. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As New Yorkers today decided whether Rudolph
Giuliani will be their mayor, ABC gave Jackie Mason, the
candidate's one-time honorary campaign chairman, bad news _ it
voted out his series.
   ABC said Mason's ``Chicken Soup,'' a new situation comedy in
which he plays a Jewish ex-salesman in love with an Irish-Catholic,
has been canceled. The eighth and final episode airs tonight.
   Mason quit the Giuliani campaign in September over remarks he
made about the GOP candidate's Democratic rival, David Dinkins, who
is black. Among other things, the rabbi-turned-comedian said Jews
would vote for Dinkins out of guilt.
   Mason apologized for his remarks, which were reported by the
Village Voice, and said he had learned that ``what's funny on stage
can be insensitive when it's said off the stage and in the world of
politics. And for my insensitivity, I apologize.''
   Janice Gretemeyer, an ABC spokeswoman, would not say whether the
cancellation was in any way due to the controversy.
   In a statement, Robert A. Iger, ABC Entertainment president,
called Mason's show ``a well-executed program'' but said it didn't
realize ABC's hopes that it would help maintain the network's
ratings strength on Tuesday, ``our key night.'' ``Chicken Soup''
follows the hit ``Roseanne.''
   ``Clearly, we're disappointed that `Chicken Soup' didn't achieve
that objective,'' he said.
   ``Chicken Soup,'' which co-starred Lynn Redgrave as the object
of Mason's affections, had averaged respectable ratings _ an 18.6
rating and a 29 per cent share of the audience in its Tuesday time
slot _ and occasionally landed in the top 15. Each ratings point
represents 921,000 homes.
   The show was the third new series dropped so far this season.
NBC has canceled ``Nutt House'' and CBS its ``The People Next
Door.''
   ABC said ``Coach,'' a comedy that premiered last season and
stars Craig T. Nelson as a college football coach, will succeed
``Chicken Soup'' starting Nov. 21.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
