<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrashTrial     11-07 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Attorney Seeks Jurors With Awareness of Drunken Driving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 potential jurors will be
interviewed starting Wednesday about their awareness of drunken
driving as the trial starts for a man accused of killing 27 people
in a fiery bus crash.
   Larry Mahoney is charged with 83 separate crimes, including 27
counts of murder, for his role in the crash of a church bus on
Interstate 71 on the night of May 14, 1988.
   The prosecution charged that Mahoney was drunk behind the wheel
of his pickup truck traveling the wrong way on the highway when it
slammed into a bus from a Radcliff church returning from an outing
at an amusement park.
   Defense attorney William Summers said he knows that most
potential jurors will have heard of the case, which prompted
national debate over the safety of school buses and the dangers of
drunken drivers.
   ``They know it happened,'' Summers said. ``They know it inflamed
passions and prejudice in them. But despite whatever those are,
that they will at least make a sincere promise to go out of their
way to try and be objective.''
   The prospective jurors will be questioned in three large groups
before individual interviews that Judge Charles Satterwhite has
ordered closed to the public.
   Summers said his ideal juror will have some understanding of how
widespread drinking and driving has become. Potential jurors also
will be asked if they have been convicted of drunken driving.
   Mahoney, 36, pleaded guilty to driving under the influence
several years ago in another case. He currently faces a charge of
driving under the influence in the current proceeding, along with
dozens of assault and wanton endangerment charges for the injuries
to the 40 people who escaped death in the crash.
   After the crash, Mahoney spent several weeks in the hospital and
was then examined at the Kentucky Correctional Psychiatric Center.
He was jailed until until October 1988, when his family put
together enough money and property to post his $540,000 bond.
   Mahoney returned to work at M&amp;T Chemicals in Carrollton and
lives with his parents in nearby Worthville. Mahoney neither drives
nor drinks anymore, Summers said.
   Survivors of the crash, most of whom were members of the First
Assembly of God in Radcliff, are expected to testify at the trial.
People who lost family members in the crash are expected to attend
at least parts of the trial, which could last six weeks or more.
</TEXT>
