<FIRST>r w AM-Kennedy-CivilRights 320   11-07 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kennedy-Civil Rights, 320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kennedy to Launch Civil Rights Fight Against Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy is preparing a
confrontation with President Bush on civil rights by proposing an
update of the 1964 Civil Rights Act that the president has called
unnecessary.
   The legislation that the Massachusetts Democrat plans to file
within weeks would overturn several Supreme Court rulings handed
down in June that made it easier to challenge affirmative action
programs and more difficult for workers to sue their employers for
racial bias.
   Bush said then that the impact of the decisions was being
overblown.
   One highly publicized decision upheld the right of several white
firefighters from Birmingham, Ala., to challenge the department's
minority hiring plan.
   Republican conservatives in the Senate say they will fight the
legislation, particularly if the president sticks by his position.
   ``If the president is committed to a veto, we can sustain a
veto,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, adding that civil
rights advocates want to embarass Bush.
   Kennedy said that Bush isn't sure more legislation is needed.
   ``In my view, the need is obvious,'' Kennedy said. `` A new
national civil rights act will send a strong message that Congress
does not intend to abandon our 25-year-long commitment to civil
rights.''
   Justice Department spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade said the
administration is taking a ``wait-and-see'' attitude.
   ``We haven't come out and said absolutely no to the
legislation,'' she said. ``We don't think the legislation is
absolutely necessary at this time, but once it's proposed we will
not sit back.''
   Kennedy and other lawmakers have been working with a broad array
of civil rights advocates, labor unions and women's groups to craft
a bill that can be introduced in virtually identical form in both
the House and Senate, said Ralph Neas of the Leadership Conference
on Civil Rights.
</TEXT>
