<FIRST>r p AM-ELN--TexasCongressional     11-07 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Texas Congressional,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eleven Vie for Mickey Leland's Congressional Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Polls close at 8 p.m. EST; material below the dash should stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven people vied Tuesday for the congressional
seat left open by the death of Rep. Mickey Leland, whose plane
crashed during a famine relief trip to Africa in August.
   City Councilman Anthony Hall and state Sen. Craig Washington
emerged as front-runners, followed in pre-election polls by state
Reps. Ron Wilson and Al Edwards. All are Democrats.
   The winner will represent one of Texas' most Democratic and
racially mixed districts until the regular election is held in 1990.
   A candidate needed more than 50 percent of the vote to avoid a
runoff, which would be scheduled by the governor.
   Other Democratic candidates included attorney Shirley Fobbs and
businessman Timothy John Hattenbach and Lee Arthur Demas Jr.
   Republicans included attorney Beverly Spenser, businessman Manse
R. Sharpe Jr. and Byron J. Johnson, an education supervisor. Austin
stockbroker Gary Johnson, no relation, was the Libertarian
candidate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The leading candidates differed little on the major campaign
issues: fighting drugs, helping constituents rise out of poverty,
and, to varying degrees, supporting the right to abortions.
   They focused instead on their rivals' behavior.
   Hall accused Washington of failing to pay $17,000 in local
taxes. Washington countered that he was delinquent on only about 10
percent of that amount, and would be paying it before he went to
Congress, if elected.
   Hall was accused of a conflict of interest in taking his family
on two trips paid for by the Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co. As a
councilman, he had voted in favor of HL&amp;P rate increases.
   The 18th Congressional District, created in 1971, has produced
two of the nation's most prominent black members of Congress:
Leland, known for his leadership on famine issues, and predecessor
Barbara Jordan, one of the country's leading stateswomen.
   The district encompasses downtown Houston and the city's poorest
residents in central and northeast Houston. In 1980, 41 percent of
the residents were black and 31 percent Hispanic.
</TEXT>
