<FIRST>r a AM-PakistaniPlot     11-07 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistani Plot,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Defendant Claims Ties to Zia Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug trafficking trial has taken a
startling turn with the defendant testifying he was trying to track
down a drug dealer he says absconded with $500,000 in a plot to
kill Pakistan's former leader.
   The unusual defense, built around Pakistani President Gen.
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq who died in a mysterious plane crash, isn't
something the defendant's lawyer said he would have chosen to take
into the courtroom.
   ``It's not my idea of the best defense believe me,'' Stephen
Ferrarone, court-appointed attorney for Mushtaq Malik, said
Tuesday. ``I would prefer not to have my guy stand up and say, `I
may have been involved in an assassination.'''
   Prosecutors declined comment as they prepared to begin
cross-examination Wednesday.
   The 41-year-old defendant, who prosecutors say is known as ``The
Black Prince,'' stopped short of saying he was involved in the
plane crash that killed Zia on Aug. 17, 1988. Malik was arrested in
Brazil on the drug charges five months before the crash in which 29
other people died, including U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel.
   Malik is being tried on charges of conspiracy and importation of
heroin. Prosecutors claim Malik arranged for Samir N. Houchaimi of
Amman, Jordan, to bring $10 million in heroin to the United States.
   Houchaimi was arrested at a bus terminal in Springfield in
February 1988. He was carrying a nylon handbag filled with two
kilograms of heroin that he told authorities he had been given in
Cyprus to sell for Malik.
   After his arrest, Houchaimi arranged a meeting in Rio de Janeiro
with Malik and a U.S. drug agent operating under the alias ``Mr.
Costa.'' Transcripts of those calls have been introduced as
evidence.
   Malik and the agent met, ostensibly to make plans to go to Costa
Rica, but instead Malik was arrested and returned to the United
States.
   Malik's defense, according to his testimony Monday, is that he
actually had contracted with Houchaimi to kill Zia. Malik testified
he advanced at least $500,000 to Houchaimi on behalf of superiors
in the Pakistan People's Party, currently led by Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto, to hire people and buy equipment for the
assassination.
   Malik said he followed the 51-year-old Houchaimi to the United
States after it became obvious that the plot was stalled. He said
he then played along with drug plans in hopes of retrieving the
money.
   ``I don't know anything about money for heroin in America,'' he
testified Monday.
   ``Malik was basically in a position where he would have been
totally wiped out. He has said that he would either have to come up
with this money or commit suicide,'' Ferrarone said.
   The lawyer said his client doesn't fear retribution for his
testimony of assassination plotting from the current Pakistani
government, which maintains the cause of Zia's death is unknown.
   The Pakistani consulate in Boston did not return a telephone
call to The Associated Press on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
