<FIRST>r w AM-AirTraffic     11-07 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Traffic,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Problem Delays Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second computer problem within a week at the
Washington Air Route Traffic Control Center caused some flight
delays Tuesday, the Federal Aviation Administration reported.
   ``There was never a safety issue,'' said FAA spokeswoman Diane
Spitaliere. ``The worst-case scenario was massive delays, and that
never happened.''
   Officials said a problem with telephone lines caused a computer
at Leesburg, Va., to lose contact with some remote radar
facilities, meaning information about some flights had to be put
into the system manually.
   The problem started in the early morning hours and was corrected
by noon, causing minimal delays in flights, Ms. Spitaliere said.
   She said the FAA was investigating the cause and trying to
determine how it can be prevented from reoccurring.
   Thousands of airline passengers flying into, out of or through
the Washington area encountered long delays Friday when air traffic
controllers at the center lost about half their computer capacity.
   Flights headed for the nation's capital were grounded in various
cities and flights in the air were kept about 25 percent farther
apart, officials said.
</TEXT>
