<FIRST>r a AM-IlliniwekControversy     11-07 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Illiniwek Controversy,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Enter Dispute Over University Indian Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cardinal in last graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's two U.S. senators are on opposite
sides of a dispute over whether a university mascot _ a
headdress-bedecked American Indian chief _ should be discarded as
offensive.
   Chief Illiniwek has been a symbol of the University of Illinois
since 1926, prancing at sporting events and emblazoning clothing,
coffee mugs and other paraphernalia.
   Robert Honig, a pre-law student at the school, began a fight
last month to dump the chief, saying it was an insult to American
Indians.
   ``There is no way we would tolerate someone dressed as an
old-time black slave dancing on the field or someone portraying a
Jew,'' said Honig, who is from suburban Skokie.
   Democratic Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois agreed, and joined the
effort to find a new mascot. His fellow Democratic senator, Alan
Dixon, is prepared to lead a fight to keep the mascot.
   Because of opposition, the university in Champaign-Urbana has
agreed to have cheerleaders and band members stop wearing
Indian-style face makeup during games, school spokesman Terry
Shepard said Tuesday.
   But he added, ``I think it would take something very cataclysmic
for the chief to be done away with.''
   The chief is named for a confederacy of woodland tribes that
once lived in Illinois and parts of Wisconsin, Iowa and Missouri.
   Dixon is an alumnus of the university and said he is filled with
``pride for my school'' every time he sees the chief.
   Simon acknowledged Monday during a Chicago visit that the chief
``is a revered figure'' to University of Illinois fans.
   ``But it remains a sore point for many Native Americans,'' he
said. ``I would favor further discussion that could eventually lead
to a new mascot for the university.''
   Other schools have changed Indian mascots, including Stanford
University, which several years ago changed the name of its sports
teams from the Indians to the Cardinal.
</TEXT>
