<DOCNO> AP891107-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1656EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Paris-Parking     11-07 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paris-Parking,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Crack Down on Illegal Parking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Paris Periwinkles stuffed butterflies under
windshield wipers with unusual alacrity Tuesday as part of a
crackdown on illegal parking, a major contributor to the city's
nightmarish traffic.
   Periwinkles are what the French fondly call their meter maids
and butterflies are what, far less fondly, they call parking
tickets. Traffic policemen and police auxiliaries are helping with
the blitz of illegal parkers.
   After a brief publicity campaign notifying the public that the
days of lax enforcement were over and the ``anything goes'' style
of French parking had gone, authorities sprang into action Monday
with tickets and tow trucks.
   ``It's really interfering with my work,'' said Rodrigues
Barbosa, a housepainter working in a central Paris apartment. ``I
keep having to climb down from the ladder and stick my head out of
the window every 15 minutes.''
   It was worse for drivers of delivery trucks, who block narrow
streets with impunity and unload their wares with majestic
nonchalance at all hours despite restrictions on delivery times.
   ``You simply cannot work in Paris without breaking the law,''
one said.
   Another complained: ``They're not really attacking the traffic
problem, they're taking it out on drivers. What they need is to
build more parking places in Paris, but that's more complicated.''
   Paris is blessed with wide avenues, but they are knit together
by hundreds of narrow streets that quickly become congested.
   Parisians, desperate for a places to leave their cars, park them
on sidewalks, in crosswalks, at taxi stands. They'll even park
double or triple at intersections.
   No one is being spared in the painful new regime. Police and
Periwinkles, named for their light blue uniforms, have orders to
ticket every violator, accept no excuses, accede to no pleadings.
   Special attention is being paid to those who park
``dangerously,'' as in bus lanes. Tow-away tickets are stuck on
windows, radio calls placed and the vehicles vanish in 15 minutes.
   ``It's quite a shock to go out and see your car gone,'' said a
journalist who parked in a taxi stand when he arrived at work
Monday night.
   Paris police said 457 vehicles were towed away Monday, compared
with about 300 on a usual day. They said 10,117 parking tickets
were issued, 23 percent more than the previous Monday.
   A ticket for parking that disrupts traffic costs 230 francs
($37). Parking in a delivery zone is worth 500 francs ($80) and
retrieving a vehicle from the car pound lightens the wallet by 471
francs ($75). Dangerous parking might cost a driver's license.
   ``Users of Paris streets must appreciate the consequences of the
increase in individualistic parking conduct, which is at the very
least cavalier, if not outright dangerous,'' Police Chief Pierre
Verbrugghe said last month.
   City plans call for eliminating 100,000 parking places in 10
years and creating 300 ``red streets,'' where parking will be
prohibited to facilitate through traffic.
   How long the current heat will last is not clear.
   ``Before, when I was writing a ticket and the owner of the
vehicle arrived, I had a tendency to let it go,'' a Periwinkle
said, ``but now, we are under very strict orders. Nobody escapes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Pakistan-Leaflets     11-07 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pakistan-Leaflets,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistan Air Force Plane Drops Advertising Leaflets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pakistani air force plane buzzed
Islamabad on Tuesday and dropped leaflets advertising a private
home furnishing business _ but it was all for charity.
   The U.S.-built C-130 transport made several low passes over
Islamabad as clouds of white paper fell from its open hatch.
   They read: ``Long Live Pakistan ... Come For New and Unmatchable
Variety of Furnishing, Fabric, Carpets.'' They gave the addresses
and phone numbers of Malik Fabrics, Carpets and Furniture in three
Pakistani cities.
   A military spokesman, when informed of the incident, at first
refused to believe it.
   ``That's incredible, absolutely incredible,'' said Col. S.M.A.
Iqbal, deputy chief of military public relations.
   After investigating, he said the aircraft was authorized to drop
leaflets advertising an upcoming charity bazaar to be held by the
Pakistan Air Force Women's Association.
   The leaflets didn't mention the event.
   Employees at the Malik shop in Islamabad denied any knowledge of
the unorthodox advertising.
</TEXT>
