<FIRST>r p AM-ELN--Koch     11-07 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Koch,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lame Duck Mayor Says He's `Free at Last'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After three terms as mayor and stints as a
congressman, councilman and district leader, Edward I. Koch
couldn't find his name on the ballot Tuesday. He proclaimed himself
``free at last.''
   The lame-duck mayor said he got up at 5:30 a.m., put in an hour
at the gym, went to a police station to ``say goodbye to the cops''
and then cast his ballot for David Dinkins and the rest of the
Democratic ticket.
   ``I feel very sanguine,'' he said outside the Loeb Student
Center at New York University. ``I'm probably the most relaxed guy
in town today.''
   He said he did not mind being out of the political action and
accepted his loss to Dinkins in the Democratic primary in September.
   ``No poignancy. No regrets. No sensitivity,'' he said. ``I have
a sense of `Free at last! Free at last! Great God Almighty! Free at
last!'''
   Koch first ran for office, unsuccessfully, in the Democratic
primary for the state Assembly in 1962. He won a race for
Democratic district leader in Greenwich Village the next year,
ousting Tammany Hall boss Carmine DeSapio.
   ``My critics _ those who have opposed me in election after
election _ thought that somehow or other my life would come to an
end if I were not the mayor,'' Koch said.
   ``And they're dumbfounded. They're confounded, that I am going
on to a new career: from a financial point of view, much more
enriching.''
   Koch, who is paid $130,000-a-year as mayor, has lined up a
fellowship as a lecturer on urban affairs at New York University, a
two-minute commentary on a daily morning radio talk show, a
possible newspaper column, a big-bucks lecture circuit contract and
what he said will probably be a TV show.
   He has also said he would consider ``tasteful'' commercials.
   However, he added, ``Obviously there's no job as good as that of
being mayor. I said that all along.''
</TEXT>
