<FIRST>u w AM-SharkShortage 1stLd-Writethru a0732 11-07 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shark Shortage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaws Alert: Humans May Pose Bigger Threat Than Sharks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS 7th graf, bgng, So serious ... to make shark fish,
not mammals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the battle between sharks and people, it
turns out that the jaws most to be feared are those of humans.
   The National Marine Fisheries Service announced Tuesday that the
sharks in the North Atlantic may need protection.
   Sharks have been overfished for a decade, resulting in a severe
depletion in the western North Atlantic, the Commerce Department
agency said.
   Once a secondary product caught by fishermen seeking tuna and
swordfish, sharks have become a sought-after seafood on their own,
said Pat Kurkul of the Fisheries Service in Gloucester, Mass.
   Shark meat is becoming common on American stores and shark fins
are increasingly exported, she said.
   Feared for their voraciousness, featured in such films as
``Jaws'', sharks are slow to mature, have a long reproductive cycle
and produce only a few offspring annually, officials said.
   So serious is the concern that the Fisheries Service is taking
the extraordinary step of scheduling a series of hearings over the
next two months to discuss the problem and draft a management plan
for the fish.
   The plan could include setting a commercial quota, requiring
permits for commercial use and establishing recreational bag limits.
   That plan could go to the secretary of commerce by February and
take effect by June, said Ms. Kurkul.
   Mako is the most commonly caught and sold species of shark, but
the management plan would consider some 38 species if they are
found to be in danger, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
