<FIRST>r w AM-SouthPacificNuclear 120   11-07 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Pacific Nuclear, 120</SECOND>
<HEAD>House OKs Nuclear Free Treaty in South Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday approved a resolution
supporting U.S. ratification of a treaty establishing a zone free
of nuclear weapons in the South Pacific.
   The United States, France and Great Britain, which have long
tested nuclear weapons in the South Pacific, have refused to sign
agreements under the 1986 Treaty of Rarotonga.
   That treaty would restrict development or permanent placing of
nuclear weapons in the region.
   The non-binding resolution, passed by voice vote, says ``United
States practices and activities in the region are consistent with
the Treaty of Rarotonga and its protocols.''
   ``It is therefore the sense of the Congress that the United
States should sign and ratify the protocols to that treaty.''
</TEXT>
