<HEAD>Tuesday's Events in the Changing Communist World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tuesday's developments in the changing Communist bloc:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's government resigned amid growing nationwide
unrest, a continuing exodus of thousands of its people and pleas
from within the Communist Party for a sweeping top-level shakeup. A
parliamentary committee rejected a law promising up to 30 days of
travel to the West and urged a new law allowing unrestricted stays
abroad. Since Saturday, more than 28,000 East Germans have fled to
the West through Czechoslovakia _ arriving in West Germany at the
rate of 120 an hour.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOVIET UNION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A march by 5,000 anti-Communist protesters, a strike by coal
miners, a flag-burning in Latvia and clashes between police and
demonstrators occurred as a scaled-down military parade was held on
Red Square to celebrate the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution. President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev tempered the Revolution Day festivities by
saying the nation's economic problems hang like a ``sword of
Damocles over us.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Films made in the 1960s and banned after Soviet tanks crushed
``Prague Spring'' reforms in 1968 will be shown in Czechoslovakia,
the Communist Party newspaper Rude Pravo reported. Government
cultural officials were quick to add, however, that the decision
wasn't meant to rehabilitate the liberalization period. Among the
films to be shown will be ``The Party And The Guests'' directed by
Jan Nemec.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HUNGARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The red star atop Hungary's neo-gothic parliament building will
be replaced in the spring by a weather vane, which adorned the
structure before the Communist takeover, the state news agency
announced.
</TEXT>
