<HEAD>Bush Praises World Series Champs Oakland A's</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS death toll from 63 to 66 in 11th graf, bgng, The Athletics
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday credited the World
Series championship Oakland Athletics for helping earthquake-weary
San Francisco Bay residents recover from ``hard and tragic times.''
   In a Rose Garden ceremony, Bush praised the team as ``champions
on the field and champions off it.''
   In a World Series that will be most remembered for the earthquake
that interrupted it for 11 days, Bush said both the A's and their
rivals, ``those equally magnificent'' San Francisco Giants,
``bounced back, overcoming adversity, uniting a populace. ...''
   The two teams showed ``how true pros perform when the odds are
longest and the evening darkest, and the game is on the line _ the
game of baseball or the larger game of life.''
   The president, a first baseman and captain of his 1948 Yale
baseball team, was presented a baseball jersey with ``Bush'' in
large black letters displayed on its front.
   ``We're looking for a left-hand-hitting first baseman,'' team
manager Tony La Russa told Bush.
   Actually, Bush pitches left-handed but hits right-handed.
   Bush said he only wished La Russa ``could help pilot my budget
through Congress the way he piloted the A's to this World Series
victory.''
   ``Today we're talking baseball. And a team that is clearly and
truly No. 1,'' Bush said, speaking on a raw, overcast day. With the
team's players lined up in business suits behind him, he added:
``big-leaguers, all, each contributing big-time to the cause.''
   ``You helped the Bay Area through some hard and tragic times,''
he said.
   The Athletics beat the Giants in a four-game sweep. But the
series was abruptly interrupted after a quake measuring 7.1 on the
Richter scale struck at the start of game No .3. The quake killed 66
people, left thousands homeless and did billions of dollars worth of
damage.
   Of the Earthquake Series' most valuable player, A's pitcher Dave
Stewart, Bush said: ``I'm just glad I'm not running for office''
against him.
   Addressing the whole team, Bush said: ``To you we all say, well
done.''
   Team owner Walter A. Haas Jr. told Bush, ``baseball is our
national pasttime and you're our most valuable player.''
   Joked Bush: ``I'll bet it's not often that the Oakland A's are
honored by an unofficial scout for the Texas Rangers.'' His oldest
son, George W. Bush, is an owner of the Texas franchise.
</TEXT>
