<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-USSIowa     11-07 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-USS Iowa,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee to Probe Iowa Blast, Navy Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Armed Services Committee will begin
hearings next week on the explosion aboard the USS Iowa that claimed
the lives of 47 sailors, the panel's chairman said Tuesday.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said the panel will hold hearings both on
the April 19 blast and the Navy's investigation of it.
   The Navy concluded that gunner's mate Clayton Hartwig ``most
likely'' caused the explosion by inserting some type of detonator
between bags of gunpowder in one of the ship's 16-inch guns.
   But since the service issued its report on Sept. 7, members of
Congress, Hartwig's family and the sailor's former shipmates have
criticized the Navy's conclusions.
   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., chairman of a House Armed
Services subcommittee that also is reviewing the matter, cited an
FBI report that said its laboratory inquiry was inconclusive.
   Mavroules said the fact that two government departments _ the
Pentagon and the FBI _ failed to reach the same conclusions raises
serious doubts about the Navy's findings.
   However, Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, who oversaw the Navy's
technical and criminal study, said in an interview last week that he
stands by his conclusions.
   ``I am not aware of anything that would cause me to change my
report,'' he said.
