<FIRST>r a AM-S&amp;LConvention     11-07 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Convention,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Executives See Higher Home Prices if Rule Not Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;Ls-Lincoln</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the changes enacted by Congress in response
to the savings and loan crisis may have the unintended effect of
making new homes more expensive, thrift and housing executives said
Tuesday.
   Officials of the U.S. League of Savings Institutions, the thrift
industry's largest trade group, have identified the new restriction
on loans to one borrower as a top priority in their campaign to
amend S&amp;L legislation passed in August.
   The new limit is 15 percent of an institution's capital, down
from 100 percent previously, a level that allowed an institution to
fail because of the default of a single borrower.
   The lower limit was intended to break up the relationship between
some builders and a few thrift executives who would fund highly
speculative development projects.
   But, U.S. League President Fred Webber said 15 percent is too
restrictive. Kent W. Colton, executive vice president of the
National Association of Home Builders, said ``war stories'' are
beginning to filter in from builders whose credit lines with S&amp;Ls
have been cut drastically.
   Home builders need large acquisition and development loans to
prepare subdivision plots for sale, he said.
   ``I'm not talking about dollars to finance land speculation. ...
There are people who have sold the lots but can't get the money to
put in infrastructure,'' he told 3,600 delegates to the league's
97th annual convention.
   Colton said a scarcity of development loans could increase the
cost of new homes and said builders and S&amp;L executives should unite
to lobby Congress to ease the restriction.
   David Seiders, chief economist of the home builders, said S&amp;Ls
may eventually learn to cope with the new rule, which has applied to
national banks for years, by combining in groups to make development
loans or by selling shares in the loans to other institutions.
   Meanwhile, House Secretary Jack Kemp drew cheers from the S&amp;L
executives by repeating his call for lower interest rates.
   The Federal Reserve Board has been trying to ease inflation
pressures by slowing the economy with high interest rates, a policy
Kemp called ``a barbaric solution to the inflation equation.''
   Lower interest rates are ``absolutely critical'' for making homes
affordable to Americans, he said. New homes sales in September,
according to the Commerce Department, plunged 14 percent, the
sharpest dive in nearly eight years.
   However, economists appearing at a panel discussion predicted the
Fed would only reluctantly ease interest rates as signs of economic
sluggishness emerged.
   ``The decade is going out with a whimper and you might get some
short-term relief from high interest rates,'' said James Christian,
chief economist of the S&amp;L trade group.
   Christian is predicting that construction of new homes will
remain flat at about 1.4 million units in 1990 and 1991.
</TEXT>
