<HEAD>NBC's Comedies Surpass ABC in the Ratings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT 21st to 23rd. ADDS 4 grafs at end,
with new, low ratings.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC appears to be winning the battle of the
network comedy nights as ABC's Tuesday shows fell in the ratings and
``Chicken Soup'' was canceled.
   ``Chicken Soup,'' starring comedian Jackie Mason, touted as this
season's biggest potential hit, will have its final telecast Tuesday
night.
   NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' ``A Different World'' and ``Cheers''
all nosed out ABC's ``Roseanne'' for first, second and third place
in the Nielsen ratings for the week ended Nov. 5. NBC's other
Thursday night comedy, ``Dear John,'' was sixth.
   ``Roseanne'' fell to fourth place after last week's finish at the
top. Other ABC Tuesday comedies were also down. ``The Wonder Years''
was 17th, ``Who's the Boss?'' tied for 19th and ``Chicken Soup'' was
23rd.
   NBC won big for the week in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey. Its
average was 15.2. ABC was second with 13.7 and CBS third with 11.9.
A rating is the percentage of the nation's 92.1 million homes tuned
to a show.
   NBC is also ahead for the season-to-date and in the November
sweeps. The ratings for the first seven weeks of the fall season:
NBC 15.0, ABC 13.7, CBS 12.6. For the first four days of the Nielsen
sweeps: NBC 15.0, CBS 12.8, ABC 11.3. The first five days of the
Arbitron sweeps: NBC 14.8, CBS 12.4, ABC 12.3.
   The sweeps are designated times when local stations' ratings are
recorded to establish advertising rates. Networks usually present
their flashiest shows during the monthlong sweeps period.
   Two veteran network stars, Carroll O'Connor and Andy Griffith,
contributed to the fall of ABC's Tuesday comedies. NBC won the night
with ``Matlock,'' ``In the Heat of the Night'' and ``Midnight
Caller'' for the first time this season. ``In the Heat of the
Night,'' starring O'Connor, was 14th, ``Matlock,'' starring
Griffith, was 18th, and ``Midnight Caller,'' starring Gary Cole, was
26th.
   Here are the top 10: NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``A
Different World,'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``The
Golden Girls,'' NBC's ``Dear John,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote,'' NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and NBC's ``L.A. Law,''
tied.
   This past week was the most normal week of the season so far.
NBC's ``L.A. Law'' was the last regular show to premiere, the World
Series is over and the end of daylight savings time is raising the
eight o'clock ratings to standard time levels.
   ``Chicken Soup'' will be replaced by the return of ``Coach,''
starring Craig T. Nelson and Shelley Fabares.
   The opening chapter of the NBC miniseries ``Cross of Fire'' on
Sunday was 42nd. Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``Married ... With
Children'' was 51st for the week.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' was first again in the ratings,
despite the fact that 18 West Coast stations telecast it earlier or
dropped it entirely on Mondays because of ``Monday Night Football.''
ABC has won for the past four weeks and was tied with CBS the week
before that. The ratings: ABC 11.4, CBS 10.7, NBC 10.1.
   The lowest rated network show of the week was CBS's ``Wolf.'' The
five bottom network shows were: ABC's ``Homeroom,'' ABC's ``Living
Dolls,'' CBS' ``A Peaceable Kingdom,'' ABC's ``Mr. Belevedere'' and
CBS' ``Wolf.''
</TEXT>
