<FIRST>u w AM-Narcotics-Banks     11-07 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Narcotics-Banks,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Countries Freeze $60 Million Bank Accounts Of Drug Lord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five foreign countries froze $60 million in
bank accounts owned by a major narcotics trafficker, a senior U.S.
drug enforcement official said Tuesday.
   The official, Terrence M. Burke, acting deputy administrator of
the Drug Enforcement Administration, said efforts are being made to
freeze an additional two or three bank accounts belonging to the
same Columbian drug dealer.
   Burke told reporters the action represents a significant advance
in the war on drugs because it is an example of valuable
cooperation by the government of Colombia and the five other
nations in which the numerous bank accounts were located.
   Burke disclosed the development during testimony before a House
Foreign Affairs subcommittee hearings held to evaluate the Bush
administration's attempt to attack major drug cartels at the source
in Colombia and other Latin American nations.
   Elaborating on his testimony after the hearing, Burke declined
to identify the drug dealer whose accounts were frozen or to name
the countries in which the accounts were located. No American banks
are believed to be involved, Burke said.
   ``Based on information provided by the Colombian government in
the last 10 days, we have been able to identify and freeze bank
accounts in five countries that contain at least $60 million,''
Burke told reporters.
   He said the accounts were not part of a money laundering-system,
``but represent savings accounts of one of the major Colombian
narcotics dealers.''
   ``These are accounts which we believe contain liquid assets of
this particular trafficker,'' Burke said.
   Burke said the drug dealer is being sought by law enforcement
authorities.
   ``I think this development demonstrates international
cooperation,'' Burke said. ``The Colombian authorities developed
this information in real time and gave it to us. And several other
countries cooperated in turn to freeze these funds. I think that's
very significant.''
   ``We are striking at the heart of these trafficking syndicates
by confiscating their money and goods,'' Burke said in his prepared
testimony.
   He noted that earlier this year the DEA and other federal and
foreign law enforcement agencies conducted a joint operation dubbed
``Operation Polar Cap'' which closed down a money-laundering
enterprise that handled some $1.2 billion in illicit drug profits
belonging to Colombia's Medellin cartel.
   ``Operation Polar Cap resulted in the seizure of more than one
ton of cocaine, the confiscation of $92 million in cash, jewelry
and real estate and the indictment of 127 individuals,'' Burke said.
</TEXT>
