<DOCNO> AP891107-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Pentagon-Jamming 640   11-07 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Jamming, 640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon: Jamming System `Has Problems'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department acknowledged Tuesday
that a planned $9 billion system for jamming enemy radar ``has
problems,'' and that a major review has been ordered to determine
whether the program will proceed.
   The program came under fire in September when Sen. David Pryor,
D-Ark., called it a ``potential waste of billions of dollars'' and
quoted Navy documents that called the system ``marginally
operationally effective.''
   The Airborne Self-Protection Jammer will deceive or jam enemy
radar and will be carried aboard Navy and Air Force fighter planes,
including the F-14, F-18, F-16 and AV-8B.
   The Defense Department planned to produce 2,369 of the jammers
at a total cost of $9.4 billion over the expected 20-year life of
the program. So far, $681 million has been spent.
   Aircraft are to be equipped with electronic warfare systems that
use a radar-warning receiver to alert a pilot when the airplane is
being tracked by enemy radar. It also sends out signals to confuse
enemy missiles or radar, creating false targets or giving opponents
the idea that U.S. planes aren't where they seem to be.
   Many electronic warfare systems are in use and determined to be
satisfactory, but the services are pursuing the new system in the
expectation of growing technological threats.
   ``It has problems,'' Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman told
reporters when he was asked about the system. But he declined to go
into detail, saying only that the system had ``performance,
reliability'' problems.
   Deputy Defense Secretary Donald Atwood and the undersecretary of
defense for acquisition, James Betti, are ``engaged in the
problem,'' Hoffman said.
   ``Where we stand now is that there has been a memorandum that
calls for a review of the program after a one-year period,''
Hoffman said, adding that the Pentagon then will decide whether to
continue the program.
   Meanwhile, he said, a limited production of 100 units has been
ordered.
   ``Work is being done on this, and we hope to get this thing on
track,'' Hoffman said.
   Duane P. Andrews, nominated to be assistant secretary of defense
for Command, Control, Communications and Intelligence, told the
Senate Armed Services Committee that support for the system remains
strong despite problems.
   ``I'm told it's the most effective system that we currently have
for our deployed forces and the office of the secretary of defense
is standing behind the program,'' Andrews said at his confirmation
hearing Tuesday.
   According to Pentagon sources who spoke on condition they not be
identified, the program is four years behind its original
production start date.
   The source said that the delays were due in some measure to
``updated threat intelligence'' information and a decision to delay
development to upgrade the system.
   The Pentagon inspector general and the General Accounting Office
are reviewing the decision to proceed with the program, the source
said.
   Navy Capt. Matt Small told The Washington Post in an article
published Tuesday that ``we don't do a good job of evaluating
jammer performance,'' and that problems with the program's flawed
test methods and equipment can be overcome.
   The source said a joint Air Force and Navy group has been formed
to improve those testing procedures and that the effort is expected
to be completed by the end of the year.
   In a report released in September, the GAO said the test
equipment used by the Air Force to determine the effectiveness of
the radar-warning receivers and other electronics on tactical
fighters was faulty and unreliable.
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, said the problems
undermined the combat readiness of the aircraft and attributed the
problems to the Air Force's acquisition process, in which it bought
test sets before determining whether they would work properly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
