<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineAbuse     11-07 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Abuse,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abuse Charges Dropped Against Mother Of Cocaine-Addicted Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors say they will appeal a
judge's decision to drop a child-abuse charge against the mother of
a baby born addicted to cocaine.
   Broward Circuit Judge Robert B. Carney said he based the
dismissal on an earlier case that determined Florida's child-abuse
laws do not apply to a fetus.
   In the earlier case, the 4th District Court of Appeal in West
Palm Beach decided charges of battery against an infant could not be
brought against a man who shot a pregnant woman who delivered a
wounded baby.
   ``The state will certainly seek to appeal,'' said Assistant State
Attorney Dennis Bailey after Carney dismissed charges Monday against
Cassandra Gethers, 23, of Hollywood.
   Ms. Gethers remains in jail, serving an 18-month sentence for
violating probation she received for an earlier conviction for
possession of cocaine. Her attorney, Russell Adler, said she may be
released in one to three months.
   ``She wants to get her baby back, get a job and get counseling,''
he said.
   She was arrested in February and charged with child abuse after
she and her baby daughter were found to be cocaine-dependent.
   No woman has been convicted in the United States of child abuse
as a result of harm she caused her baby by using cocaine during
pregnancy.
   The State Attorney's Office said it prosecuted Ms. Gethers
because she also gave birth in February 1988 to a cocaine-dependent
son and was counseled at that time on the dangers of using cocaine
while pregnant.
</TEXT>
