<FIRST>r w AM-Iran-Contra     11-07 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Prosecutor Seeks Transcript of Closed Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iran-Contra prosecutor urged the U.S. Court
of Appeals on Tuesday to issue a transcript of a closed hearing in
the case of Joseph Fernandez, the former CIA station chief in Costa
Rica.
   Independent counsel Lawrence Walsh told the Richmond, Va., court
that a censored version of the transcript from the Aug. 23 hearing
should be made public because much of the testimony isn't
potentially damaging to national security.
   Justice Department lawyers prevailed on the court to close a
portion of that hearing dealing with CIA programs in Costa Rica
aimed at protecting the country against a possible invasion by
Nicaragua.
   In a court filing, Walsh said intelligence agencies had
authorized him to disclose that information and that the Justice
Department approved its disclosure at public trial.
   But the department said the information, contained in documents
prepared by the government, still was considered classified for
purposes of oral argument.
   Even federal law protecting classified information ``implies that
the Attorney General may not certify the closure of an entire
hearing where only a `portion' of that hearing risks disclosure of
classified information,'' Walsh said.
   ``Thus, while the Attorney General has authority to close an
argument because of the likelihood that classified information will
be disclosed, the Attorney General has no authority ... to prohibit
access to a redacted, unclassified transcript,'' Walsh said.
   Walsh's court filing was in support of five organizations _ CBS
Inc., The New York Times Co., The Washington Post, the American
Civil Liberties Union and the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the
Press _ that have filed a motion for access to a redacted transcript.
   Fernandez is charged with obstructing the Tower Commission and
the CIA inspector general and making false statements in the
Iran-Contra affair. He allegedly assisted White House aide Oliver
North's secret Contra re-supply operation.
   His trial is delayed while the Justice Department decides whether
it wants to appeal a ruling that the attorney general may not
intervene in the Fernandez case with court appeals to protect
classified information.
   The ruling leaves Attorney General Dick Thornburgh with the
option of allowing certain classified information to be divulged at
Fernandez's trial or filing an affidavit barring its disclosure.
Filing an affidavit could scuttle the prosecution.
</TEXT>
