<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Panhandler-Shooting     11-07 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panhandler-Shooting,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Killed Panhandler Pleads Guilty to Misdemeanor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white man who said he shot a black
panhandler out of fear for his life was given a suspended jail
sentence after pleading guilty to a misdemeanor homicide charge.
   Clifford Smith, 40, was also placed on probation for two years in
the 1986 shooting death of Jimmy Jackson, 42. Smith fired when
Jackson approached a pickup driven by Smith at a red light in
Birmingham.
   Smith's 1987 trial ended in a mistrial when the jury deadlocked
10-2 in favor of convicting him of the same charge he pleaded guilty
to Monday in a plea bargain at Jefferson Couty Circuit Court.
   The sentence drew criticism Tuesday from attorney Henry L.
Penick, who is representing Jackson's brother in a $4 million
wrongful death suit against Smith. The civil lawsuit is pending.
   Penick said he was ``outraged and disturbed'' by what he
considered a ``very light sentence, certainly in comparison to the
nature of the crime.''
   ``It is precisely a Bernhard Goetz case,'' said Penick. ``In
fact, it is more heinous than that case in the sense there was no
allegation that Jimmy Jackson was trying to rob Mr. Smith. He was
merely asking for a quarter.
   Goetz, who shot four young black men on a New York subway in
December 1984, said he feared he was about to be robbed. He was
cleared of attempted murder and assault charges but was sentenced to
one year in jail and fined $500 for illegal gun possession.
   In the Birmingham case, Penick said the prosecution and sentence
would have been harsher if the unarmed victim had been white and the
gunman black.
   ``I know both the judge and the district attorney to be fair
persons, but I do not understand how they came to agree on this
particular sentence,'' he said.
   Bill Neumann, deputy district attorney, denied any racial
motivation behind the plea bargain with Smith. He said the
prosecution had problems finding witnesses, and noted that a 1987
jury deadlocked with 10 wanting to convict Smith of no more than
criminally negligent homicide. The other two jurors favored a more
serious manslaughter conviction.
   ``Based on the evidence we felt we could put on with the
witnesses we had, the age of the case and the jury voting the way
they did before,'' Neumann said, it seemed better to make the offer
to Smith.
   Smith contended he shot Jackson because he feared for his life.
He said Jackson had approached him previously and when Smith refused
to give him money, Jackson tried to take the keys from the ignition
of his vehicle.
   On the day he shot Jackson, Smith said Jackson approached him
yelling, ``I remember you! I remember you!'' Smith said he fired a
warning shot at the ground, then fired again when Jackson kept
advancing.
   Smith has been on non-paid leave from his job as a U.S. Postal
Service mechanic since the shooting. One of his attorneys said he
now will start the process of getting reinstated.
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' Smith said outside the courtroom.
</TEXT>
