<FIRST>r i AM-Thailand-Ship     11-07 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thailand-Ship,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boats Rescue 35 Survivors from Gulf of Thailand Typhoon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SONGKHLA, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fishermen have rescued 35 survivors of
a typhoon that ravaged the Gulf of Thailand and about 70 bodies have
been recovered, including seven from a capsized U.S.-owned ship,
reports said Tuesday.
   The Thai navy said its ships would take aboard the survivors
found by fishing boats but it did not know if any of the victims
were from the Seacrest oil-drilling ship. The Seacrest, operated by
Unocal of Los Angeles, had 97 crewmen aboard when it capsized
Saturday as Typhoon Gay roared across the gulf.
   Unocal reported that six crewmen were rescued and the bodies of
seven have been recovered from the accident about 270 miles south of
Bangkok.
   Navy and local officials reported 400 Thai fishermen are still
missing along with 84 Seacrest crewmen.
   The navy said the storm sank at least 63 fishing boats.
   Navy spokesman Capt. Suravut Maharom reported warships recovered
17 bodies from the gulf, east of Songkhla, since beginning the
search Monday and 30 bodies were found washed ashore on a Chumphon
province island.
   Carol Scott of Unocal in Bangkok said search teams aboard company
helicopters found 16 bodies and they were recovered by Unocal boats
Tuesday.
   She said she did not know if any of the 16 were from the Seacrest.
   Navy divers on Monday removed a seventh body from the 5,373-ton
oil- and gas-drilling ship, which was upside-down in the water.
   A Unocal news release said, ``We have no plans to give up the
search effort.''
   The Interior Ministry said 31 people on land were killed by the
typhoon but the governor of Chumphon placed the death toll in his
province alone at 71.
   Unocal identified six of the Seacrest crewmen who perished and
whose bodies were recovered as Ed Seliger, the West German captain
of the vessel; Delvin Irby, a drill worker from Mississippi; Kent
Nolen, an assistant driller from the United States; Andrew Charles,
a British field engineer, and Thai crewmen Anan Charoensuksomboon
and Munard Moowangohareen. Hometowns were not given.
   Unocal's local subsidiary said four of the bodies were found in
the ship's wheehouse and the other two in the water.
   Most of the Seacrest's crew crew were Thais but there also were
seven Americans aboard. No American is known to have survived.
   Chalit Duangpakdee, one of the Thai survivors, told the Bangkok
Post, ``All I remember is the sound of swirling wind, the darkness,
the rain, the waves. And every now and then, the screams for help.''
   The kitchen worker said when an alarm sounded to abandon ship he
grabbed a life jacket, jumped into the sea with many other crew
members and managed to secure himself with rope inside a life raft.
   He said after several hours he was picked up by a fishing boat.
   Unocal reported survivors said all of the crew abandoned ship
except the captain and three men who remained in the wheelhouse.
   The Seacrest capsized in the Platong field, one of several being
explored for natural gas by Unocal.
</TEXT>
