<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 2003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-House-CoastGuard 340   11-07 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House-Coast Guard, 340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Funds Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday approved a $3.4 billion
program for the Coast Guard in fiscal 1990, including provisions
designed to crack down on alcohol abuse among merchant seamen.
   The bill, approved 383-3 and sent to the Senate, contains several
provisions that address the Exxon Valdez oil spill in Alaska last
spring.
   The House was to vote Wednesday on another bill expedited by the
Exxon accident _ oil spill liability.
   The Coast Guard measure would require the agency to review the
criminal records of applicants for new or renewed licenses,
registrations and other needed documents. If there's enough evidence
of alcohol abuse, the agency could withhold papers until the problem
is corrected.
   The Exxon Valdez ran aground March 24, dumping 11 million gallons
of crude oil into Prince William Sound. Investigators were told that
the tanker captain had been drinking and wasn't on the bridge when
the accident occurred.
   By voice vote, the House added a requirement that the Coast Guard
conduct random drug tests of its employees.
   The bill calls for new research and development of techniques for
cleaning up oil spills. It also authorizes the Coast Guard to spend
$24 million for advanced aircraft radar to detect drug smugglers and
develop new procedures for seizing vessels on which drugs are
detected.
   Much Coast Guard activity involves policing recreational boaters,
but some need more policing than others.
   The bill requires the agency to identify how much it's spending
to provide security for President Bush's fishing and boating
activities at his summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   The oil spill liability coming up Wednesday sets limits on the
amount an oil company or oil carrier would have to pay if a spill
occurs.
   Heated floor debate is expected over an amendment proposed by
Reps. George Miller, D-Calif., and Gerry Studds, D-Mass., that would
allow states to set stricter liability laws than the federal
statute. As written, the bill would require a single law, the
federal one.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
