<HEAD>Man Burned Over 50 Percent of Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old man climbed a transformer
tower and burst into flames, leaving him in critical condition
Tuesday.
   Rob Colyer of Lake Grove suffered burns over 50 percent of his
body, said Pam Johnson, a spokeswoman for the Emanuel Hospital &amp;
Health Center.
   The accident Monday evening briefly knocked out power in the area.
   Colyer was among a group of 15 teen-agers who gathered near the
Portland General Electric Co. transformer station, said Mick Brady,
battalion chief at the Lake Oswego Fire Department.
   Brady said the youth suddenly ran toward the station, scaled the
fence surrounding it and climbed up the 30-foot tower.
   Hilary Demary said she was driving through a nearby intersection
when she heard an explosion and saw sparks at the top of the tower.
   She said the lights went out and she heard another explosion,
followed by a burst of flames, which she realized was a person on
fire.
   The man fell to the ground in flames, Demary said.
   Fire officials said there were no indications of what prompted
Colyer to climb the tower.
