<HEAD>Guerrilla Group Says it Killed a Man by Mistake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guerrilla group said its
members mistakenly killed a self-employed tiler, thinking he was a
member of Northern Ireland's security forces.
   The outlawed Irish People's Liberation Organization issued a
statement after police said the victim, Robert Burns, 49, had no
connection with the army or police.
   Burns was fatally wounded by assailants who fired through the
front door of his house in Derriaghy.
   The Irish People's Liberation Organization is a breakaway group
from the Irish Republican Army, also outlawed in both Britain and
Ireland. Both are fighting to unite Northern Ireland, a British
province where Protestants outnumber Roman Catholics 3-2, with the
predominantly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
   In another development, police ordered an urgent review of
security for Northern Ireland's senior police officers after an IRA
bombing Monday of the home of a chief in the Royal Ulster
Constabulary.
   Assistant Chief Constable David Mellor, 52, had just left the
living room when the bomb exploded under a bullet-proof window
inches behind the armchair where he had been reading. Mellor's wife
and two young daughters were nearby but were not injured.
   The IRA said its guerrillas placed a 3-pound bomb at the window.
   It issued a statement saying, ``We deliberately placed a small
charge only because we were aware of the young children in the
house. Otherwise we could undoubtedly have guaranteed Mellor's death
with a larger charge.''
   Police are concerned that the guerrillas were able to breach
Mellor's security arrangements that included a full alarm system
with special lights.
   Eight Royal Ulster Constabular officers, including a chief
superintendent and two superintendents, have been killed by the IRA
this year.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Brooke said Tuesday there was no
change in the government's policy toward terrorists but stood by his
remarks last week when he said it was ``difficult to envisage'' a
military defeat of the IRA. He had suggested the government might
hold talks with the IRA's legal political wing, Sinn Fein, if the
organization ended its terror campaiagn.
