<DOCNO> AP891107-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 2017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Church     11-07 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Church,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church of England Synod Supports Principle of Women Priests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Church of England's General Synod voted in
favor of the principle of women priests on Tuesday, the first step
toward possible ordination of women by the state church.
   Members of the General Synod passed by a simple majority the
first clause of a proposed amendment to canon law to permit
ordination of women.
   It reads: ``It shall be lawful for the General Synod to make
provision by canon for enabling a woman to be ordained to the office
of priest if she otherwise satisfies the requirements of Canon Law
as to the persons who may be ordained as priests.
   ``Nothing in this measure shall make it lawful for a woman to be
consecrated to the office of bishop.''
   The change came on the first day of a two-day debate and was
supported by all three branches of the synod, the church's
parliament. The bishops voted 30-17 in favor, the clergy 149-85 in
favor and the lay members 144-78 in favor.
   ``It went better than we thought,'' said Margaret Orr Deas,
executive secretary of the Movement for the Ordination of Women.
``We are very pleased.''
   The issue now goes to the 43 dioceses for discussion by ordinary
members of the church. This is expected to start next year.
   The question will probably not return to the General Synod for a
final vote until 1992, when a two-thirds majority will be required.
   The General Synod threw out two controversial amendments _ one to
create a separate church allowing only male priests; the other to
allow a parish within a diocese that ordained women to transfer to a
diocese which did not.
   About 1,200 women have been ordained in Anglican churches, mainly
in the United States, Canada and New Zealand. It has been a major
point of contention between Anglicans and Roman Catholics in their
ecumenical encounters.
   The Church of England has debated the issue for two decades. Some
opponents among the clergy and laity say they will break away if
women are ordained.
   At the start of debate, Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie
said he would vote to allow discussions on the ordination of women
to proceed in the dioceses, despite remaining undecided on the basic
principle of women priests.
   ``I judge that the dioceses may surprise us by what they bring
forward,'' he said.
   Explaining his dilemma, Runcie said on one hand he believed
theological arguments could justify ordaining women. On the other,
he said, women priests would have a detrimental effect on church
unity, as both he and Pope John Paul II said during his visit to
Rome in September.
   ``I cannot deny the serious obstacle which this move has created
there,'' he said.
   The bishop of Durham, the Right Rev. David Jenkins, drew loud
applause when he said, ``Ordination of women to the priesthood is
not the end of the world. If the Church of England's making a
mistake were the end of the world, the world would have ended long
ago.''
   The bishop of Portsmouth, the Rt. Rev. Timothy Bavin, said he
would have to consider resigning if the legislation was finally
passed, despite being a supporter of women priests.
   He said he did not want to have to choose between favoring
opponents or supporters among his congregations.
   Canon Frances Briscoe, one of 500 women deacons anxious to become
priests, told the Synod: ``The vast majority are not a regiment of
strident feminists but are dedicated women who quietly and
efficiently get on with the job within the confines of the present
strictures.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-07 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winds Gust Across the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winds gusting up to 70 mph blew through parts of Wyoming,
Colorado and Oregon on Tuesday as rain fell across much of the East,
including heavy storms that flooded New Orleans streets.
   Gusts of 60 mph were recorded in Cheyenne and Rawlins, Wyo.;
winds gusted to 58 mph in Pendleton, Ore., and to 70 mph between
Cheyenne and Laramie, Wyo.
   Winds gusted to over 55 mph in foothills west of Denver, and
blowing, drifting snow was reported at higher elevations of
Colorado's northern and central mountains.
   Snow showers over the mountains of northwest Montana diminished
to flurries after dumping up to 10 inches of snow in the higher
elevations since Monday morning.
   Rain showers and thunderstorms fell from the upper Texas coast to
southern and eastern Louisiana, Mississippi, western and northern
Alabama, northern Florida, southeast and northern Georgia,
Tennessee, West Virginia and eastern Kentucky.
   Rain also extended from Ohio to western Pennsylvania, western New
York statee and southern lower Michigan, and fell on Oregon's
southern coast.
   Southeast Louisiana got up to 9 inches of rain Tuesday morning,
and the wet weather continued. Streets around New Orleans were
flooded.
   Thunderstorms produced small hail and strong gusts in Bluff Park,
Ala., and hail half an inch in diameter fell in Altoona, Ala.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included
9.17 inches in Harvey, La.; 6.90 inches at New Orleans' airport; 4.2
inches at Belle Chase Naval Air Station, La.; 2.15 inches in Biloxi,
Miss.; and 1.62 inches in Baton Rouge, La.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 27
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 91 degrees at Laredo, Texas.
   The low temperature for the Lower 48 states Tuesday morning was
13 degrees in Truckee, Calif.
</TEXT>
