<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugSentencing     11-07 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Sentencing,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Medellin Trafficker Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY JOSE MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Medellin drug cartel extradited
last month from Colombia was sentenced Tuesday to 15 years in prison
and fined $25,000 for his 5-year-old drug conviction.
   Bernardo Pelaez Roldan, 44, fled to his homeland after his 1983
indictment, forfeiting a $200,000 bond. He was convicted in absentia
in Detroit in 1984 of conspiracy to possess with intent to
distribute 660 pounds of cocaine.
   Defense attorney Richard Lustig said he wasn't surprised Pelaez
received the maximum federal penalty, but contended his client's
rights were ignored.
   ``Pawns like Bernardo are being given to the public because of
the hysteria over drugs,'' Lustig said.
   At Tuesday's hearing, Lustig asked that Pelaez be returned to
Colombia because of improper extradition procedures, and that the
time he has served in prison since his 1983 indictment be credited
to his sentence.
   ``The defense motion for credit for time served is premature,''
U.S. District Judge Ralph M. Freeman said, adding that such a motion
must go to the Justice Department and not to the sentencing court.
   In 1987, the Colombian Supreme Court ruled that Pelaez couldn't
be extradited to the United States because the charges against him
predated an extradition agreement between the two countries. Pelaez
had been incarcerated for 22 months in Colombia pending that ruling.
   But Pelaez was extradited under presidential orders, independent
of Colombian courts, Lustig said.
   President Virgilio Barco revived extraditions to the United
States as part of the emergency measures against drug traffickers
imposed Aug. 18, after the assassination of a presidential candidate
who was an outspoken foe of the drug trade.
   Six people have since been extradited; Pelaez is the only one
tried and convicted, according to the U.S. Justice Department.
   Freeman said he will rule Nov. 22 on the extradition question.
   The government portrayed Pelaez as a major money launderer for
the Medellin cartel, which is believed to supply 80 percent of the
cocaine sold in the United States.
   Testimony in the 1984 trial revealed Pelaez was responsible for
shipments of cocaine valued at $6 million in 1981 and 1982. But
Lustig maintained his client was merely a courier.
   ``He did something wrong and admitted to it,'' Lustig said. ``But
if I might use the term, he was a flunky.''
   Lustig said he will appeal the conviction and Pelaez's
extradition.
</TEXT>
