<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermany-Synagogue     11-07 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Synagogue,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Synagogue Relic Discovered in Restoration Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restoration workers have discovered an important
relic of Berlin's once-magnificent main synagogue, East Germany's
ADN news agency said Tuesday.
   ADN said workers restoring the synagogue in East Berlin uncovered
the house of worship's ``Eternal Lamp,'' or Ner Tamid, as they were
removing a concrete ceiling.
   The synagogue was damaged by fire during the 1938 Nazi Crystal
Night pogrom against the Jews and later suffered heavy damage during
Allied bombing raids.
   Hermann Simon, director of a foundation established to restore
the building, said the lamp was a ``sensational find.''
   ADN said the silver lamp was donated by a Jewish family in 1866
and had likely hanged in a prominent place in the synagogue.
   The synagogue was once one of the largest in Europe. The ruins
have stood unattended since the end of World War II.
   Restoration efforts began in late 1988. When completed, the
building is to become an international center for Jewish culture and
tradition.
