<SECOND>AM-Justice-Opinion, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0755,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Says It Won't Show Congress FBI Policy Opinion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 19th graf: ``A senior,'' with further justification
for not publishing opinion.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Tuesday it won't
show a House subcommittee a legal opinion broadening FBI arrest
powers overseas because Congress is no more entitled to see it than
the public.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said the opinion
stating that FBI agents have legal authority to seize fugitives
overseas without permission of a foreign government is considered
private legal advice for the bureau that won't be made public.
   The opinion's author, Assistant Attorney General William P. Barr,
is scheduled to be questioned about it on Wednesday by members of
the House Judiciary subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights.
   Asked why the opinion, which is not classified, was being
withheld from members of the subcommittee, Runkel replied: ``Why
would we treat the committee any differently than the news media or
the general public?''
   ``Bill Barr will go up and talk about it and answer questions,
but it's in keeping with department policy not to make the opinion
public,'' Runkel said. ``It's our view that it's a confidential
legal opinion.''
   Runkel argued that the Justice Department is not privy to legal
opinions produced for Congress by House and Senate legal counsel.
   The Justice Department's Office of Legal Counsel, which Barr
heads, issued the June 21 opinion in response to a request for
advice from the FBI.
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., the subcommittee chairman, expressed
incredulity over Runkel's statement his panel was not entitled to
see the document.
   ``Maybe that Department of Justice needs more experience, it
needs an education about how the government is supposed to work in a
free society,'' Edwards said. ``And our hearing tomorrow, I hope,
will guide them along that path.''
   Besides approving the Justice Department's budget, Edwards noted
that the Judiciary Committee by law is required to oversee its
operations.
   ``That's what we take the oath of office to do,'' Edwards said.
   Barr was summoned along with Associate Deputy FBI Director Oliver
B. Revell to answer questions about the opinion, which sparked
veiled criticism last month from Secretary of State James Baker III.
   Baker called it ``a very narrow legal opinion based on
consideration only of domestic United States laws.'' The secretary
said ``it did not take into account international law, nor did it
weigh the president's constituitnal responsibliity to carry out the
foreign policy of the United States.''
   The document entitled ``Authority of the FBI to Override
Customary or Other International Law in the Course of
Extraterritorial Law Enforcement Activities'' reverses a 1980 legal
opinion that the FBI could not arrest a fugitive without obtaining a
foreign government's permission.
   The earlier opinion, written in response to a query over whether
the FBI had authority to seize fugitive financier Robert Vesco in
the Bahamas, was eventually published.
   Justice Department officials have stressed that the opinion is
aimed intended to clarify the FBI's legal authority to seize
fugitives from countries that do not cooperate with the United
States or where there is no law and order, such as in Lebanon.
   A senior department offici
</TEXT>
