<FIRST>u p AM-ELN--VaGovernor 1stLd-Writethru a0641 11-07 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Va Governor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wilder and Coleman Neck-and-Neck In Virginia Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with early returns showing Wilder
and Coleman about even; Terry winning attorney general race; picks up after
dash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat L. Douglas Wilder and Republican J.
Marshall Coleman were running even in early returns Tuesday in an
election that could make Wilder the nation's first elected black
governor.
   With 415 of 1,967 precincts counted, or 21 percent, Wilder and
Coleman each had 50 percent of the vote. Coleman had 176,364 votes
to Wilder's 172,894 votes.
   Many of the early returns were from traditionally conservative
Henrico County, a constituency expected to favor Coleman.
   The state's first woman attorney general, Democrat Mary Sue
Terry, won re-election against Republican state Sen. Joseph B.
Benedetti, with early returns giving her more than a 3-2 edge.
   The governor's race pitted two candidates with a history of
overcoming long odds and featured a high-profile debate over access
to abortion, which Wilder supports and Coleman opposes.
   Early turnout was described as heavy in most parts of the state.
``We're on roller skates,'' said Alice Lynch, the registrar in
Richmond, describing the action in her office. ``It seems like a
tremendous turnout.''
   The 58-year-old Wilder, who earned money for college by waiting
on tables at whites-only political dinners in downtown Richmond,
defied the conventional wisdom by winning election as lieutenant
governor in 1985.
   He is hoping to become the nation's first black governor since
Reconstruction, and the first one ever elected by the voters of his
state. The only other black governor, Pinckney B.S. Pinchback, was
appointed acting governor of Louisiana when the incumbent was
impeached in 1870.
   Coleman, a 47-year-old Republican who has battled his own party's
establishment repeatedly during his political career, is attempting
a comeback after losing the 1981 election for governor to Democrat
Charles S. Robb.
   In other races, Democrat Donald S. Beyer Jr. was leading
Republican Edwina P. Dalton, who had been favored to become the
state's first woman lieutenant governor. With 16 percent of the
precincts counted, Beyer had 54 percent of the vote to 46 percent
for Dalton.
</TEXT>
