<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Wounded     11-07 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Wounded,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wounded Rebels Occupy Church, Demand to Leave Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six wounded guerrillas and 25 of
their relatives occupied a Roman Catholic church Tuesday to demand
they and the others be allowed to leave the country for treatment.
   ``We are going to stay here as long as necessary to be able to
leave,'' said Rosa Elida, a 19-year-old former rebel for the
Farabundo Marti Liberation Front. Suffering from a leg wound, she
said she has been with the guerrilla forces for nine years.
   Ms. Elida said she had received primitive medical attention in a
rebel camp but still has difficulty walking and has not been able to
return to combat.
   The group took over Calvary Chruch in downtown San Salvador to
demand that President Alfredo Cristiani allow 109 of the war
casualties be allowed to go abroad for specialized medical care.
   An injured 18-year-old rebel, who gave his name only as Miguel,
said the occupation is indefinite.
   ``We will not move from here until we obtain evacuation,'' he
said.
   The group's evacuation had been scheduled for last May by the
government of then-President Jose Napoleon Duarte. It was suspended
in the face of strong opposition from the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, of Cristiani, who took office June 1.
   A group of 47 wounded rebels were allowed to leave for Cuba in
September after occupying the Metropolitan Cathedral for 43 days and
then taking refuge in the Mexican Embassy in San Salvador.
   Evacuations of Salvadoran war wounded began in 1984 under the
Duarte administration through negotiated exchanges of army officers
held by the guerrillas for the wounded. In 1987, agreements were
reached on evacuating the wounded without negotiations and exchanges.
   Since 1984, 393 former combatants have been given safe conduct
out of the country to receive medical attention and rehabilitation
in West Germany, Sweden, France and Cuba.
