<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Lebanon     11-07 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Lebanon,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Welcomes New Lebanese President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council on Tuesday night
hailed the election of Lebanon's new president under an Arab League
peace plan, a not-so-thinly veiled rebuke to Gen. Michel Aoun, who
rejects the development.
   Aoun, the Christian army commander, spurned the entire peace plan
adopted by Lebanon's Parliament on the ground it did not include a
timetable for withdrawal of 40,000 Syrian soldiers from Lebanon.
   The Security Council responded by adopting a unanimous statement
urging ``all sectors of the Lebanese people, including the armed
forces, to come to the support of their president.''
   The council members ``welcome the election of the president of
the Lebanese republic and the Taif agreement by the Lebanese
Parliament.'' The legislators adopted the changes at an emergency
meeting held in Taif, Saudi Arabia.
   Parliament met at Kleiat in Syrian-controlled northern Lebanon on
Sunday and elected Rene Mouawad, a Maronite Catholic, as president.
It endorsed political changes worked out by legislators at Taif with
Arab League mediation, which give Moslems more power in an effort to
end the 14-year-old civil war.
   The legislators met in northern Lebanon because Aoun threatened
to shell the Parliament building in Beirut.
   The Security Council said they ``pay particular tribute to the
high sense of responsibility and to the courage of the Lebanese
members of Parliament.''
   The Syrians are in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from
the Arab League. Aoun calls it an occupation army. A six-month
artillery war between Aoun's men and the Syrians killed hundreds of
people and wounded thousands before it was suspended by a truce in
September.
   Aoun and acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss have led competing
Christian and Moslem governments since September 1988, when the
six-year term of President Amin Gemayel ended without Parliament
agreeing on a successor.
   Lebanon's civil war has killed more than 150,000 people since
1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
