<FIRST>u p AM-ELN--FlorioProfile     11-07 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--Florio Profile,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>For New Jersey's James Florio, Third Time's A Charm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. James Florio has served eight terms in
Congress and wrote the nation's Superfund cleanup law. But he has
always made it clear that he would happily trade the nation's
Capitol for New Jersey's Statehouse.
   On his third try Tuesday, he made it. Florio, a 52-year-old
Democrat, was elected governor, easily defeating Republican Rep.
James Courter. The victory came eight years after Florio lost the
closest gubernatorial election in the state's history.
   For Florio, mastering subjects such as the environment and
transportation played well to New Jersey residents, who live in a
pollution-riddled and traffic-clogged state.
   ``I didn't pick these topics because I wanted to be governor,''
Florio said. ``I've been involved in environmental legislation for
20 years. I was a bird-watcher when I was a kid.''
   The son of an Italian immigrant shipyard painter, Florio was born
in Brooklyn and left high school at age 17 to join the Navy. He
earned his high school equivalency diploma, and later degrees from
Trenton State College and Rutgers University Law School.
   After three terms in the state Assembly, he was elected to
Congress in the Democrats' 1974 ``Watergate'' freshman class. His
district takes in Camden, an aging industrial city just across the
Delaware River from Philadelphia.
   Florio gained statewide recognition when he ran fourth in his
party's 1977 gubernatorial primary. He won the Democratic nomination
in 1981, but lost the general election to Republican Thomas H. Kean
by 1,797 votes out of nearly 2.4 million cast. Kean went on to
become one of the most popular modern governors, but was barred by
state law from seeking a third consecutive term.
   In 1981, Florio was criticized as being an icy candidate who
couldn't relate to people. He set out to change that this year, and
jokingly referred to himself as ``warm and wonderful.'' He became
Florio the people-meeter.
   Friends say a big part of the transformation is attributed to a
happier personal life. But others say the ``new Florio'' persona has
been carefully crafted by an experienced campaign staff.
   Florio ran as a loner in 1981 while separated from his first
wife. This time, he campaigned with his new wife, Lucinda, a school
teacher. He drew approving cheers throughout the campaign by
mentioning his two new grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
