<DOCNO> AP891107-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 2059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Aquino     11-07 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aquino,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Aquino Defends Her Government's Human Rights Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino of the Philippines on
Tuesday defended her government's record on human rights, saying she
was personally committed because she had been a victim of abuses.
   Speaking with reporters following a meeting with Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney, she said, ``I would like to tell you that having
been a victim of human rights abuses myself, I am certainly
committed. In fact I have stated throughout my administration that
we will not tolerate any violations of human rights.''
   Her husband, Benigno Aquino, was shot to death in 1983 at the
Manila airport when he returned from self-exile in the United States
to campaign against President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino became president after Marcos was ousted in a
military-civilian uprising in February 1986.
   Several human rights groups claim Mrs. Aquino's government has
failed to control army and paramilitary groups that the groups say
violate rights in the fight against Communist rebels.
   Mrs. Aquino is on a four-day visit to Canada and then will go to
the United States for four days.
   She said she hears few complaints about human rights abuses until
she travels abroad.
   ``We have a very free press in the Philippines and I want to tell
the Canadians that very rarely does this (allegations of rights
violations) appear in our press,'' she said. ``I am really surprised
that it is only in foreign countries that there is so much talk
about alleged human rights abuses.''
   Mulroney, also speaking with reporters after a 90-minute meeting
with Mrs. Aquino in the Parliament building, said he has done much
to improve human rights. He also said she had done a remarkable job
in transforming her country from a dictatorship to a democracy.
   ``We are very interested in helping her along the road to greater
reforms and greater democracy ... as opposed to inhibiting any flow
of aid at all,'' he said.
   Foreign Secretary Joe Clark announced that Canada would provide
$100 million in new aid for the Philippines. He said the money would
be used to purchase commodities and telecommunications equipment,
help fund anti-poverty organizations and support an environmental
management program.
   Mrs. Aquino has said a main goal of her trip is to encourage
foreign investments in the Philippines.
</TEXT>
