<FIRST>u p AM-ELN--NewYorkMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0665 11-07 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ELN--New York Mayor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0665,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Yorkers Pick New Mayor: First Black or Republican Reformer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with TV stations calling race for Dinkins based on exit
polls, minor editing below dash. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters decided New York City's most contentious
mayoral election in more than a decade Tuesday, choosing between a
Democrat who would be the first black to win City Hall and a
Republican running as a reformer.
   Three network-owned television stations projected Democrat David
Dinkins as the winner over Republican nominee Rudolph W. Giuliani.
WABC-TV, WCBS-TV and WNBC-TV called the contest based on surveys of
voters leaving polling places as soon as they closed at 9 p.m.
   Dinkins, the Manhattan borough president, maintained the
multiracial support that enabled him to defeat three-term incumbent
Mayor Edward I. Koch in the Democratic primary, according to
pre-election polls.
   Giuliani, hamstrung by the vast Democratic majority in New York,
accepted the tiny Liberal Party's nomination in a bid to fashion a
reform-minded ``fusion'' candidacy that crossed party lines.
   In late morning, under a clear sky and bright sunshine, Board of
Elections spokesman Jon Del Giorno said he expected the predicted
turnout of 60 percent to 65 percent to hold up.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Giuliani, 45, a former federal prosecutor making his first run
for elective office, sharply criticized Dinkins throughout the
56-day campaign, calling him a clubhouse politician with
questionable ethical standards.
   Dinkins criticized his opponent's change of views on abortion _
Giuliani first opposed it, then reversed himself _ and his
qualifications for office.
   Dinkins also drew the contest as a battle between Democrats and
the Republican Party, which he blamed for deep federal budget cuts
in urban programs. Many prominent Democrats campaigned and
advertised for him.
   Mainly, though, the 62-year-old Dinkins stressed his theme of
social healing, repeatedly referring to New York's ethnic and racial
groups as ``a gorgeous mosaic'' stitched together by common
interests. Both candidates asked that they be judged on their
abilities, not their race.
   Dinkins was propelled by his solid defeat of Koch, the ebullient
but often-abrasive mayor since 1977. The city's Democratic
organizations and most unions lined up with Dinkins, providing him
endorsements, donations and thousands of volunteers. Koch worked and
advertised for his conqueror.
   The general election was the most hotly contested since Koch beat
Mario Cuomo, running as a Liberal, in 1977.
   Giuliani's most daunting hurdle was the Democrats' monster edge
in voter registration: Democrats outnumber Republicans by a 5-1
margin in New York, 2.2 million to 450,000. There are an additional
460,000 independents.
   To overcome that disadvantage Giuliani tried to remake the
cross-party ``fusion'' candidacies fashioned by the three
Republicans elected mayor this century _ Seth Low in 1901, Fiorello
H. La Guardia in 1933, 1937 and 1941, and John V. Lindsay in 1965.
   In appealing for Democratic defectors, Giuliani stressed his
record as a corruption-fighting prosecutor and hammered at Dinkins'
sloppy financial record-keeping, including his failure to file
income taxes from 1969-72.
   Dinkins said the tax lapse was an oversight and a thing of the
past. But there were damaging reports of more recent flaws:
conflicting valuations Dinkins assigned to stock that he transferred
to his son in 1986; failure to disclose a friend's partial funding
of a vacation he took to France; two votes by aides, acting in his
place, that contravened an Ethics Board recommendation.
   Dinkins also underwent repeated questioning about his
relationship with Jesse Jackson, whose 1988 presidential campaign he
headed in the state. Jackson is anathema to some Jewish voters
because of his support for Palestinian rights and his 1984 reference
to New York as ``Hymietown.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
