<FIRST>u w AM-US-Aquino     11-07 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Aquino,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Upbeat U.S. Expectations for Aquino Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States expects a broad agreement on
renewing the lease for military bases in the Philippines when
President Corazon Aquino makes her second official visit to this
country this week, a senior administration official said.
   ``This is going to be an important and, we think, a very
successful visit,'' said the official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The official also told reporters the United States is confident
``that, at the end of the day, there will be an agreement'' on U.S.
use of military bases in the Philippines beyond expiration in 1991
of the current arrangement.
   The issue is expected to come up during Mrs. Aquino's scheduled
meeting with President Bush at the White House Thursday, and the two
countries have agreed to start formal negotiations next month on
extending their bases agreement.
   Mrs. Aquino arrives from New York Wednesday evening on the second
U.S. state visit of her presidency. White House talks and a state
dinner hosted by Bush, meetings with Cabinet secretaries and leaders
of both houses of Congress and visits to the International Monetary
Fund, Arlington National Cemetery and the National Museum of Natural
History are on her two-day schedule in the capital.
   Predicting ``long and very complicated'' negotiations over the
future of Clark Field, Subic Bay naval station and four smaller U.S.
bases, the official said, ``we think there's a logic that both
parties will see ... that these facilities do, in fact, serve the
interests of both countries in very important ways.''
   ``I think that will be the compelling fact that will assert
itself, and I think we will have an agreement. We're going into it
with that frame of mind,'' he said.
   Despite the drop in East-West tension, the bases remain important
to Philippines and regional security and ``are regarded by every
government in East Asia as a stabilizing factor,'' the U.S. official
said.
   ``They are a known quantity and an important representation of
the United States commitment to the security and stability of the
region ... and I think that's a sentiment still widely shared
throughout the region.''
   The main purpose of Mrs. Aquino's visit is to stimulate interest
in trade and investment, along with a continued flow of development
aid, the official noted.
   He said Philippines officials are in the final stages of reaching
agreement with creditors on a buyback of up to $1.4 billion worth of
the country's foreign debt. ``We hope it succeeds. We will help it
succeed if we can,'' he said.
</TEXT>
