<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Matsuda     11-07 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Matsuda,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor Yusaka Matsuda Dead at 39</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yusaku Matsuda, the award-winning actor who played a
murderer in the current U.S. film ``Black Rain,'' has died of
bladder cancer. He was 39.
   Matsuda died at a Tokyo hospital Monday. He had been hospitalized
since Oct. 7.
   Matsuda won the Japan Academy Award and the Kinema Junpo award
for best actor for his role in the 1983 film satire ``Kazoku Geimu''
(``Family Game''), directed by Yoshimitsu Morita. In the film, which
was a critical hit in the United States as well as Japan, Matsuda
portrays a sadistic private tutor coaching a high school student
through ``examination hell.''
   In his last film, ``Black Rain,'' Matsuda played an ambitious
yakuza gangster who committed a murder in New York. Michael Douglas
played the American detective who brought him back to Japan and
pursued him through the streets of Osaka after he escaped custody.
   Matsuda also co-starred with Olympic gold medalist Florence
Griffith-Joyner in a 140-minute television drama that aired Oct. 7.
In ``Karei-naru Tsuiseki'' (``The Great Pursuit''), Matsuda played a
detective who helps a sports journalist, played by Griffith-Joyner,
in investigating a plane accident in which she lost her adopted
child.
   Matsuda was known for his frequent real-life brawls as well as
his slender build and cool, cynical style. He made his first
appearance on screen in 1973 and appeared in numerous TV and screen
films.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</TEXT>
