<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayLandslide     11-07 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Landslide,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landslide Closes Pacific Coast Highway</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wave of mud and rocks cascaded down a
hillside and across the Pacific Coast Highway on Tuesday, sweeping
three cars across the scenic route and closing it for at least 24
hours, authorities said.
   Two people were treated for injuries at a hospital.
   Motorists said they were suddenly cloaked in darkness as a wall
of mud ripped across all four lanes. The renowned highway, marked as
State Route 1, links Los Angeles with Malibu, Oxnard and other
northern coastal communities.
   ``All of a sudden it got dark and my sister said, `My God it's a
landslide,''' said Judy Lester, a passenger. ``We broke through the
dirt, she steered very hard. We went into the side of the hill, did
a 360 (-degree turn) and went in backwards. It just engulfed us.''
   By late Tuesday, much of the debris had been cleared but the
highway remained closed. Fire officials said homes perched on the
hill over the highway, with a panoramic view of the Pacific, were in
no immediate danger from the slide.
</TEXT>
