<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Aftershock     11-07 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Aftershock,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aftershock of 4.3 Magnitude Causes No Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS GATOS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate aftershock from the killer
earthquake three weeks ago rattled the Santa Cruz Mountains and
nearby areas on Tuesday, injuring at least one person but causing no
property damage, officials said.
   A woman fell down at a shopping center and broke an arm, said
police in Los Gatos, which is nearly 45 miles southeast of San
Francisco.
   The quake measured 4.3 on the Richter scale, making it the 23rd
aftershock of magnitude 4.0 or higher since the Oct. 17 quake that
caused 66 deaths and an estimated $17 billion in property damage.
   That quake, which registered 7.1 on the Richter scale, was
centered in the Santa Cruz Mountains. The center of Tuesday's
aftershock was 12 miles southwest of San Jose and 17 miles north
Santa Cruz, and was felt as far north as San Francisco.
   ``It was a pretty good shake,'' said Capt. Bob Schuster of the
Los Gatos Police Department.
   ``It was scary,'' said Dinah Phillips, a Santa Cruz County public
information officer.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
</TEXT>
