<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Nov. 10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Failure to engage the ``cultural right'' may
have contrtibuted to the membership slump in mainline churches,
says a researcher into church lifestyles.
   The Rev. Tex Sample, an ethicist-theologian at the St. Paul
School of Theology in Kansas City, Mo., characterizes the
``cultural right'' as ``life-oriented, respectable, traditional''
and intensely patriotic.
   Reporting findings for a new book, ``U.S. Lifestyles in Mainline
Churches,'' he told the United Methodist General Council on
Ministries that seminarians often do not learn to relate well to
rank-and-file people.
   He said the mainline churches should take some cues from a
predominant ``cultural right,'' numbering at least 60 million
Americans, on church growth, evangelism, social justice and
inclusiveness.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of Reformed Church
ministers in three Netherland provinces finds that one in 10 would
rather have another job. The report notes that the ministers work
an average 58 hours a week, compared to 38 for Dutch workers
overall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida Baptists have voted overwhelmingly
to condemn abortion and support restrictive legislation.
   With only scattered opposition, 1,656 ``messengers'' from 2,057
congregations of the Florida Baptist Convention approved a
resolution declaring:
   ``We believe human life to be sacred and that it begins at
conception. ... The right of life must be protected by the state.
We call upon Florida Baptists to support legislation that will
achieve the dramatic saving and nurturing of human life.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Jewish Committee has established
a Pacific Rim Institute to facilitate understanding with the
growing Asian American population and with increasingly influential
Asian nations.
   Bruce M. Ramer, chairman of AJC's trustees, told its executive
council Asian immigration and trade now far surpass that from
Europe and work is needed to improve relations with that sector and
counter some anti-Semitic tendencies in it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Church of Christ has decided to
hire a full-time staff member to coordinate its AIDS ministry and
to launch in 1990 a series of educational projects on the disease.
   The Rev. Charles Shelby Rooks, exeuctive vice president of the
denomination's Board of Homeland Ministries, termed the church's
commitment to AIDS ministry ``an act of justice to overcome fear
and discrimination ... and an act of compassion to the sick.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-three percent of older Americans, age 60
or older, believe in life after death, according to a survey by
Mark Clements Research Inc. for Parade magazine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a commemorative conference of the
Episcopal Church marking the 200th anniversary of the American
version of the Book of Common Prayer, church historian John Booty
said the book fostered the church's ``comprehensiveness and
inclusiveness.''
   Booty, of the University of the South's School of Theology, said
the Episcopal Church ``has been a church of reconciliation in a
pluralistic society.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishops' committe has urged
priests and parents to encourage young men to enter the priesthood
and religious life.
   Citing the shortage of priests, the committee on vocations asked
``our brother priests and each parish community to nuture vocations
and call forth individuals to look specifically at priesthood and
religious life.''
   In a statement issued to coincide with the November observance
of the bicentennial of establishment of the Catholic Church in the
United States, the committee said:
   ``As we continue to call forth the laity to vital roles in our
local churches, we cannot forget to call forth priests to gather
this community around Christ in the eucharist.''
</TEXT>
