<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Jillian Adv24-26   11-07 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Jillian, Adv 24-26,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ann Jillian Returns in New Comedy Series</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Jillian says her new comedy series for
NBC brings out her motherly instincts.
   Jillian, who has no children, plays the mother of 14-year-old
actress Lisa Rieffel in ``Ann Jillian,'' as the show is called.
   ``She makes me miss having a teen-age daughter,'' she said.
``Our relationship is the whole basis of the show. I've just lost a
husband and she's lost a father and we're very supportive of each
other. It's a comedy, but it's about self-esteem, friendship and
trust. There are a lot of young people in the show, but always the
focus is on that magical relationship between a mother and
daughter.''
   The series marks Jillian's return to regular television after
numerous TV movies and miniseries. In 1985 she underwent a double
mastectomy for breast cancer. Her last series was a brief return to
``It's a Living'' when the former ABC comedy was picked up for
syndication. She starred in NBC's ``Jennifer Slept Here'' in
1983-84, and as a child she was in ``Hazel.''
   Jillian also stars with Tim Matheson in the NBC movie ``Little
White Lies,'' a romantic comedy filmed partially on location in
Rome. Both the movie and premiere of the series were tentatively
set for late November or early December.
   In ``Ann Jillian,'' she plays a recently widowed woman who moves
to a small Northern California town where she and her husband spent
their honeymoon. She takes a job in a Victorian-style shop that
sells coffee, jams, cookies and muffins.
   ``Our dream had been to return to the town,'' she said. ``You
know, with the porch swing and everything. But her husband was
killed on the job as a fireman.''
   She calls ``Little White Lies'' her reintroduction to the
audience before the premiere of ``Ann Jillian.'' Her last movie was
``Original Sin,'' telecast by NBC last February.
   ``This is the first funny thing I've done in years,'' she said.
``The past four or five things I've done have all been dramas. I'm
not complaining. I got three Emmy nominations and two Golden Globe
nominations. I won a Golden Globe for `The Ann Jillian Story.'''
   That movie told of her battle against cancer.
   In ``Little White Lies,'' Jillian plays a policewoman who goes
to Rome on vacation and meets a doctor played by Matheson. However,
each lies to the other and makes up a phony background. She tells
Matheson she's a business executive and he tells her he's a
hospital orderly.
   She wants to keep her identity secret because she thinks men
want to date her so she can fix traffic tickets. He's afraid that
women only want to go out with him because they want to marry a
doctor.
   ``We were in Rome for only three days, so we spent long hours in
front of the camera,'' said Jillian, who was accompanied by her
husband and manager, Andy Murcia. ``We started before dawn each day
and worked until late at night. Andy and I had been there on
vacation a month before so we were able to suggest the best places
to film.''
   Her husband makes his film debut in ``Little White Lies'' as a
loudmouth American tourist.
   ``He plays a patient of Tim's who nearly gives away his phony
identity,'' she said. ``I felt like a stage mother. I wanted to
tell Andy, `Smile, baby.' He hit his marks and was great.
   ``If the movie does well in the ratings we could do some
sequels. The chemistry between Tim and I was wonderful, which you
really need for a romantic comedy. We had to do a lot of kissing
and after a while it became technical just figuring out how to do
it different each time. We had one kissing scene in which the
cinematographer caught a flash of gold light behind us as the sun
sparkled on the Tiber River and the dome of St. Peter's at the
Vatican.''
   Jillian went through some training at the Los Angeles Police
Academy and talked to some women detectives to prepare for her role.
   She also got some pointers from her husband, a former police
sergeant in Chicago.
   ``Andy showed me how to use a gun, although my character doesn't
use one in the picture,'' she said. ``He showed me simple things
like how to flip a badge. I'd come home from filming and talk
police jargon and Andy would laugh. He said: `It's a trade. I'm an
actor now and you're a cop.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26</NOTE>
