<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-RedfordtheActivist Adv12   11-07 1220</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Redford the Activist, Adv 12,1254</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robert Redford Uses Star Status in Down-to-Earth Activism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUNDANCE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At Robert Redford's place, even the
senators wear blue jeans.
   For years, this rustic mountain resort was the private hideaway
of Redford the movie star. But now, Redford the environmental
activist has opened it to a high-powered crowd. He's enlisting
politicians, business leaders, scientists and others to help him
find common ground in the polarized landscape of environmental
politics.
   Lured by Redford's fame, they play by Redford's rules: Leave the
stiff collars and rigid ideologies at home; relax and try to see
opponents as at least partly human.
   Redford has long been known as one of Hollywood's premier
do-gooders, using the rugged, casual charm that launched his film
career to call attention to environmental issues.
   But as times change, so does Redford.
   At 52, he has softened the radical edges that marked his early
activism. Since 1983, when he founded the Institute for Resource
Management, he has been more mediator than instigator, drawing
together adversaries in disputes such as Bering Sea oil exploration
and energy development on Navajo lands.
   The normally low-key institute took a higher profile in August
by sponsoring ``Greenhouse Glasnost.'' It was an unusual meeting of
American and Soviet officials, scientists, environmentalists and
entertainers designed to highlight the threat of global warming due
to the greenhouse effect.
   Last month, Redford tackled nuclear energy, bringing together
industry representatives and environmentalists at Sundance to
debate whether the nation's struggling nuclear power industry
should be revived.
   Activism is nothing new to Hollywood, where almost every cause
has its celebrity champion. But Redford, in an interview, explained
that his passion for the environment long preceded his stardom.
   He was 10 years old, recovering from a mild case of polio, when
his mother took him to Yosemite National Park. He was awestruck.
``I said to myself, `That's it _ I want to be a part of that.'
   ``I shifted right then. I spent more time outdoors. I started to
hike. I went to Yosemite to work, and I learned to climb there.''
   His native Los Angeles, booming after World War II, also
affected him.
   ``The air was going bad. The fruit groves were disappearing and
giving way to malls and suburbs. Everybody just came and grabbed
what they could grab and built what they could build. I took that
personally. I wanted out of there.''
   His wanderings took him to Colorado, Europe and New York. But he
knew in 1961 that he had found home when he and his wife, Lola Van
Wagenen, bought two acres in a canyon near Mount Timpanagos. Here,
in the rugged beauty of Utah's Wasatch Range, he could ski some of
the West's finest powder and find the empty, silent spaces he
craved.
   He expanded the homestead as his film career gained speed. After
several successful movies in the late '60s, culminating with
``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' he bought nearly the whole
canyon, complete with a rundown ski resort. He named it after his
character in the movie.
   But he soon discovered he couldn't hide from the development
pressures that had forced him from Los Angeles. Highway officials
proposed widening the Provo Canyon road, which passes near
Sundance. Redford campaigned against it, arguing the project would
help only truckers while ruining a peaceful canyon and a popular
trout-fishing stream.
   That local involvement led to environmental battles around the
country. He lent his name to liberal political candidates; he
showed up at scenic rivers and toxic waste sites; he lobbied for
energy-conservation laws.
   In 1975, a consortium of utilities proposed building a
coal-fired power plant on Utah's Kaiparowits Plateau. Redford
researched the project, concluded it was a boondoggle, and jumped
into the fray. The project was shelved, and Redford was burned in
effigy by angry opponents.
   Despite his victories, Redford disliked the contentiousness of
environmental politics and the ``boneheaded arguments'' he heard on
both sides.
   His presence publicized issues, but it also heightened
opposition. ``You were almost canceling yourself out,'' he said.
   He founded the Institute for Resource Management so he could
take a quieter, less inflammatory role.
   It complements another Redford organization also dedicated to
the human factor. His Sundance Institute has sponsored film, dance
and screenwriting workshops at the resort since 1980, helping
independent artists pursue their visions without the pressure to
``go commercial.''
   The IRM works on the premise that nobody, including an
industrialist, wants to destroy the planet. Typically the institute
puts adversaries together in a room for a few days and lets them
seek their own solutions.
   Not all conferences occur at Sundance. One of the institute's
best-known attempts to reach common ground started at sea _ and
nearly sank there.
   It was August 1985, the issue was oil drilling in the Bering
Sea, and Redford thought a pleasure cruise in California's Morro
Bay would ease tensions between the oil executives and
environmentalists who had reluctantly agreed to meet.
   But the adversaries weren't talking, and the boat started
heaving in 9-foot waves. ``Pretty soon everyone was sick,'' Redford
said. ``The image of environmentalists and industry heads throwing
up together was something I won't forget. I also thought it was the
end of our organization.''
   It proved instead to be the human factor he seeks, eroding
participants' reserve. The conference led to an extraordinary
agreement that recommended drilling in some areas and placing
others off-limits.
   Interior Department officials say they adopted many of the
agreement's provisions in their Bering Sea drilling plans _ though
not enough to satisfy Redford, who still contends the agency
``shelved it.''
   Redford manages to avoid the Hollywood penchant for all flash
and little substance, said Frederic Krupp, executive director of
the Environmental Defense Fund, who spoke of the actor-activist's
``vision and hard work.''
   Redford also is gaining some friends in industry. His old
nemesis from the Kaiparowits battle _ Howard Allen, head of
Southern California Edison _ now is chairman of the IRM board.
   ``In recent years,'' Allen said, ``he has developed a cautious
respect for productivity, economic considerations and balance.''
   He's also developing new ways to integrate his film career and
environmental interests. His two institutes collaborated this year
on a documentary, narrated by Redford, about Yosemite. And last
year Redford directed ``The Milagro Beanfield War,'' in which poor
New Mexican villagers battle a recreational development. The
villagers win, of course.
   Redford's own development at Sundance aims to complement nature.
Architectural Digest recently praised the resort's attempt to
``echo the canyon's geology'' with rough-hewn siding and old
tree-trunk columns that help the auditorium, lodge and guest
cottages blend into the background.
   Once a year, Redford requires all Sundance employees to drop
their usual tasks and plant a tree. At the global warming
conference, while speeches droned on, Redford sometimes gazed
wistfully out the window at children playing by a pond.
   It was the human factor again.
   ``At the point when people start repeating themselves, or the
same person wants more time on the floor, that's the time to get
out,'' he said. ``That's the time to go plant a tree.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
