<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-07 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0810</SECOND>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc. announced it had ceased all
scheduled passenger service immediately because a severe cash
shortage doomed the airline's bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   William G. McGee, chairman, president and chief executive
officer, said Monday the action was taken to preserve assets while
Braniff continues to develop alternatives, which might include
selling the airline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court removed the last legal
obstacle to carrying out a $2.5 billion settlement for victims of
the Dalkon Shield birth-control device.
   The justices, over one dissenting vote, on Monday rejected a
challenge by about 650 women to the settlement reached with A.H.
Robins Co., manufacturer of the intrauterine device.
   In another action, the high court agreed to decide in a case
from Illinois whether lawsuits charging employers with violating a
key federal anti-bias law must be filed in federal _ not state _
courts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. once again is facing tough
financial times, but things are different than they were 12 years
ago when Chairman Lee Iacocca sought help in Congress for loan
insurance.
   The company, analysts said Monday, is moving aggressively to cut
its costs and improve profitability, and the next target may be
labor. Chrysler is trying to carve $1 billion from its $26 billion
annual budget and is trimming its salaried work force by about 8
percent, or 2,300 jobs.
   The company is changing its structure, but not key personnel or
their titles. Chrysler Motors Corp., the carmaking arm of the
company, will cease to be on New Year's Day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners wants to ruffle the feathers of
UAL Corp. and force a payday for investors, but it's unclear
whether its efforts to shake up United Airlines' parent will fly
with shareholders and fractious unions.
   Coniston, a New York investment group, has made money from
United before, when it helped force the airline's former parent,
Allegis Corp., to restructure in 1987.
   Things may be more complicated the second time around, in the
wake of a failed $6.75 billion buyout attempt by a pilot-management
group and with United's three largest unions seeking new contracts,
analysts said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savings and loan regulators announced new, more
stringent financial standards for the nation's thrift institutions
and reported another heavy loss for the industry in the
July-September quarter.
   The financial standards, announced Monday by the Office of
Thrift Supervision in Washington, will require S&amp;L owners starting
Dec. 7 to back their lending with more of their own capital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five former officials of Princeton-Newport
Partners LP and a former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader were
sentenced to three- and six-month prison terms in the first
racketeering trial of securities professionals.
   The sentences pronounced Monday by U.S. District Judge Robert
Carter were considerably less than the maximum 20 years the
defendants faced on the racketeering count.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese companies are building plants in this
country to ride U.S. coattails into European markets in the next
decade, Texas oilman T. Boone Pickens said.
   Pickens also told a news conference Monday that legislation may
be needed to restrict Japanese investment in this country until the
Japanese open up their financial markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Chicago Mercantile Exchange chairman
failed to stop two employees of his trading firm from
systematically defrauding customers, a Commodity Futures Trading
Commission attorney said.
   Brian Monieson, head of GNP Commodities Inc., ``refused to see
what everyone else could see, and that was that his customers were
being robbed,'' CFTC attorney Patricia Donahue said Monday at an
administrative proceeding against Monieson and the others. But
Monieson's attorney, Jerrold Salzman, said the CFTC's case is
flawed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional inaction on a bill raising the
federal debt ceiling forced the Treasury to postpone its weekly
bill auction and threatened the government with its first default
in history.
   The Treasury had planned to offer $16 billion in three- and
six-month bills Monday, but postponed the sale because Congress has
not completed action on legislation to increase the statutory debt
limit.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Worries about corporate profits and interest-rate uncertainties
combined to drive stock prices sharply lower in a ``blue Monday''
atmosphere on Wall Street. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
fell 47.34 points to 2,582.17.
   The dollar ended higher against most key currencies. Gold prices
also rose.
   Bond prices finished slightly lower.
   Precious metal futures prices rose; grain and soybean futures
were mixed; sugar was lower; oil futures were mixed; copper prices
fell; and livestock and pork futures were higher.
</TEXT>
