<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SoftwareTalks     11-07 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Software Talks,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unix Rivals to Step Up Talks on Cooperation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rivals for control of the Unix software standard
say they are expanding discussions on cooperation that could lead
to a healing of the split between them.
   The statement Monday was good news for computer users, who have
been pressing hard for a single Unix standard. Unix is a base layer
of software that makes it possible for programs to run on many
different kinds of computers, the same way compact discs can be
played on many different brands of compact disc players.
   Unix is split now between a group that includes American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., the originator of Unix, and a rival camp
whose main members are International Business Machines Corp.,
Digital Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.
   The split means that programs written for one version of Unix
won't necessarily work with the other version. The latest AT&amp;T
version was released last week, while the one from the rival Open
Software Foundation is due out in late 1990.
   ``What we're trying to do is remove the assumption and
perception that we're all competing with each other,'' David Tory,
the president and chief executive of the Open Software Foundation,
said in a telephone interview.
   ``We genuinely want to converge, both parties, and the industry
wants us to as well,'' Tory said.
   Discussions have been going on for the past year, and if they go
well they may lead to ``something big and dramatic'' around the end
of this year, said AT&amp;T's Michael DeFazio, director of system
software for the company's Unix software operation.
   Even if the talks don't result in a major breakthrough, the two
groups will continue working on areas of cooperation in the area of
open software, DeFazio said.
   IBM, Digital and others formed the Open Software Foundation in
May 1988 out of fear that AT&amp;T was controlling Unix for its own
commercial advantage. AT&amp;T attempted to allay such fears by ceding
control of Unix standards to an independent group called Unix
International, of which it is a member.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Pepsi-VideoGame     11-07 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepsi-Video Game,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Next Maybe Mario Brothers Will Endorse a Brand of Mustache Wax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pepsi logo will appear in a new Nintendo
video game, making Pepsi-Cola Co. the first soft drink maker to tap
into electronic games for commercial exposure, the companies said.
   Under an agreement announced Monday between Pepsi and Tradewest,
which is licensed to manufacture video games for Nintendo of
America Inc., Pepsi's logo will be featured in Magic Johnson's Fast
Break.
   The professional-style video basketball game, to be released
early next year, is set in an arena packed with cheering fans.
   The Pepsi name appears in the game's opening title sequence and
on signs at courtside. The soft drink maker's logo also is on the
scoreboard shown at the end of each quarter.
   ``Pepsi's identification in the game mirrors the real life
display of logos and banners that adorn athletic venues across the
country,'' said Michael D. Simpson, Pepsi's executive vice
president of marketing and national sales.
   The amount of money Pepsi is paying to be a make-belive game
sponsor was not disclosed.
   Only one other company ever has had its symbol shown in a
Nintendo game. The Racket Attack game used the logo of the Wilson
tennis racket and sporting goods manufacturer.
   The hookup between Pepsi and Nintendo is part of a trend that
has developed as companies search for alternative advertising
outlets.
   ``As traditional advertising mediums become increasingly
cluttered and segmented, advertisers must respond creatively,''
Simpson said.
   The proliferation of commercials on television plus changes in
viewing habits _ including the widespread use of video cassette
recorders and the practice of changing channels to zap past
commercials _ has persuaded advertisers to promote products in new
ways.
   Pepsi has had some experience and success with nontraditional
marketing methods. For instance in 1987, Pepsi placed the first
commercial ever on a home video cassette, putting the Diet Pepsi
``Mustang'' ad was placed on the film ``Top Gun.''
   The beverage giant says video games potentially are a major
marketing medium. It is estimated that nearly 26 percent of U.S.
households will own a video game machine by the end of this year.
   Nintendo's entertainment system that turns a TV set into a game
screen is projected to be in 22 percent of American homes by the
end of this year.
   Nintendo of America, a subsidiary of Japan's Nintendo Co. Ltd.,
dominates the U.S. electronic games market. Some of its most
popular titles feature the mustachioed Mario Brothers.
   Pepsi already has a promotional alliance with Nintendo on a $10
million national campaign for the holiday season.
   During the two-month campaign, which began Nov. 1, Pepsi will
give away thousands of Nintendo's newest gadget, the Game Boy
hand-held video game, through contests and sweepstakes. Other
Nintendo and Pepsi products also will be available through the
promotion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891107-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler Bjt   11-07 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler, Bjt,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler on a Crash Diet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Times are tough again for Chrysler Corp., which
has launched a crash diet to shed $1 billion in expenses in 14
months, but the atmosphere that led to concession contracts in the
early 1980s isn't present this time around.
   ``There is a lot of bad news that's coming all at once,''
analyst John Kirnan of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. Inc. in New York said
Monday. ``But I think management should be given credit for taking
the initiative for what the market is going to be like in the
1990s.''
   On Jan. 1, Chrysler Motors Corp., the carmaking arm of the
company, will cease to exist as a separate division, spokesman
Steve Harris said Monday. No key personnel or titles will change,
Harris said.
   ``We're merging Chrysler Motors into Chrysler Corp. and the
legal entity of Chrysler Motors goes away,'' Harris said. ``The
move is purely technical, legal and tax-oriented. It will not have
any impact on people or titles and will not change the company's
internal or external operation in any way.''
   Harris declined to say how much tax money the company expects to
save because of the move.
   That news comes on the heels of Chrysler's announcement Friday
that it will stop car production at its Jefferson Avenue assembly
plant in Detroit in February, more than a year earlier than
originally anticipated, will cut one of two shifts at its carmaking
plant in St. Louis and close a parts plant in Wisconsin next year.
   About 4,000 hourly workers will be affected. The consolidation
involves the elimination of the Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon
subcompact models.
   Within the next year, Chrysler will face increasing competition
for its two most profitable vehicles _ Jeeps and minivans _ and
will deal with lower earnings due to the projected softening in the
North American auto market. And it will sit down at the bargaining
table with the United Auto Workers union.
   On Friday, UAW Vice President Stan Marshall, in charge of the
union's Chrysler Department, sounded an ominous note as the UAW
prepares preliminary work toward negotiations next summer.
   ``This decision is bound to have a detrimental impact on our
future relations,'' Marshall said of Chrysler's announcement
Friday. ``It reinforces the view that the corporation's commitment
to retaining the good faith and loyalty of its workers is sorely
lacking when the going gets tough.''
   While things are tough for Chrysler this year, they aren't the
same as they were a decade ago, when Chairman Lee Iacocca was
haunting the halls of Congress looking for guarantees for millions
of dollars in state and federal loans.
   A dozen years ago, interest rates and gasoline prices were much
higher than now and the Japanese auto invasion was gearing up to
rob U.S. makers of their market share.
   Chrysler had to go to the federal government to guarantee
millions of dollars in loans to keep it afloat. It also went to the
UAW with contracts calling for worker concessions.
   During the 1980s, Chrysler and the UAW agreed to modify work
rules at some plants and to cooperate on everything from factory
floor decisions to those made in the board room.
   In 1990, for the first time in years, the UAW's contracts with
the Big Three expire on the same day, Sept. 14. And an end may be
at hand to the practice of ``pattern bargaining,'' in which the
union targets one company, reaches a contract with it and then
signs similar agreements with the other two, said labor analyst
Dale Brickner.
   ``What you're going to see is contracts tailored to individual
corporations,'' said Brickner, associate director of the School of
Labor and Industrial Relations at Michigan State University in East
Lansing. ``The old theory of pattern bargaining is a dead duck.''
   Marshall says that's bunk.
   ``We just got back to pattern bargaining again and that's
exactly where we'll stay,'' he said Monday. ``Chrysler's profits
are still way up from where they were during the lean time.''
   In the first nine months of 1980, Chrysler lost $1.48 billion;
during the same time this year, it made $717.5 million.
   ``They are getting too worried about their stockholders and not
enough about their workers,'' Marshall said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
