<FIRST>r f PM-TradeBarriers Bjt   11-07 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade Barriers, Bjt,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Gets an Earful on U.S.-Japanese Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While U.S. and Japanese negotiators resumed
talks on how to eliminate structural barriers that have contributed
to the $50 billion trade deficit with Japan, American business
leaders were telling Congress why the talks were needed.
   They told a Senate panel Monday that they are more interested in
opening up Japanese markets than protecting American markets.
   The business leaders also told the Senate Finance Committee's
international trade subcommittee that changes are needed on both
sides of the Pacific to solve the U.S.-Japanese trade imbalance.
   ``Japan's systems for buying and distributing goods are the
biggest obstacle facing U.S. manufacturers who export or do
business in Japan,'' said R.K. Morris, director of international
trade policy for the National Association of Manufacturers.
   He and other witnesses complained about Japan's distribution
system under which firms purchase parts and supplies almost
exclusively from long-term business partners and companies either
make their own supplies or keep tight reins over their suppliers.
   But Morris, who just returned from a monthlong trip to Japan,
added: ``We should not kid ourselves. We cannot expect real help
from the Japanese in reducing their surplus or our deficit unless
we in the United States can demonstrate the very great importance
we attach to constructive change in this area.''
   Mitchell E. Kertzman, speaking for the American Electronics
Association, said, ``We believe the imbalance in commercial
relations between the U.S. and Japan will destroy the international
trading system unless it is effectively addressed.''
   He said U.S. electronics exports to Japan are only $6.3 billion
per year, compared with $26.8 billion of U.S. electronics imports
from Japan.
   He also said there must be changes in this country.
   ``Frankly, it is our hope that our Japanese friends will press
the U.S. government to deal with its own economic problems that
impact the bilateral trading relationship. High among these
problems is the high cost of capital driven by our enormous budget
deficit and our tax system which favors consumption over savings
and investment,'' he added.
   A harder line was taken by Texas oilman and sometime corporate
raider T. Boone Pickens, who called corporate Japan ``a closed
shop.''
   He said the ``most damaging'' structural barrier to free trade
was Japan's ``cartel-like system of interlocking corporate
ownership.''
   Because of that, Pickens claimed, ``a relatively small group of
insiders dictate corporate policy.
   He said his own problem with Koito Manufacturing Co., a Japanese
auto headlight maker, ``is symbolic of the current trade relations
between the United States and Japan.''
   Pickens, known for his often hostile raids on U.S. companies,
has been battling with the management of Koito for representation
on its board. But he has been rebuffed despite his 26 percent stake
in the company.
   ``The entire system of Japan is geared toward the denial of a
meaningful flow of information to shareholders,'' said Pickens.
   Nearly all the day's speakers supported the continuing
structural impediment initiative talks between U.S. and Japanese
representatives.
   The talks, first held Sept. 4 and 5 in Tokyo, are an outgrowth
of a White House decision in May that found Japan, India and Brazil
responsible for restrictive trade and investment practices under
U.S. trade law.
   At the same time, the United States and Japan agreed to discuss
a number of ``structural impediments'' outside the procedures and
timetables of U.S. trade laws.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
