<FIRST>u f PM-SFQuake-Mall Bjt   11-07 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Mall, Bjt,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Enterprise Alive After Quake; Merchants Move to Tents</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SCZ1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last month's deadly earthquake ripped
the economic heart out of this community by ravaging the Pacific
Garden Mall, but merchants hope to salvage the Christmas shopping
season by moving to tents.
   ``I know that if I'm not open the day after Thanksgiving, I'm
bankrupt,'' mall businesswoman Margaret Wilson told the City
Council last week.
   Hardest hit in this quaint, seaside town 60 miles south of San
Francisco was the mall, a typically eclectic California collection
of about 250 shops.
   They sold everything from rare books to imported coffee beans to
beads as well as many necessities in turn-of-the-century buildings
linked by open-air walkways along a tree-lined street.
   Three people were killed in the mall and several dozen of its
buildings crumpled by the Oct. 17 quake, which registered 7.1 on
the Richter scale, killed 66 people in Northern California and did
$7 billion in damage.
   On Monday, Gov. George Deukmejian signed a temporary
quarter-cent sales tax increase into law to raise a projected $800
million for earthquake relief.
   The hike, which takes effect Dec. 1 and lasts through 1990, adds
to a statewide sales tax of 6 cents on the dollar, higher in some
areas because of local levies.
   The tax rise was part of a package of quake relief legislation,
enacted in a special session of the Legislature, that includes $200
million in assistance from state reserve funds and $150 million in
tax relief.
   Now that they've gotten over the shock of the quake, many Santa
Cruz merchants have put aside competition and banded together.
   With a lot of work and a little luck, they say those hardest hit
by the quake will be able to come up with enough money to lease the
tents and reopen by Thanksgiving weekend.
   Ms. Wilson, owner of the variety store Lily Wong's, is among the
majority of mall merchants who have vowed to rebuild. Her store was
damaged, but can be repaired.
   ``My guess is, it's going to be a cliffhanger every single day
until (the mall itself) opens,'' Ms. Wilson told the City Council.
``But we can do it and it will be open and we will have a Christmas
downtown.''
   The council agreed to donate $20,000 toward rental of three huge
tents, with a total floor space of 20,000 square feet. It would
cost $314,000 to lease the tents for the year the merchants figure
they'll be displaced.
   City officials also are trying to identify other sites that
could be used as retail space, said Ann-Marie Mitroff, a city
spokeswoman.
   Among those is a Bank of America building and a former county
jail, said Ms. Mitroff. The neighboring city of Scotts Valley has
agreed to donate to the merchants a 5,000-square-foot portable
building, she said.
   ``It is crucial the businesses get back on their feet as soon as
possible,'' she said.
   The mall merchants collectively sell about $100 million worth of
merchandise annually and generate about $1 million a year in sales
tax revenue for the city, she said.
   As many as a fourth of the mall's businesses now face the
wrecking ball, if they haven't been torn down already, Ms. Mitroff
said.
</TEXT>
