<FIRST>r f BC-Pickens-Koito     11-07 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pickens-Koito,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Demands Increase in Koito Dividend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas-based oilman T. Boone Pickens is demanding
that Koito Manufacturing Co., in which he is the largest
shareholder, pay an increased dividend for the first half of fiscal
1989, Koito said Tuesday.
   In a letter received by Koito Monday, Pickens demanded that it
increase its dividend to 7 yen per share from the current 5 yen,
Koito spokesman Shinji Hagiwara said.
   He said Koito would notify Pickens of its decision after a
meeting of company executives on Nov. 21.
   Pickens, known for his often hostile raids on U.S. companies,
has been battling the management of Koito, a Japanese auto parts
maker, for representation on its board.
   He has complained that despite a 26 percent stake in the
company, he has been denied a seat on the board, although Toyota,
the Japanese car maker, has three seats with only 19 percent of the
company's stock.
   In his letter, Pickens said the extra dividend payment would not
go to the Azabu Motors Co. group, from which Pickens bought many of
his shares, Hagiwara said.
   He said Pickens' comments about Azabu were in response to an
earlier inquiry from Koito, which had been concerned that Pickens
would pay the extra dividend to Azabu.
   Koito believes the extra dividend demanded by Pickens is
intended to cover a 1.17 billion yen ($8.2 million) payment to
Koito by Azabu in fines for rapid trading in its stock, said
another Koito official, Mikio Tsuruta.
   ``Although Mr. Pickens said the money wouldn't go back to Azabu,
they are partners, and Azabu admitted that,'' he said. Pickens has
refused to comment on their partnership, he said.
   ``It doesn't seem very wise if our dividend will indirectly help
make up Azabu's loss, does it?'' Tsuruta said.
   The Finance Ministry earlier this year found that Azabu had
violated rules prohibiting rapid resale of shares and ordered it to
turn over the profits gained from its sale of Koito stock to the
company.
   Earlier this year Koito shareholders voted to deny Pickens a
seat on the board. Pickens said in Washington recently that his
difficulty in obtaining management rights in Koito ``is symbolic of
the current trade relations between the United States and Japan.''
   Pickens repeated his assertion that his purchase of Koito stock
was not intended for speculative purposes.
   ``We would never do anything to damage the company,'' said
Pickens, denying that he planned a so-called greenmail campaign, in
which a corporate raider buys a company's stock in hopes the
company will buy the shares back at a higher price.
</TEXT>
