<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CFTC-Monieson     11-07 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CFTC-Monieson,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>CFTC Accuses Former Merc Chief of Winking While Brokers `Robbed'
Customers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter is
among character witnesses scheduled to testify for a former Chicago
Mercantile Exchange chairman accused of failing to stop two
employees from bilking investors of thousands of dollars.
   Brian Monieson, head of GNP Commodities Inc. in Chicago, is the
focus of a hearing before a Commodity Futures Trading Commission
administrative law judge considering the regulatory agency's
allegations.
   Although the CFTC does not allege that Monieson himself engaged
in fraud, it contends in an 18-page complaint that from at least
January 1986 until May 1986, ``He did not act in good faith and-or
knowingly induced, directly or indirectly, the fraudulent trade
allocation by'' two GNP brokers.
   Monieson ``refused to see what everyone else could see, and that
was that his customers were being robbed,'' CFTC attorney Patricia
Donahue said in a statement Monday at the start of the seven-day
hearing. But Monieson's attorney, Jerrold Salzman, said the CFTC's
case is flawed, based on ``conjecture, speculation'' and unreliable
evidence.
   Salzman contends his client did not directly supervise the
workers named in the CFTC complaint _ Norman Furlett and Ira
Greenspon _ and he argued that Monieson ``believed in good faith''
that their customer dealings were honest.
   Furlett and Greenspon have since left the company. Their
attorney, James Koch, said the two ``never stole a dime, didn't
defraud any customers.''
   ``We're here today because the CFTC is on a runaway train on the
wrong track,'' he said in his opening statement.
   Monieson, 53, founded GNP in 1972, headed the Mercantile
Exchange from 1983 through 1985 and remained at GNP during that
time.
   Yeutter, who served as Merc president under Monieson, is
expected to make a statement on Monieson's behalf that will be read
into the record at the hearing before George Painter, a CFTC
administrative law judge.
   Yeutter has worked with Monieson ``and has known him for years
and he will offer his testimony as a U.S. citizen who feels very
strongly about something,'' a spokeswoman said.
   Others scheduled to testify for the defense include Robert
Wilmouth, president of the National Futures Association, who said
recently of Monieson, ``His moral character is above rproach.''
   The CFTC alleges that the brokers at GNP, described by Salzman
as a top clearing member of the Merc and Chicago Board of Trade,
engaged in ``allocated trades'' that defrauded customers of
thousands of dollars.
   The term refers to initiating futures contracts without the
required customer account numbers, then keeping profitable trades
for themselves while sticking customers with the losers.
   ``This is a particularly insidious fraud you have because a
customer can't win'' and doesn't know he's being bilked, Ms.
Donahue told the judge.
   According to the CFTC, Monieson was told several times between
June 1985 and May 1986 that the two brokers were engaging in
fraudulent activity. But he chose to ignore the warnings and did
nothing to stop the brokers' actions, Ms. Donahue said.
   The defense maintains that the allegations of fraud stem from
complaints by a disgruntled lower-rung employee who was fired from
GNP and vowed to seek revenge.
   If found guilty, the three defendants could be permanently
barred from trading and fined hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
