<DOCNO> AP891107-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 0923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CompaqComputers 1stLd-Writethru   11-07 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Compaq Computers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compaq Introduces Powerful Desktop Computer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, The Compaq ... with 2 grafs to UPDATE with NCR
announcement of new computer and Businessland deal; picks up 9th graf pvs,
IBM has ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With fanfare more typical of movie or amusement
park openings, Compaq Computer Corp. has introduced two computer
systems it says will revolutionize the industry.
   The Houston-based firm used indoor fireworks, laser lights and
booming synthesizer music Monday to announce Deskpro 486-25 _ a
system touted to be the world's most powerful desktop personal
computer _ and the Systempro personal computer system, said to be
another industry milestone.
   ``Our new product offers true general purpose flexibility ...
meaning it will not become obsolete,'' Compaq President Rod Canion
said.
   ``You could compare it to the IBM PS-2, Model 80, which is a
floor-standing unit,'' he said. ``But the Deskpro 486-25 has more
expansion capability even though it sits on a desk.''
   The Deskpro 486-25 uses an Intel Corp. 486 microprocessor as its
heart and has three times the computing speed of its predecessor,
which used a 386 chip.
   The Systempro, designed for network and multi-user situations,
functions with a high-speed drive array storage system in a tiny
area. It fits under a desk yet has the computing power of
minicomputers that require racks of equipment, according to Compaq.
   ``It's not just a higher horsepower engine, but a new way of
doing things,'' Canion said. ``What we're really doing today is
setting the wheels in motion toward a major fundamental change in
the computer industry.''
   The Compaq announcement came one day before rival computer maker
NCR Corp. unveiled its 486-based personal computer. Unlike Compaq's
Deskpro, however, NCR will use a system similar to the IBM Personal
System-2 line of personal computers.
   NCR also announced that its entire personal computer line would
be sold through Businessland Inc.'s 125 locations worldwide.
   IBM has not introduced a personal computer built on the 486 chip
yet, but it did come out with a card that lets users plug the 486
chip into their existing personal computers.
   The 486 chip is so powerful that it will allow personal
computers to do certain jobs now done by engineering work stations,
minicomputers and even mainframes.
   Compaq detected some minor problems with the chip last month and
informed Intel, which has said it would begin shipping a fixed
version of the chip by the end of this month.
   The uncertainty about the new chip, combined with slowing sales
in the American market, prompted Compaq last week to announce that
its fourth-quarter earnings would be below those of a year ago.
That announcement triggered a 15 percent plunge in the price of
Compaq stock.
   On Monday, however, Compaq's stock jumped 75 cents a share in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading, closing at $89.25.
   The new Deskpro 486 will be offered in three models, ranging in
price from $13,999 to $20,499 with first shipments expected at
Compaq dealers by late December or January.
   The Systempro, also in three versions, ranges from $15,999 to
$25,999, with shipments to begin in December.
   Compaq, founded in 1982, had worldwide sales last year of about
$2 billion.
   The company's phenomenal growth came as it made computers that
followed the IBM standard. Compaq, however, refused to follow IBM
in 1987 when IBM brought out its Personal System-2 line, using a
new data pathway known as Micro Channel.
   Compaq and eight other personal computer makers deny IBM's
assertion that Micro Channel is the way of the future and say they
have found a way to extend the life of the old data pathway, which
they call Extended Industry Standard Architecture, or EISA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
