<FIRST>d f BC-Kellogg-Psyllium     11-07 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kellogg-Psyllium,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cereal Leader Launches Fiber Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an advertising battle against a
rival cereal maker's health claims about oat bran, Kellogg Co. has
launched a $40-million campaign touting the cholesterol-cutting
powers of psyllium.
   Ads Monday in USA TODAY and U.S. News &amp; World Report, also
scheduled to run in Time and Newsweek magazines, show a red boxing
glove holding a stalk of psyllium grain. ``If you think oat bran is
tough, meet the new champ,'' the caption reads.
   Kellogg is taking a poke at General Mills Inc., which analysts
say has used an emphasis on oat bran to increase its cereal market
share to 27 percent from about 22 percent in the past year.
Kellogg's share has slipped to 38.6 percent from more than 40
percent.
   ``Anything that changes the emphasis from oats is in Kellogg's
best interest due to their under representation in the oat bran
category,'' said John McMillin, a food industry analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities in New York.
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration ordered both Kellogg and
General Mills in September to document the safety of psyllium, a
grain grown primarily in India. An FDA spokesman said the agency is
reviewing Kellogg's response.
   ``We're so confident that (psyllium) is safe that an ad like
this is just natural for us,'' Kellogg spokeswoman Celeste Clark
said. The ads are part of a $40-million campaign for the Heartwise
cereal introduced in August.
</TEXT>
