<HEAD>Sony Completes Columbia Pictures Buyout, Tender Offer for Guber-Peters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. said Tuesday it has completed its
$3.4 billion acquisition of Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc.,
the film and television production giant.
   The Japanese electronics and records company said its $200
million tender offer for the Hollywood production concern
Guber-Peters Entertainment Co. had also expired, and that about
99.5 percent of that company's shares were either tendered or
promised by the deadline.
   Sony reaffirmed that it intended to name the heads of
Guber-Peters, Peter Guber and Jon Peters, to top posts at Columbia
Pictures.
   Talks were said to be continuing between Sony and leaders of the
Warner Bros. studio over releasing the two producers whose credits
include ``Batman'' from an exclusive five-year contract to makes
moves at Warner.
   Sony completed its tender offer for Columbia stock last week,
and 99.3 percent of its stock was tendered under the $27 a share
offer.
   The second part of the merger was completed Monday, converting
the remaining Columbia shares into the right to receive $27 a share
in cash.
