<HEAD>Grain and Soybeans Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed in quiet
trading this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean futures were mixed and corn was steady at the opening,
with prices getting support from unexpectedly large export figures
from the U.S. Agriculture Department.
   Analysts say selling pressure could build because the
Agriculture Department's crop report, due Thursday, may show larger
than expected corn and soybean crops.
   Wheat prices opened slightly lower. There are reports the Soviet
Union may enter the market soon, which is giving some support to
wheat prices.
   As trading opened, wheat was 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.04\ a bushel; corn was
a { cent lower to a \ cent higher with December at $2.38 a bushel;
oats were } cent to 1{ cents lower with December at $1.42{ a
bushel; soybeans were a \ cent lower to a { cent higher with
November at $5.64 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were lower and pork futures mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .27 cent lower with December at
74.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .47 cent lower
with November at 82.60 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent to .05
cent lower with December at 47.72 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .75 cent to 1.43 cents higher with February at 60.37
cents a pound.
