<FIRST>d f BC-Earns-CentralNewspapers     11-07 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Central Newspapers,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Newspapers Reports Dip in Net Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central Newspapers Inc., which owns papers
in Indiana and Arizona, today blamed a 12 percent drop in
third-quarter income on tax rate adjustments.
   The newspaper chain founded by Vice President Dan Quayle's
grandfather reported after-tax earnings of $6.5 million during the
third quarter compared with $7.4 million during the same period a
year ago.
   Profit per share came to 24 cents, down from 28 cents during the
third quarter of 1988.
   CNI adjusted its 1989 effective tax rate to 38.9 percent from
35.9 percent to reflect expected timing differences resulting from
an investment in Ponderay Newsprint Co. CNI owns a 13.5 percent
interest in Ponderay.
   Company officers projected that fourth-quarter earnings would be
adversely affected by a $1.3 million pre-tax loss from the
operations of Ponderay Newsprint.
   CNI's third-quarter revenue was $100.8 million, up 2.3 percent
over the $98.5 million a year ago.
   The company also reported a 9.9 percent increase in operating
income to $10.9 million from $9.9 million last year.
   CNI reported revenue of $317.1 million for the first nine fiscal
months ended Sept. 24, up 3.5 percent from the $306.3 million
during the same period of 1988.
   Net income for the first three quarters was $26.3 million, up
15.1 percent over the $22.8 million a year ago. Income per share
was 99 cents compared with 86 cents the year before.
   CNI publishes eight newspapers in Indiana and Arizona, including
the Arizona Republic, The Phoenix Gazette, The Indianapolis Star
and The Indianapolis News.
   The company also publishes the Arizona Business Gazette and, in
Indiana, The Muncie Star, The Muncie Evening Press and The
Vincennes Sun-Commercial.
   CNI sold stock to the public for the first time in September.
   The stock offering had been approved over the summer by
shareholders as part of a recapitalization plan. The Eugene C.
Pulliam Trust, which has had voting control since 1965, permitted
the plan as long as it retained at least 53.77 percent voting power.
   Pulliam, the vice president's grandfather, was publisher of the
two Indianapolis papers. His son, Eugene S. Pulliam, Quayle's
uncle, is the current publisher.
</TEXT>
