<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
Tuesday in lethargic trading in Europe.
   Gold prices rose sharply.
   Dealers said dollar traders appeared to be marking time in the
absence of new reports on the state of the U.S. economy which could
provide some clues as about the Federal Reserve's next move on
credit policy.
   ``There's no news out, and technically, (the dollar's) not going
anywhere,'' said an economist at a U.S. bank in London.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 143.63 Japanese yen from
143.45 yen on Monday. Later in London, the dollar fell 143.45 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5810 from $1.5795 late
Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Monday, included: 1.8442 West German marks, down from 1.8517;
1.6175 Swiss francs, down from 1.6240; 6.2520 Frenchfrancs, down
from 6.2805; 2.0820 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0910; 1,349.00
Italian lire, down from 1,357.25; and 1.1705 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1712.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $384.50 a troy ounce, up
from $380.25 late Monday. In Zurich, gold rose to a closing bid of
$384.00 an ounce from $380.25 late Monday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.02 an ounce to close at
$381.57.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid of $5.26 a troy
ounce, up from $5.25 late Monday.
