<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Soars</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened Tuesday against all major
currencies, reflecting concern that U.S. interest rates are heading
lower.
   Gold prices, meanwhile, rose sharply here and abroad.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $386.20 a troy ounce, up $4.70 from Monday.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold at
$384.75 an ounce, up $4.50 from Monday.
   Currency traders said worries that the Federal Reserve might be
easing its credit policies, in the face of recent evidence showing
an economic slowdown, depressed the dollar's value but supported
gold prices.
   ``The dollar's upside position is very limited under that
scenario,'' said Ronald H. Holzer, chief dealer for Harris Trust &amp;
Co. in Chicago.
   He said traders were paying particular attention to the federal
funds rate, which is the interest on overnight loans between banks
and a rate over which the Fed has some control. Fed funds traded at
8{ percent late Tuesday, down from 8 11-16 percent late Monday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed up at 143.63 Japanese yen from 143.45 yen
Monday. It traded at 143.45 yen in London, and at 142.95 yen in New
York, down from 143.85 yen.
   The dollar was also weaker against the British pound. Sterling
rose to $1.5810 from $1.5795 in London late Monday, and to $1.5865
in New York from $1.5765 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday's
quotes, included: 1.8430 West German marks, down from 1.85325;
1.6165 Swiss francs, down from 1.6245; 6.2470 French francs, down
from 6.2820; 1,348.00 Italian lire, down from 1,356.50; and 1.17125
Canadian dollars, down from 1.17075.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Monday, included:
1.8442 West German marks, down from 1.8517; 1.6175 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6240; 6.2520 French francs, down from 6.2805; 2.0820
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0910; 1,349.00 Italian lire, down from
1,357.25; and 1.1705 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1712.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $384.50 an ounce, up from
$380.25 Monday. In Zurich, gold rose to $384.00 an ounce from
$380.25.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.02 an ounce to close at
$381.57.
   Silver prices rose. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery settled at $5.265 a troy ounce, up from $5.238
late Monday. Silver rose in London to $5.26 an ounce from $5.25.
</TEXT>
