<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mixed in Slow Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished mixed Tuesday in
quiet trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
closed down 8 cents at $20.02 a 42-gallon barrel. The January
contract ended at $19.79 a barrel, unchanged from Monday.
   Refined products traded on the exchange finished mixed.
   Analysts said the market focused on buying heating oil contracts
and selling gasoline futures.
   No. 2 heating oil for December delivery gained 0.17 cent to
59.83 cents a gallon, while wholesale unleaded gasoline for
December dropped 0.05 cent to 52.41 cents a gallon. Contracts for
later delivery were higher for both markets.
   The price changes marked a flip-flop from Monday, when heating
oil fell and gasoline rose.
   Peter Beutel, energy analyst for Elders Futures Inc., said
heating oil has gained consistently against gasoline in the last
months but reversed directions on Monday because of selling in
heating oil to gain profits.
   He said there were no outside factors moving the oil futures
markets Tuesday.
