<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0228,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Rally Amid Interest Rate Optimism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied Tuesday amid renewed
investor optimism that the Federal Reserve might move to lower
interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished 14.96 points
higher at 2,597.13 after a sharp loss on Monday.
   Wall Street observers said the Fed's addition of reserves to the
banking system through customer repurchase agreements sparked a
rise in the bond market that helped boost stock prices.
   Investors interpreted the Fed's action as evidence that the next
move could be an easing of the discount rate, said Michael Metz,
equities analyst with Oppenheimer &amp; Co. The discount rate is the
interest the central bank charges its member banks.
   ``Investors were in the mood to listen to favorable rumors and
seized on this as a rationalization to nibble a bit,'' said Metz,
adding that such an interest rate move by the Fed was unlikely.
   Investors hope for a decline in short-term interest rates to
revive sagging corporate profitability in the fourth quarter,
analysts said. On Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
47.34 points on what analysts said was a response to unexpectedly
weak third-quarter earnings reports and a bleak near-term outlook.
   The yield on long-term Treasury bonds fell sharply after the
Fed's move, reflecting bond investors' optimism about a rate cut.
The federal funds rate, the interest commercial banks charge each
other for overnight loans, also declined.
   ``We finally got the turn that we needed to stimulate the stock
market,'' said L. Crandall Hays, analyst with Robert W. Baird &amp; Co.
   Stock prices opened weak then seesawed through the morning
session following the previous day's losses.
   Analysts also attributed Tuesday's gains to bargain hunting and
technical factors after Monday's steep declines.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 11 to 9 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
813 issues up, 662 down and 496 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 163.00 million
shares, up from 135.48 million on Monday.
   Analysts said that program trading, a computerized form of
buying and selling large blocks of stocks, has remained a factor in
price movements but did not cause wide price swings in the last two
sessions.
   ``Program trading is there, but it's not gotten as volatile, as
whippy, as before,'' said Ralph Bloch, chief market analyst for the
investment firm Raymond, James &amp; Associates.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 191.458 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, stock markets overall rose by $14.420
billion, or 0.44 percent, in value from Monday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.97 to 185.74.
   Among the most actively traded issues on the NYSE, Tosco rose 7\
to 25[ on reports that several companies had expressed an interest
in buying the company or its refinery in northern California.
Philip Morris climbed [ to 40~; Chrysler gained [ to 20; and IBM
rose } to 97].
   Chemical Bank, meanwhile, lost [ to 31[; BankAmerica declined ]
to 27]; and Pinacle West lost ~ to 8.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 2.54 to 381.39, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index climbed 2.20 to 334.81.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market ended
1.38 higher at 449.40. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 368.51, down 0.17.
</TEXT>
