<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-07 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Prices Soar As Demand Outstrips Supply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar futures prices climbed sharply Tuesday on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange as demand continues to outstrip
supplies on the world market.
   On other markets, copper and precious metals futures surged,
pork and livestock futures gained, energy futures were mostly
higher and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Sugar futures settled .22 cent to .50 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in January at 14.40 cents a pound.
   The market continued to show concern over the availability of
Brazilian sugar despite the announcement Tuesday by government
officials that Brazil will honor 492,000 metric tons of export
contracts.
   Adding to the surge in prices was the sale of a large block of
sugar to Cuba, said Erik Dunlaevy, an analyst with Balfour Maclaine
Corp. in New York.
   He said the sale to Cuba, a sugar exporting country, was to help
that country fulfill supply contracts with China and Japan.
   ``The supply situation tightened up substantially overnight,''
Dunlaevy said, adding that market is living on a hand-to-mouth
basis.
   ``The market is set,'' he said. ``Whenever someone buys a large
amount of sugar, the market will go higher, then drift until the
next purchase, when the market will go up again.''
   Reports that miners at Codelco's Chile operations will vote to
strike this week sent copper prices up sharply on New York's
Commodity Exchange.
   Analyst Jim Steel of Refco Inc. in New York noted that the
market was ready for a price surge because of the steep decline in
copper prices in recent weeks. The falloff was due to the
settlement of strike last month in British Columbia.
   The problems at the Codelco mine are due to a restructuring of
management, which also is limiting the influence of the unions,
Steel said.
   December copper rallied to a session high of $1.1290 a pound
before profit taking pushed back to a close of $1.1115 for a gain
of 1.55 cents.
   Precious metals prices climbed on the Comex as the dollar
slumped.
   Gold settled $4.60 to $4.70 higher with November at $386.20 a
troy ounce; silver was 2.7 cents to 2.9 cents an ounce higher with
November at $5.265 a troy ounce.
   Frozen pork bellies were up the daily trading limit on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, with gains fueled by orders from
commission houses and short covering.
   The buying was supported by projections of firm fresh belly
prices. The surge in pork bellies prices spilled over to live hog
futures, which were also helped by strong cash prices at terminal
markets.
   Steady to higher prices at feed cattle sales help lift livestock
futures prices.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .18 cent higher with December at
74.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .15 cent higher
with November at 83.05 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent to .73
cent higher with December at 48.32 a pound; frozen pork bellies
were 1.53 cents to 2 cents higher with February at 61.55 cents a
pound.
   Oil futures prices finished mixed in quiet trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange, as the market focused on buying heating
oil contracts and selling gasoline futures.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 1 cent to 8 cents lower
with December at $20.02 a barrel; heating oil was .17 to .55 cents
higher with December at 59.83 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.05 cent lower to .40 cent higher with December at 52.41 cents a
gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed in modest trading
on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat settled } cent lower to 2} cents higher with December at
$4.05\ a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1 cent lower with December at
$2.38 a bushel; oats were \ cent to { cent lower with December at
$1.43{ a bushel; and soybeans were \ cent lower to 3{ cents higher
with November at $5.64\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
