<DOCNO> AP891107-0307 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SupermarketMerger     11-07 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Supermarket Merger,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Van de Kamp Allows Consolidation of American's Northern California
Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co., awaiting final word on
whether the merger of its Lucky and Alpha Beta markets violates
antitrust law, said Tuesday it had worked out a deal to sell 13 of
its 36 Alpha Beta stores in Northern California and merge the others
with Lucky operations.
   American and the state attorney general's office also agreed that
if the attorney general wins the antitrust case, any additional
divestitures by American in Northern California will be limited to
$1 million a week in sales.
   That could amount to as many as seven or eight more stores,
depending on how much business they do, Deputy Attorney General Chet
Horn said.
   Most of the 550 Lucky and Alpha Beta supermarkets are in Southern
California, and the divestiture of the 13 stores, combined with
earlier divestitures, essentially settles the anti-trust case in the
northern part of the state, Horn said.
   ``Clearly the bulk of the problem was in the south,'' Horn said.
   He said that in the Napa market area in Northern California,
American also agreed to open no new stores for three years. They
already have two stores there now, Horn said.
   State Attorney General John Van de Kamp contends that the $2.5
billion merger would cost shoppers $400 million a year, and has
taken his suit seeking to block it to the U.S. Supreme Court, which
has yet to rule on the case.
   In the meantime, a preliminary injunction issued by U.S. District
Judge David Kenyon in Los Angeles prevents American from going ahead
with the merger.
   American Stores, in a release from its headquarters in Salt Lake
City, said it had worked out a deal with Van de Kamp to allow the
sale of 13 stores in Contra Costa, Monterey, San Mateo, Santa Clara
and Alameda counties to other supermarket operators.
   The remaining stores north of Kern, San Luis Obispo and San
Bernardino counties will be integrated into Lucky operations.
</TEXT>
