<FIRST>r f AM-HughesAircraft     11-07 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hughes Aircraft,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hughes President to Step Down, Duties to Be Assumed by Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald H. White will retire as president and
chief operating officer of Hughes Aircraft Co. on Dec. 1 and will
not be replaced immediately, the company announced Tuesday.
   Malcolm R. Currie, Hughes chairman and chief executive since June
1988, said White's duties will be assumed by the executive committee.
   Hughes spokesman Ray Silvius said White, 58, will eventually be
replaced, but for now Currie will rely on the company's three
executive vice presidents.
   The company, a General Motors Corp. unit, is in the middle of a
six-month streamlining that includes the layoffs of 6,000, or 8
percent, of its 75,000 workers. The program is designed to prepare
for tighter federal defense budgets.
   White, a former Northrop Corp. and IBM executive, joined Hughes
in 1974 as vice president and controller and assumed his current
duties in 1983. He will ``pursue longstanding personal plans,''
Hughes said.
   During his time with the company, annual sales grew from $1
billion to $7 billion per year.
</TEXT>
