<FIRST>r f BC-NordamContract     11-07 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nordam Contract,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nordam, Pratt &amp; Whitney Get Contract for Noise-Reduction System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Technologies Corp. division and
Tulsa-based Nordam will make a noise-reduction system for Boeing
Co.'s 737-200 aircraft engines under a contract that ultimately
could be worth more than $2 billion, officials said Tuesday.
   Nordam's 1,200 employees manufacture bonded composite military
shelters, commercial aircraft interiors and noise suppression ``hush
kits'' for McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s DC-8 aircraft.
   Pratt &amp; Whitney, the United Technologies subsidiary, makes 90
percent of the engines that power the 1,000 737-200 aircraft used by
the nation's commercial airlines.
   The noise-reduction devices are expected to cost $2.5 million to
$3 million per engine.
   Nordam officials said a final design for the hush kits for Pratt
&amp; Whitney's JT8D engine will be selected in May 1990, with
certification expected by the FAA in late 1991.
   Pratt &amp; Whitney will be the program's technical director. Nordam
will hold the FAA's Supplemental Type Certificate and related parts
manufacturing authority for the system.
   Nordam will manufacture all parts of the hush kit except
modifications to the engine itself, which will be done by Pratt &amp;
Whitney, said Peggy Kay, a P&amp;W spokeswoman in Hartford, Conn.
   Nordam says it is the world's largest privately held,
FAA-approved repair station for bonded composite structures. The
19-year-old company had 1988 sales of $100 million.
   ``There may be several other (commercial noise suppression)
efforts out there, but we don't think they will be cost effective,''
Ms. Kay said. ``Nordam has shown us that their technical ability
certainly meets our needs and they have the manufacturing facilities
to produce these under our technical direction.''
</TEXT>
