<FILEID>AP-NR-11-07-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Commodore     11-07 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Commodore,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commodore Reports $6.5 Million Quarterly Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST CHESTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodore International Ltd. on Tuesday
reported a fiscal first-quarter loss of $6.5 million, which it
blamed on a decrease in demand for the company's computers.
   The loss for the quarter ended Sept. 30 translated into 20 cents
per share on sales of $165.3 million, compared with a profit of $9.6
million, or 30 cents a share, on sales of $200.2 million in the same
quarter a year ago.
   Irving Gould, chairman and chief executive, cited a drop in sales
of the C64 computer group. Despite the softer computer market,
demand for the company's Amiga 500 personal computers increased,
Commodore said.
   ``We are encouraged by the performance of the Amiga 500 and our
professional products,'' Gould said. ``For the current Christmas
quarter, we are aggressively increasing advertising and marketing to
help stimulate growth in all our markets worldwide.''
</TEXT>
